<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Drought-SpiderMites     08-09 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drought-Spider Mites,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Spider Mites Threaten Drought-Stressed Soybean Crops</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KALAMAZOO, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drought-weary farmers who are pinning
their hopes on soybeans now face another threat: tiny, hungry mites
that like dry weather and can go unnoticed while destroying crops.
   State agriculture officials say spider mites are invading
soybean fields in Michigan and other drought-plagued Midwest states.
   ``It's a difficult critter to fight because they're hard to see
with the naked eye,'' said Doug Landis, a field crops entomologist
at Michigan State University.
   ``When a crop looks bad, it's blamed on other things _ mostly
the drought. It's not until the problem becomes severe that the
mites are discovered,'' Landis said Monday.
   The mites, which thrive in dry, hot conditions, feed on the
underside of plant leaves by piercing plant cells and extracting
the sap, Landis said. After a few days, the leaves bear yellow
speckles and eventually turn brown or bronze.
   ``Entire fields can be completely lost if spider mites are not
controlled and weather conditions allow them to build up
populations,'' Landis said. The eight-legged pests are easily
carried on the wind from field to field.
   ``It's just another thing you've got to fight,'' said farmer
Larry Bennett of Fulton, who recently discovered mites in his
soybean field.
   The infestation is potentially another serious blow to farmers
who have lost much of their corn crop in the drought and were
hoping to cut their losses with soybeans, which are bringing in
higher prices.
   Because farmers in Ohio, Indiana, Iowa, Illinois and Minnesota
also are combating the mites, there has been a shortage of
pesticides to kill the pests, Landis said.
   ``We are running at capacity in an attempt to meet the
stepped-up demand,'' Dow Chemical Co. spokesman Sam Barrick said of
the production of one such pesticide, Lorsban 4 E. ``The demand has
been so great for the product we're just running out of product.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
