<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     08-09 0460</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0476</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On the Lite Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILLBURY, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A distaste for turning lambs into chops
has transformed a sewage treatment plant into a haven for sheep,
chickens, geese, rabbits and, as their keeper puts it, ``whatever
people throw over the fence.''
   The creatures live on the 107-acre spread of the Upper
Blackstone Water Pollution Abatement District amid tanks, pipes,
pools, pumps, an incinerator and plenty of grass for grazing.
   Emil Holland, plant director, recalls that in the spring of 1978
a farmer was allowed to leave two lambs there to fatten up on the
plant's grassy field.
   By the time the farmer returned in the fall, plant employees had
grown attached to the lambs and pleaded that they be spared their
fate as shish kebab. So, the sewage district board voted to buy the
sheep from the farmer. Soon, more creatures arrived unannounced,
apparently abandoned by their owners.
   ``We'd come in the morning and one day we had 12 geese,''
Holland said Monday. ``The next day we had 12 ducks, then four
chickens.''
   On Monday, the ``community,'' as Holland describes it, included
three sheep, two dozen geese, two dozen chickens and roosters _
``we get a lot of roosters'' _ and uncounted rabbits and pigeons.
   The animals drink from a fountain that carries clean water. They
also have the run of two huts, and staff at the sewage plant feed
them grain.
   Motorists stop every day to look, Holland said, and some leave
with a pet. ``We give them away to anybody who asks,'' Holland
said, ``as long as they're not going to eat them.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>AUGUSTA, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State officials wanted a big check from
Victor H. Bourre for back taxes, and that's what they got. Bourre
handed then a check measuring 7 inches by 14 inches, or more than
twice the standard size.
   ``It's a perfectly legitimate check,'' said Bourre, a Dover,
N.H., resident and a opponent of a Maine law that requires him to
pay Maine income taxes because he works at the Portsmouth Naval
Shipyard.
   The shipyard is on an island in the Piscataqua River between New
Hampshire and Maine and is connected by a bridge to Kittery, Maine.
   Maine state Treasurer Samuel Shapiro agreed that the check,
printed on thick brown paper, was legal tender.
   Shapiro's deputy, Maurice F. Stickney, deposited the $981.12
payment in a bank Monday afternoon.
   Bourre, 40, said Monday that a friend arranged for a printing
shop to blow up a check. He said he wanted to make it 4 feet by 8
feet, but ``that's the biggest I could get made up right away.''
   Bourre said he had withheld payment during a legal challenge by
shipyard workers. The U.S. Supreme Court refused to hear the case.
</TEXT>
