<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Statlers,0167</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wrigley Field Lights Prompt Statler Lyric Change</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Cub Lights, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Turning the lights on for the first
night game at Chicago's Wrigley Field is forcing country music's
Statlers quartet to change the lyrics of their 7-year-old song
``Don't Wait On Me.''
   The lyrics of the 1981 song contain the phrase, ``When the
lights go on at Wrigley Field, I'll be coming home to you.''
   Although the recording, from the album ``Years Ago,'' can't be
changed, the group will substitute the line with, ``When they put a
dome on Wrigley Field, I'll be coming home to you'' in performances.
   ``That ought to keep us ahead of them for a few years,'' The
Statlers' Don Reid said from his home in Staunton, Va.
   ``It never crossed our minds that one day they would put lights
in Wrigley Field,'' said Reid, a baseball buff who wrote the song
with his brother and fellow group member, Harold Reid.
</TEXT>
