<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Reagan     08-09 0456</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan,450</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Prods Congress To Move Faster On Welfare Reform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan says Congress has not moved
quickly enough on welfare reform and urban renewal, and he told the
nation's governors they've been ``way out front'' on many social
issues.
   Reagan, a former two-term governor of California, used a speech
to the governors Monday to tout his ``New Federalism'' policy of
shifting more responsibility for social programs away from the
federal government and onto the states.
   Many governors, especially Democrats, have complained that the
states cannot absorb increasing cuts in federal aid while
maintaining services for their citizens. During his speech at the
National Governors Association's meeting in Cincinnati, Reagan
described his effort as one giving states a ``leadership role.''
   ``We have broken the federal government of its compulsion to
control every breath the states take,'' he said.
   Reagan, facing a host of last-minute issues on Capitol Hill as
lawmakers draw near a recess for the Republican National
Convention, was playing host to Republican congressional leaders at
the White House today.
   In his Cincinnati speech, Reagan complained that Congress has
not acted on legislation he submitted six years ago, proposing that
the most depressed areas of America's cities receive tax breaks to
encourage business investment.
   ``Despite some minor moves last year, Congress still has failed
to pass meaningful enterprise zone legislation,'' he said. ``Not
you. Over half the states have gone forward with their own
enterprise zones.''
   Reagan also said the states have moved more quickly to get
people off welfare rolls.
   ``Welfare reform is another field in which you have been way out
front,'' he said. ``Congress today is still debating a welfare
reform package _ years after states started taking advantage of the
greater flexibility we gave them.''
   Reagan said the federal government should not ``merely let the
states toss ideas into a suggestion box,'' but that it should
``honor the leadership role the states have to play.''
   Reagan won compliments from Republican Gov. Thomas Kean of New
Jersey, who said the president ``was talking language we
understand.''
   But Democratic Gov. Bill Clinton of Arkansas said Reagan gave a
political speech designed mainly to help Vice President George Bush
in the presidential election.
   The governor's association has said it wants its meeting to be
non-partisan. Clinton said, ``I think it was as political as he
could be without stepping out of line.''
   Earlier, Reagan toured a U.S. Precision Lens Inc. plant, telling
managers and employees he resents talk about the ``Rust Belt'' in
the nation's Midwest.
   ``I get a little tired of hearing Cincinnati and other
Midwestern cities called the `Rust Belt' when the Midwest isn't the
`Rust Belt.' It's the `Boom Belt.'''
</TEXT>
