<1ST_LINE>r w PM-TurtleSoup     08-09 0515</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Turtle Soup,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Danish Film Rouses Friends of Turtle</HEAD>
<HEAD>By CARL HARTMAN</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Friends of the endangered sea turtle are upset
because a prize-winning Danish film, ``Babette's Feast,'' has
turtle soup on the menu.
   They are investigating a report from a Florida restaurant that
it got some sea turtle meat from San Francisco for use in a dinner
to promote the film.
   ``There's a gelatinous substance called calipee under the shell
of the sea turtle that's the basis for turtle soup,'' explained
Marydele Donnelly, director of the Sea Turtle Rescue Fund, in a
telephone interview Monday.
   ``Actually, the turtle you see beating its flippers in the film
seems to be a loggerhead, which is a different species that doesn't
have the calipee,'' she said. ``But both are on the endangered
species list and its illegal to catch them in this country.''
   The film is based on a short story by Danish writer Isak
Dinesen, pen name of the late Baroness Karen Blixen-Finecke, who
also wrote ``Out of Africa.''
   ``Babette's Feast'' tells of a Frenchwoman living on the coast
of Denmark who spends her lottery winnings on a big dinner for the
villagers who have befriended her in her long exile. The Motion
Picture Academy awarded it an Oscar as the best foreign film of the
year.
   Lawrence Lane-Zucker, who is helping promote the film for Orion
Classics, said its food consultant has worked up substitute recipes
using shitake mushrooms and chopped breast of duck. About 90
restaurants have been interested in reproducing the seven-course
meal, he said.
   Ms. Donnelly said some restaurants are using diamondback
terrapin, which is not a sea turtle but is found in estuaries and
considered endangered in some places. Ms. Donnelly says 10,000
terrapin a year are sold in New York fish markets and the New York
Turtle and Tortoise Society is trying to get it put on the state's
endangered list.
   Groceries sell a ``mock turtle soup,'' which she says is made
from land turtles. They are not on anyone's endangered list, but
she would prefer nobody ate turtle soup at all.
   ``Turtles in the Soup: Recipe for Disaster'' is the title of an
article written by Ms. Donnelly for the August issue of ``CEE
Report,'' published by the Center for Environmental Education.
   Meanwhile, sea turtles weren't faring well in Congress on
Monday, where the House approved legislation to bar the Reagan
administration temporarily from carrying out a plan to require
shrimp fishermen to use devices to protect the reptiles.
   Turtles often drown when snared in shrimp nets.
   The bill, sent to the Senate by voice vote, would prohibit the
mandatory use of so-called turtle excluder devices before Sept. 30,
a month after excluder-device regulations were slated to take
effect.
   The delay would give House and Senate negotiators time to work
out differences in their versions of legislation to reauthorize the
Endangered Species Act.
   Both bills would prohibit the required use of excluder devices
in inshore waters until May 1990. The Senate bill also would ban
device regulations for offshore waters until next May.
</TEXT>
