<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CubsLights 3rdLd-Writethru a0750 08-09 0871</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cubs Lights, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0750,0893</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Neighbors Love, Hate First Night Game at Wrigley Field</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE with game rained out, arrest
total. Picks up 7th graf pvs `I think...'</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX17</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELIZABETH SHOGREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Baseball after dark dawned Monday at Wrigley
Field, the last major-league ballpark with day-only games, but rain
put out the lights early.
   The first night game in the 74-year history of Wrigley Field,
between the Cubs and the Philadelphia Phillies, was delayed by a
downpour in the bottom of the fourth inning. It was officially
postponed two hours, 15 minutes later, wiping out the Cubs' 3-1
lead, since the game will have to be replayed.
   Philadelphia's Phil Bradley led off by hitting a home run into
the left-center field seats of Wrigley Field, which for 40 years
had been the sole major league ballpark to hold out against lights.
Chicago fans' mood brightened, however, after the home team came
back with a first inning homer by Ryne Sandberg.
   The Cubs, mired in fourth place in the National League East
Division, scored two more runs before thundershowers forced a delay.
   ``God is talking,'' said 26-year-old Jim Herrmann, who had just
fled the stadium. ``He doesn't want night games at Wrigley Field.''
   Authorities reported at least five arrests through the rain
delay, including three for ticket scapling and two vendor
violations, but few other problems, except for illegally parked
cars.
   Mayor Eugene Sawyer toured the surrounding Wrigleyville
neighborhood before entering the park and predicted that residents,
some of whom equate Cubs baseball with daylight, would get used to
night games.
   ``I think as we advance the whole plan and get people used to
night games I'm optimistic it will eventually smooth out,'' Sawyer
said.
   ``It's a historical moment, but it disturbs me because I don't
want people to use my gangway as a bathroom or throw bottles in my
alley,'' said Carmelo Flores, 32, a Wrigley Field neighbor painting
his fence Monday afternoon.
   ``We live here and the people in this neighborhood take care of
it. But some fans just don't respect the community,'' he said.
   Even President Reagan was struck by the history of the moment.
   Reagan, boarding Air Force One in Cincinnati on Monday, was
asked what he thought of the first night baseball game at Wrigley
Field.
   ``I'm too old-fashioned,'' said Reagan, who early in his radio
career did re-enactments of Cubs' games for stations in Iowa.
   ``There's nothing like daytime baseball. But I understand the
need for lights _ box office.''
   Chicago police scheduled 172 officers, including mounted police
and canine units, and revved up 15 tow trucks for illegally parked
cars. The normal phalanx for day games is about 50 police, said
Officer William Kernan.
   Permit parking is available only for residents of the
neighborhood of turn-of-the century, two- and three-flat apartments
that is becoming upscale from its working-class roots.
   Outside the park Monday, the excitement began early. Throngs of
fans _ some of whom had been there since 8 p.m. Sunday for the best
of the general admission bleacher seats _ lined the streets, while
T-shirt vendors hawked homemade wares. Some of the parking lot
operators near the park put up new prices, $15 in one case.
   Ivy-covered Wrigley Field held on to daytime-only baseball
decades longer than any other ballpark in the nation, joining the
fraternity of the illumined 40 years after the last team to light
up _ the Detroit Tigers.
   The Chicago City Council voted in February to lift the ban on
lights, and lights are scheduled to burn brightly in the North Side
stadium seven times this season and 18 times next season.
   The $5 million lighting system has already added a modern flare
to the blue and white Wrigley Field, which was built in 1914 to
house the Chicago Whales of the short-lived Federal League.
   There were more than a few attempts to pull the plug on lights
even before 91-year-old Cubs fan Harry Grossman could throw a
ceremonial switch to illuminate the field for the first time.
   The Tribune Co., announced soon after it bought the Chicago Cubs
in 1981 that it intended to put lights in the ballpark, saying
day-only baseball cost the company revenue from televised night
games.
   But Wrigleyville residents took on the media company and managed
to keep the ban on lights alive for almost seven years.
   Citizens United for Baseball in the Sunshine _ CUBS _
spearheaded efforts that included lobbying city and state
officials. The group decried problems with rowdy crowds, traffic
and parking it said would accompany night games.
   CUBS planned to monitor the neighborhood Monday for material to
use in a planned court action to limit night games, said Mike
Quigley, the group's vice president. Quigley refused to give
details of the court battle, but said it would begin Wednesday.
   The end of an era also brought out the entrepreneur in some
neighbors.
   ``My mom rented out our roof to some suburban rich people,''
Junior Cruz, 19, said Monday afternoon at his home across from the
ballpark. ``She's even got a gate around the top so if they get
drunk they won't fall off the side.''
</TEXT>
