<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-88 0124EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Kazantzakis     08-09 0783</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kazantzakis,0806</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Author of `Zorba' and `Last Temptation' Remains Popular in Greece</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KERIN HOPE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HERAKLION, Crete (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Novelist Nikos Kazantzakis, who created
joy of life with ``Zorba the Greek'' and a religious storm with
``The Last Temptation of Christ,'' remains popular in his native
land 30 years after his death.
   His novels sell thousands of copies every year, mainly in Greek
but also in English, French, German and Japanese. He is believed to
be the most-read writer in modern Greek.
   ``We have a huge turnover in the half-dozen major Kazantzakis
novels. ... In Greek he's mostly bought by young people, and then
the tourists pick up the foreign language copies,'' said Byron
Dokimakis. He owns a leading bookstore in Heraklion, capital of
Crete, the island where Kazantzakis was born.
   Dokimakis said the two most popular novels are ``Zorba,'' an
exuberant portrayal set on Crete of a man with a huge zest for
life, and ``Last Temptation,'' which presents Jesus as a weak,
unstable man who doubts his divinity and dreams of making love to
Mary Magdalene, the reformed sinner.
   Michael Cacoyannis' award-winning 1963 film version of ``Zorba
the Greek,'' starring Anthony Quinn, has become a classic. Martin
Scorsese's ``The Last Temptation of Christ,'' to be released
Friday, has provoked protest and outrage by Christian groups in the
United States.
   Such a reaction comes as no surprise in Greece. The Greek
Orthodox Church condemned the book as heretical when it was
published in 1954 and nearly excommunicated Kazantzakis.
   George Moustakis, a Greek theologian, said Kazantzakis escaped
excommunication ``only because the Cretans were so angry they
threatened to burn every church on the island if it went through.''
   ``There's still a puritan streak in American life that's bound
to be offended by the film,'' he added, ``and I'm sure that its
release in Greece will bring protests from the church.''
   The Vatican also blacklisted the novel in 1954. Italian director
Franco Zeffirelli said he would withdraw his ``Young Toscanini''
from the Venice Film Festival later this month if Scorsese's movie
was scheduled to be shown just before or after it.
   Kazantzakis acknowledged strong personal identification with the
tormented character of Christ he portrayed, but said the book was
an affirmation of faith.
   ``I am certain that every free man who reads this book, so
filled as it is with love, will more than ever before ... love
Christ,'' he wrote in the introduction.
   On Crete, the largest Greek island with a population of 550,000,
Kazantzakis is a hero symbolizing its tradition of radicalism and
defiant independence.
   He was born in 1883 into a farm family and studied in Athens and
Paris. As a young man, he spent six months in a Greek Orthodox
monastery on Mount Athos, but later embraced a range of
philosophies that included Marxism, Buddhism and nihilism, the
denial of all meaning in life.
   Kazantzakis turned to novels late in life after completing what
he called his life's work, the 33,000-line philosophical poem ``The
Odyssey: a Modern Sequel.'' He settled in Antibes in southern
France, but always had fistful of earth from Crete in his study.
   When he died in 1957, Kazantzakis was internationally acclaimed
but embittered by his failure to win the Nobel Prize for
literature. He blamed that on the Greek literary establishment.
   ``He was always an outsider who never got along with the other
literary personalities of his day like (George) Seferis,'' a Greek
poet who won the prize, said Katerina Angeliki-Rooke, a poet. Her
family knew Kazantzakis well.
   ``The establishment here still chooses to ignore him,'' she
said. ``There's been no serious intellectual study of his work in
Greece.''
   A Kazantzakis revival started seven years ago when Premier
Andreas Papandreou's new Socialist government made him required
reading in public high schools.
   Rose Kyriakakis, 15, of Heraklion said: ``I love his books, the
way he uses the language, the strange words and the great big
ideas. He's inspirational.''
   The Greek Orthodox Church keeps official silence on Kazantzakis,
but lay religious organizations still describe his work as
blasphemous.
   Many literary critics dismiss his philosophy as naive and his
dialect style as exaggerated and self-conscious.
   Kay Cicellis, a novelist, reflected a common view among Greek
writers: ``I find Kazantzakis hopelessly old-fashioned. His ideas
belong in the 19th century and he forces the Greek language into a
rigid, unpleasant mold,''
   Readers disagree, and enthusiasm for Kazantzakis surmounts
social and regional differences.
   Ms. Angeliki-Rooke said: ``He catches the popular imagination in
a way that no other modern Greek writer has done. In a Greek home
with only a few books, one of them will surely be a Kazantzakis.''
</TEXT>
