<1ST_LINE>r p PM-GeorgiaGOP     08-09 0669</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Georgia GOP,660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Robertson Vs. Bush Supporters From Georgia Take Battle To New
Orleans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA CASSATA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Georgia Republicans spent more than six
months feuding over control of the party, and at the end of a
four-hour hearing on seating the state's delegation at the national
convention, they wanted more time.
   The Georgia GOP, which was overrun earlier this year by
dissidents and supporters of television evangelist Pat Robertson,
has tried to regroup after local conventions dissolved into shoving
matches, bullhorns and allegations of death threats.
   Moments after the state committee's counsel completed his
summation, the attorney for the challengers asked for an additional
10 minutes to present evidence.
   John McDonald of Iowa, chairman of the Committee on Contests,
ruled that that the case was closed. But Brant Frost IV, chairman
of the dissident delegation, stood up and asked to speak as a
private citizen whose reputation had been brought into question.
   The hearing remained closed.
   The Republican Party has been asked to settle challenges to as
many as 39 of the 48 delegates from Georgia, where Republican
nominee-to-be George Bush won the Super Tuesday primary but backers
of Robertson have tried to take over the state party.
   The committee, which ended the hearing after hours of testimony,
videotape presentations and boxes of evidence, planned to rule
sometime later in closed-door session and will announce its
decision when it reports to the full Republican National Committee
on Wednesday.
   ``What we are engaged in here today is not a petty squabble,''
Georgia GOP Chairman John Stuckey Jr. told the committee.
   Stuckey said that this was the ``opening battle in a war for
control of the Republican Party'' by ``zealots'' and ``traditional
malcontents.''
   However, both Stuckey and Matthew Patton, the attorney for the
opposing side, said the dispute was more complicated than a
disagreement over presidential politics.
   ``The element of Robertson vs. Bush has been greatly exaggerated
by the news media,'' said Patton, ``and picked up by the
opposition.''
   In fact, any decision over seating a delegation from Georgia
will not affect how the state's presidential votes are cast next
week at the national convention, but it will determine who casts
them.
   Because Bush won the March 8 primary, all 48 Georgia delegates
are required to vote for him at the national convention, but the
delegates themselves are picked through a process of caucuses and
conventions. It is in that process where the dissidents made their
moves, showing up in sufficient numbers to dominate the caucuses
and obtaining a series of court orders to counter attempts by the
state party to thwart them.
   The feud led to fistfights and shoving matches at one
congressional district convention and to an aborted state
convention where dissidents with bullhorns controlled the floor,
shouting down speakers on the podium.
   ``Any reasonable person would concur in my opinion that I had to
adjourn the convention to prevent a riot,'' Stuckey said of his
decision to gavel a close to the May convention. ``There was a
clear and present danger of mayhem.''
   As evidence, the state party showed a nine-minute videotape that
was a montage of television news stories about the district and
state conventions. The tape did show shouting and fist shaking at
the state convention but it did not show any violence there.
   Stuckey said he had been under guard because of a death threat
he had received at his hotel room in Albany, Ga.
   The challengers responded with their own videotape of the state
convention, showing Stuckey gaveling the event to order. Later,
after motions to replace the chairman, Stuckey gaveled the
convention closed. The tape also showed the dissident delegates
locked out of the convention hall.
   The state party spent much of Monday laying out its case, while
Patton used much of the dissidents' time to cross-examine the
party's witnesses.
   Either side can appeal the RNC's decision to the Credentials
Committee of the national convention. The ultimate authority on
challenges is the national convention itself.
</TEXT>
