<1ST_LINE>r p PM-BushComplaint     08-09 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush Complaint,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Democratic Leaders Ask FEC to Investigate Bush Spending</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES HANNAH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The presidential campaign of Vice President
George Bush says a campaign-spending complaint filed with the
Federal Election Commission by four state Democratic Party chairmen
is ``ridiculous.''
   The four chairmen asked the FEC on Monday to investigate whether
the Bush campaign has violated ederal election law by exceeding
spending limits.
   ``We file this complaint today to formally raise the issues of
whether or not George Bush has mismanaged his campaign funds and
overspent the legal limit,'' said Richard Wiener of Michigan, one
of the filers and president of Association of State Democratic
Chairs.
   Mark Goodin, spokesman for the Bush campaign, called it a
``partisan challenge'' and said the campaign would welcome any
inquiry by the FEC.
   ``I think it's ridiculous,'' said Goodin. ``This campaign has
bent over backwards to comply with the letter and the spirit of the
law.''
   Wiener said that as of June 30, Bush had spent $22.1 million of
the $23.1 million he is allowed to spend for all pre-nomination
campaign activities. That, Wiener said, left Bush with only
$943,000 to spend from July 1 through Aug. 18, when he is expected
to receive the GOP nomination.
   Wiener said Bush has spent an average of about $1 million per
month since March and traveled extensively in July, going to 15
cities in 14 states.
   ``Frankly, we as state chairs wonder just how he is able to do
all of the traveling that he's doing and all the campaigning he's
doing in our states on that relatively limited amount of money,''
said Wiener. ``It appears to us that the Bush campaign is using a
variety of techniques to avoid the spending cap.''
   Wiener said those techniques may include delaying the reporting
of campaign expenditures, trying to take unlawful advantage of a
loophole by allocating to state party committees or the national
committee travel costs for so-called ``party building activities,''
and characterizing some trips as official business when they are
essentially campaign appearances.
   ``As state chairs, we believe that from our observation
violations have occurred,'' said Wiener.
   In their complaint, the four chairmen ask the FEC to conduct an
immediate investigation into whether and by how much Bush has
exceeded the spending limit, to issue an order to the Bush campaign
to stop spending federal funds, and to suspend payment of any
outstanding matching funds that still may be owed to the campaign.
   In addition to Wiener, the other chairmen filing the complaint
were James Ruvolo of Ohio, Frank Holleman of South Carolina and
Richard Lodge of Tennessee.
</TEXT>
