<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-88 0121EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Hungary-Military     08-09 0247</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hungary-Military,0255</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Alternative Service To Be Introduced Next Year</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist authorities say they will
next year introduce an alternative for those who refuse compulsory
18-month military service, making Hungary the second East bloc
country to offer the option.
   While general compulsory service would remain in effect, the
government newspaper Magyar Hirlap said Monday, ``in consideration
of Hungary's national and international interests, citizens are to
be given a choice ...''
   In June, Poland became the first Warsaw Pact country to
establish an alternative civilian service.
   Last week, a senior Communist Party official disclosed that 590
conscientious objectors have refused to serve under arms in Hungary
since 1977.
   Ferenc Szombathelyi, deputy head of department in the party's
Central Committee, said 40 to 45 young people have been jailed
annually for refusing to bear arms.
   ``This practice must be changed now,'' he told the party daily
Nepszabadsag.
   At present, people who refuse mandatory military service in
Hungary for reasons of conscience or religion are imprisoned for up
to five years.
   However, Jehovah's Witnesses, members of the Church of the
Nazarene and Seventh-Day Adventists are exempted from military
service.
   According to Magyar Hirlap, the alternative service ``is not to
be punitive in nature, nor more attractive than the armed service,
and carries no (material) advantages.''
   ``The substitutory civilian service, the introduction of which
will require amendments in the defense law, will be adjusted to the
18-month long regular (military) national service,'' the daily said
without elaboration.
</TEXT>
