<HEAD>`Cocktail' Stirs the Movie Crowd</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The love story-with-a-twist, ``Cocktail'' and
the animated antics of ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit'' gave Walt Disney
Co. a one-two lock on the weekend box office, pulling in $14
million in ticket sales nationwide.
   ``Cocktail,'' with Tom Cruise as a top-gun bartender who serves
up his trademark smile with a twist of lime, iced the competition
for a second week. It earned $8.2 million last weekend.
   The $5.8 million for ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit'' made it the
third Disney film this year to top $100 million in ticket sales.
The others were ``Three Men And A Baby'' and ``Good Morning,
Vietnam.''
   The Eddie Murphy comedy ``Coming to America,'' also topped the
$100 million mark.
   Another Disney film, ``The Rescue,'' and the horror remake ``The
Blob'' had soft openings but still made last weekend's top 10 list.
   ``Die Hard,'' the Bruce Willis action film about terrorism in a
skyscraper finished third with $5.7 million in sales, followed by
``Coming To America'' with $5 million.
   Next was the John Cleese caper comedy ``A Fish Called Wanda,''
which widened its fourth-week distribution to 616 screens and
earned $4.8 million for an average of $7,794 per screen.
   ``Midnight Run,'' with Robert DeNiro and Charles Grodin, earned
$3.7 million for sixth place, while the longtime summer hit ``Big''
was in seventh with $2.7 million.
   ``The Blob,'' a remake of the 1958 drive-in thriller featuring
an amorphous mass that grows as it feeds on human victims, did an
anemic $2.6 million for its opening weekend at eighth place.
   ``The Dead Pool,'' the latest ``Dirty Harry'' movie from
actor-director Clint Eastwood, earned $2.2 million for ninth place.
   At No. 10 was ``The Rescue,'' a teen-adventure about a group of
young Americans who attempt to save their military fathers from
imprisonment in North Korea.
   Here are the top films for the weekend as tallied by Exhibitor
Relations, with distributor, weekend gross, number of theater
screens, average per screen, total gross, number of weeks in
release and estimated production costs when available.
   1. ``Cocktail,'' Disney, $8.2 million, 1,437 screens, $5,709 per
screen, $27.4 million, two weeks, $21 million.
   2. ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit,'' Disney, $5.8 million, 1,435
screens, $4,108 per screen, $105.4 million, seven weeks, $40
million.
   3. ``Die Hard,'' 20th Century Fox, $5.7 million, 1,338 screens,
$4,289 per screen, $29.4 million, four weeks, $24 million.
   4. ``Coming To America,'' Paramount, $5 million, 1,786 screens,
$2,836 per screen, $100.4 million, six weeks, $20 million.
   5. ``A Fish Called Wanda,'' MGM-UA, $4.8 million, 616 screens,
$7,794 per screen, $8.5 million, four weeks, n-a.
   6. ``Midnight Run,'' Universal, $3.7 million, 1,146 screens,
$3,285 per screen, $20.8 million, three weeks, $20 million.
   7. ``Big,'' 20th Century Fox, $2.7 million, 1,272 screens,
$2,130 per screen, $85 million, 10 weeks, $15 million.
   8. ``The Blob,'' Tri-Star, $2.6 million, 1,081 screens, $2,446
per screen, $2.6 million, one week, n-a.
   9. ``The Dead Pool,'' Warner Bros., $2.2 million, 1,293 screens,
$1,705 per screen, $33.2 million, four weeks, $18 million.
