</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>House OKs Bill To Combat Illegal Ivory Imports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House has approved legislation to bring
the United States into line with an international agreement to
combat illegal trafficking in African elephant ivory.
   The measure sent to the Senate by voice vote on Monday would
prohibit imports into this country of any ivory taken in violation
of the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species.
   That worldwide agreement uses a system of quotas and ivory
markings in an effort to regulate the international trade in ivory
from African elephants, whose numbers have fallen to an estimated
700,000 from 1.5 million in 1979.
   The bill would ban importation of raw ivory from any nation
without a native elephant population and would prohibit exportation
of raw ivory from the United States.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Biggest US Show of Michelangelo Drawings Planned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The biggest show of drawings by Michelangelo
ever seen in the United States will open Oct. 9 at the National
Gallery of Art.
   The collection of 46 composition sketches under the title
``Michelangelo: Draftsman@Architect'' will include the artist's
graphic work, including several studies for the Sistine Chapel
ceiling in Rome.
   The ``architect'' portion of the show includes large wooden
models of the drum and dome of St. Peter's, prepared under
Michelangelo's supervision.
   This second part of the show is now on view at the Casa
Buonarroti in Florence, until Aug. 31. Other parts will be seen
here through Dec. 11 and then go to the Louvre in Paris.
   The show in the nation's capital is the only place the exhibit
will be seen in the United States.
