<2ND_LINE>PM-DeSillers,0492</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Orders DeSillers to Return Purchases Allegedly Made With
Donations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A luxury car, jewerly, clothes and other items
Maria DeSillers allegedly purchased with money donated for her
dying son's liver transplants must be returned today, a judge has
ruled.
   Dade Circuit Court Judge Francis Christie on Monday gave Ms.
DeSillers until 5 p.m. to turn over the property, which includes a
BMW automobile with cellular phone, more than $11,000 in jewelry
and a cemetery plot next to her son's grave.
   Christie also said Monday he will rule later this week on
whether to charge Ms. DeSillers with contempt for allegedly
withholding financial information from court-appointed curator
Karen Gievers.
   ``When is it all going to end?'' responded Ms. DeSillers, who
indicated she would appeal the ruling. ``I lost Ronnie. I lost it
all and they still want to keep on punching me.''
   Ms. DeSillers is accused of misusing some of nearly $689,000
donated for her 7-year-old son's three unsuccessful operations,
including $1,000 from President Reagan.
   The curator says the return of the items will aid the court's
efforts to account for the funds, even though Ms. DeSillers says
she bought the items with much of her own money.
   ``I'm really upset about what has happened, because I feel it is
unfair,'' Ms. DeSillers said. ``I feel the whole proceedings have
not focused on what the truth is, but is making up what they think
the truth is.''
   Ms. DeSillers' son, Ronnie, died in Pittsburgh's Children's
Hospital in April 1987 while awaiting his fourth liver transplant.
A $262,000 medical bill remains unpaid because Ms. DeSillers says
her son received inadequate medical care.
   Last month, Christie ruled Ms. DeSillers must give some of the
remaining $240,000 of the donations to groups helping needy and
sick children.
   A computer purchased by DeSillers was supposed to be used for
the now-defunct Ronnie DeSillers National Foundation. As head of
the foundation, Ms. DeSillers paid herself about $88,000 in salary
and other cash payments, Ms. Gievers said.
   She also gave a total of about $40,000 to her brother,
ex-husband, and ex-boyfriend, Ms. Gievers said.
   ``During this time, she did not work or have any other source of
income on her own,'' Ms. Gievers said. ``It was clear to me that
all the purchases ... were made with funds that were donated.''
   On Aug. 1, Fort Lauderdale police concluded Ms. DeSillers'
fingerprints do not match those found last year at an elementary
school where about $4,000 in donations for Ronnie was reported
stolen. Police would not say what information led them to request
her fingerprints.
   Leonard Robbins, an attorney for Ms. DeSillers, unsuccessfully
argued that she wanted to keep the cemetery plot so she could be
buried next to her son.
   ``That hurts the most,'' a teary-eyed Ms. DeSillers said after
the hearing. ``I don't care about anything else.''
</TEXT>
