<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0189</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Lower In Tokyo Morning Session</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar edged down against the Japanese yen
Tuesday, while share prices declined for the third consecutive
trading day.
   The dollar opened at 133.62 yen, down from Monday's 133.97 yen
close, and remained in a narrow range between 133.52-133.73 yen. It
finished Tuesday's trading at 133.58 yen, down 0.39 yen from Monday.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, a 109.06-point loser Monday, lost 82.76 points or
0.29 percent to close at 28,170.36. The index also finished lower
in Saturday's half-day session.
   Traders said most market participants were monitoring the U.S.
currency's movements against the West German mark. The dollar
reached 1.90 marks during Monday's trading, a level not seen since
January 1987.
   West Germany's Bundesbank intervened in the market sporadically
to keep the dollar from rising too sharply against the mark on
overseas markets.
   Dealers on the stock exchange said the market remained
relatively quiet because of the summer holidays.
   Volume on the first section was a light 650 million shares.
