<2ND_LINE>BC-Hamadi, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0502,0510</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Hamadi Admits To Being TWA Hijacker, Denies Killing U.S. Sailor</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 12 grafs to ADD Hamadi's middle name, that
admission made in prepared statement, crew members scheduled to
testify after recess. Picks up 12th graf pvs, `Hamadi was ...' ADDS
byline.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mohammed Ali Hamadi, on trial for
air piracy and murder in the 1985 TWA hijacking, on Tuesday
admitted he was one of the four hijackers but said it was not he
who killed the American sailor.
   Thirty-nine Americans were held captive for 17 days and U.S.
Navy diver Robert Stethem was killed during the ordeal, which ended
in Beirut.
   In the last court session before a summer recess, the Lebanese
Shiite Moslem defendant for the first time acknowledged publicly
that he was one of the four gunmen who commandeered the
Athens-to-Rome flight.
   ``If this act which I committed is against the law, then it is a
result of illegal conduct on the part of Israel,'' Hamadi, speaking
in Arabic, said through an interpreter. He made the admission while
reading from a prepared statement in the heavily guarded courtroom.
   Hamadi previously has denounced Israel for allegedly causing
problems in his native Lebanon, and has also condemned the United
States.
   While the United States and West Germany had said Hamadi was one
of the four, there previously had remained questions about a
precise identification from photographs taken at the scene.
   Hamadi told the court he took part in the hijacking in an
attempt to free Shiite Moslems held in Israeli prisons. Shortly
after the June 1985 hijacking ended, Israel released approximately
700 Shiites.
   While Hamadi admitted to being one of the hijackers, he denied
shooting Stethem and throwing on an airport runway in Beirut.
   ``The pistol was in his (alleged hijacker Hassan Iz-al-Din's)
hand,'' Hamadi said. ``I didn't use it. Our orders were not to harm
anyone, but I couldn't convince him not to shoot.''
   Stethem's parents, Richard and Patricia Stethem of Waldorf, Md.,
were sitting in the courtroom as Hamadi spoke.
   ``I took part in the hijacking,'' Hamadi said.
   The trial, which started in July, was to adjourn later Tuesday
until Sept. 6, when members of the crew of the TWA plane are
scheduled to begin testifying.
   Hamadi was arrested at Frankfurt airport on Jan. 13, 1987 when
customs officials found liquid explosives in his luggage.
   He has admitted in court to trying to smuggle explosives into
West Germany, a third charge raised against him.
   The West German government denied U.S. requests to extradite
Hamadi.
   Hamadi's older brother, Abbas, was convicted by a West German
court in April of masterminding the kidnapping of two West Germans
in Beirut in an attempt to force the West German government to free
Mohammed.
   Abbas was sentenced to 13 years in prison.
   One West German, Alfred Schmidt, was released in September 1987,
but the second, Rudolf Cordes, remains a hostage.
</TEXT>
