<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Missiles     08-09 0157</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Missiles,0159</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Missile Launchers and Transports Dismantled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet military, complying with the superpower
treaty banning medium-range missiles, has begun dismantling
transports and launchers for the weapons at a base in the Ukraine,
the Tass news agency reported.
   Tass said Monday that U.S. observers were on hand to look over
18 launchers to be destroyed during August. The first batch of four
missiles was blown up Aug. 1 at a test range in the Central Asian
republic of Kazakhstan.
   The superpowers signed the treaty banning medium-and-shorter
range missiles in December, the Soviets promising to destroy 1,752
missiles that have been deployed or are in storage. The missiles,
known as SS-20s in the West, have a range of 300 to 3,500 miles.
   The Tass account of the operation did not say how long it would
take to destroy the weapons, launchers and transports, or how long
the U.S. observers would stay in the Ukraine.
</TEXT>
