<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-88 0511EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PolkaFame     08-09 0528</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Polka Fame,0542</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cleveland Loves Its Polka</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DWIGHT WOODWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Move over rock 'n' roll and make room for the
polka.
   While Cleveland has been named as future site for the Rock 'n'
Roll Hall Of Fame and Museum, enthusiasts here, including Mayor
George Voinovich, are raising money for a polka hall of fame.
   Why Cleveland?
   ``The base is here, the music is here,'' said Tony Petkovsek,
chairman of the committee organizing the museum. ``Cleveland is the
polka capital of America.''
   Polka King Frankie Yankovic, who in 1986 became the first polka
artist to win a Grammy, lives here when he's not on tour with his
band. He is one of an estimated 80,000 Slovenians living in
Cleveland, more than anywhere else in the world outside Yugoslavia,
said Petkovsek.
   ``Polkas have sparked up a bit,'' Yankovic, 73, said last week
from his hotel in New Orleans where he was playing polkas for the
Fraternal Order of Eagles convention. ``Now disc jockeys are
playing it and teenagers are starting to try it. They can't really
dance it but they and jump around and have a good time.''
   The National Cleveland-Style Polka Hall of Fame will be in the
Euclid Civic Center. Petkovsek said it will document the evolution
of Slovenian folk music into Cleveland-style polka. Artifacts,
recordings, button box accordions and items honoring individuals
and bands will be on display, he said.
   There is already a Polka Hall of Fame and Museum in Chicago _
Yankovic was the first polka artist inducted there _ but the
Chicago museum's emphasis is on the Polish polka, said Yankovic,
who has been touring the country for 57 years, entertaining crowds
at county fairs, conventions and polka festivals.
   Petkovsek said Cleveland's reputation as the polka capital and
the emphasis on the Cleveland style are why the hall is being
established here.
   ``Slovenian is more middle-of-the-road. Polish has more brass,
more of a hop,'' Petovsek said. ``Bohemian has more brass, and
German is more oom pah pah _ they'll have tubas, baritones and
trumpets. Slovenians will have an accordian, sax, drum, bass and
perhaps a banjo and guitar.''
   Voinovich, a museum committee member, said he first danced the
polka as a boy and later, as a member of the Ohio House of
Representatives in 1967, introduced legislation designating
Cleveland as polka capital of the world.
   ``From a cultural, national standpoint, the polka has brought a
tremendous amount of enjoyment to millions of Americans,''
Voinovich said.
   Cleveland once had a weekly television show ``Polka Varieties.''
Petkovsek has been host of a daily polka radio hour for 27 years.
   In fact, Petkovsek has built his livelihood on a business
centered on the polka.
   Tony's Polka Village, where Petkovsek broadcasts his radio show,
sells records and tapes from what he describes as the largest
collection of polka music in the world. Petkovsek is partner in a
travel agency that conducts polka tours around the world.
   Petkovsek said he has taken up to 400 members of polka bands on
tours to Europe, South America and Australia. Band members bring
their instruments and play at taverns and listen to local polka
bands.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880809-0050 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-88 0513EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-NYCParkZoo     08-09 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-NYC Park Zoo,0477</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>New Central Park Zoo Opens Amid Fishfare</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY McSHANE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Looking for lions and tigers and other big
animals? Not in the new Central Park Zoo.
   The zoo, which officially opened amid much fanfare Monday,
instead has a more eclectic offering: the Golfodulcean Dart poison
frog, the tufted puffin, the plumbeous water redstart (that's a
bird, folks).
   ``It doesn't seem like a zoo to me. It doesn't have any
elephants or any giraffes,'' complained Daniella Alonzo, 10, one of
the first visitors to the $30 million renovation, who nevertheless
said the zoo was ``nice.''
   There are 450 animals from more than 100 species. Unlike the old
zoo, the new zoo has no large animals because of space.
   ``This is a mini-zoo, to show things likely to arouse people's
interest and a sense of caring,'' said Dr. William G. Conway,
general director of the New York Zoological Society, which runs the
zoo for the city Parks Department.
   A 4-block-long line snaked through the park within an hour of
the opening as the new attractions, housed in three different
``habitats,'' drew 13,701 first-day visitors. Most didn't share
Daniella's disappointment.
   ``These animals know how to act. They're not like people, who
have to learn how to act,'' said 11-year-old Patricia Benitez, who
toured the Tropic Zone habitat with classmates from her Manhattan
day camp.
   Monkeys, bats, fish and frogs were featured there; the Polar
Circle is home to polar bears, penguins and arctic foxes; the
Temperate Territory is home to otters, red pandas, turtles and sea
lions.
   Mayor Edward I. Koch cut the ribbon to officially open the new
zoo before playing straight man to a frisky sea lion named Finn.
   Finn, circling in the newly renovated sea lion tank in the
middle of the park, waved to Koch, waved to the visitors, caught
fish tossed by the mayor and barked on request.
   The renovation was supposed to cost $28 million, but came in at
about $30 million, partly because work took several months longer
than anticipated, Parks Commissioner Henry Stern said. Construction
began in April 1985.
   The commissioner was enthusiastic over the results. ``The other
zoo was like a Sing-Sing for animals,'' said Stern, referring to
the zoo that was shut down in the winter of 1983. ``So we've built
a humane zoo, a zoo for the 1990s.''
   There was one other new feature: visitors, who once toured for
free, now pay $1; senior citizens pay 50 cents, while kids come
through for a quarter.
   ``When I learned they were charging, I insisted the zoo has got
to cost less than an ice cream cone. If you can find an ice cream
cone for less, I'd like to see it,'' said Stern. ``Times have
changed.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
