<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Korea     08-09 0419</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Korea,0430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>North Korea Demands Urgent Talks On Olympics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   North Korea called today for urgent
parliamentary talks on its demand to co-host the Olympic Games and
rejected South Korea's proposal for preliminary negotiations.
   The communist North said it would agree to a meeting Aug. 17 to
handle logistical arrangements for inter-parliamentary talks on the
Olympics and a non-aggression pact. But it rejected a South Korean
call for detailed preliminary talks on working out an agenda for
full-scale negotiations.
   ``Time is too short to take the form of holding a preliminary
contact and then the full talks under the present condition where
40 days ... are left until the opening of the Olympic Games that
must be debated as an urgent agenda item,'' the letter said.
   The Olympic Games start Sept. 17 in Seoul and North Korea has
said it will boycott unless it can co-host the event.
   The letter from Yang Hyong Sop, chairman of the north's
rubberstamp Supreme People's Assembly, said the body wants the
first full meeting of both parliaments to be held in its capital of
Pyongyang.
   It was addressed to South Korean National Assembly speaker Kim
Chae-sun.
   The tough North Korean letter, delivered at the border truce
site of Panmunjom, said just three to five delegates from each side
should attend the Aug. 17 meeting rather than the 15-member
delegations proposed by Seoul.
   South Korea, which had tentatively accepted a North Korean call
last month for legislative talks on the Olympics and a
non-aggression pact, wants detailed preliminary talks to set an
agenda. It called for the preliminary negotiations this week.
   South Korean officials believe contacts with the north reduce
potential threats to the Olympics and they indicate privately the
hope of keeping Pyongyang talking until after the Games.
   North Korea, on the other hand, still hopes to force Seoul to
agree to co-hosting. If it cannot co-host the Games, observers say
the north needs an excuse and the failure of non-aggression talks
might enable it to blame the south.
   Most observers believe there is little chance of North Korea
dropping its co-hosting demand and taking part in the Olympics.
Such a change would represent a total turnabout after 40 years of
bitter rivalry for supremacy between the two sides.
   The north invaded the south in 1950 to start the Korean War and
the two sides technically remain at war since no peace treaty was
signed when an armistice halted fighting in 1953.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
