<1ST_LINE>r a PM-O'Hare-Problems     08-09 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-O'Hare-Problems,0584</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Safety Officials Call For More Controller Training for O'Hare
International</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The crowded skies above O'Hare International
Airport and basic errors by its air traffic controllers have
prompted federal aviation officials to scrutinize operations at the
world's second-busiest airport.
   The National Transportation Safety Board on Monday called for a
``back-to-basics'' training program for traffic controllers at
O'Hare to counter an unusually high number of controller errors.
   Federal Aviation Administration officials say they also plan a
broad review of operations at O'Hare.
   After a special investigation, the NTSB recommended that
controllers at O'Hare be provided with new and better equipment and
that the FAA find ways to increase controller staffing, reduce peak
traffic loads, improve training and develop better quality
assurance.
   The FAA declined to comment directly on the recommendations, but
said it plans its own review of O'Hare by a team of agency and
industry experts, with a report to be submitted to FAA
Administrator Allan McArtor by Sept. 20.
   FAA spokesman Fred Farrar said in Washington, D.C., the review
will go beyond air traffic control questions and will include an
examination of the airport's overall operation.
   More than 50 organizations have been invited to participate in
the review, including representatives from the airlines, pilots
union, various aviation organizations and the city of Chicago,
Farrar said.
   A spokesman for airline pilots said safety concerns aren't
unique to O'Hare.
   ``The thing to focus on is that we have overcrowded skies and an
insufficient number of controllers,'' said Capt. James Damron, a
spokesman for the Air Line Pilots Association in Chicago.
   ``We recognize the problems,'' he said. ``We are supportive and
optimistic about our collective ability to produce some
suggestions.''
   Damron blamed the troubles on the firing of striking air traffic
controllers by President Reagan in August 1981. Some have been
hired back, but not enough to keep up with the growing demand,
Damron said.
   ``There have not been enough applicants, and they have not been
able to produce enough controllers,'' Damron said.
   O'Hare Airport handles an average of nearly 2,200 takeoffs and
landings a day. Its 796,939 arrivals and departures last year, were
second only to Atlanta's Hartsfield International.
   Last year O'Hare handled more than 56 million passengers, more
than any other airport. But the airport has been the subject of
numerous investigations by the FAA, the NTSB and congressional
committees because of safety concerns.
   The latest NTSB investigation was prompted by reports in June
that controllers had committed 19 operational errors where aircraft
had been allowed to fly dangerously close to one another, seven
more than during all of 1987.
   After examining these incidents, NTSB investigators concluded
that in many cases controllers failed to follow procedures and in a
majority of the cases the errors involved a ``breakdown in basic
(air traffic control) skills.''
   The safety board said that in many cases the controllers'
performance was affected by ``excessive workload, lack of
attentiveness, forgetting, perceptual problems, fatigue, and
excessive time on position without a break.''
   The board said it was ``concerned that these controllers,
working at one of the nation's busiest terminal radar facilities
failed to act in accordance with basic controller standards and
principles,'' and it questioned the effectiveness of the FAA's
overall quality control program.
   The NTSB also said it was concerned about excessive overtime
among controllers, shortages of controllers and the need for better
equipment.
</TEXT>
