<1ST_LINE>r i PM-UN-Gulf 1stLd-Writethru a0425 08-09 0726</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-UN-Gulf, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0425,0741</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guns To Fall Silent; Security Council Meeting On Peacekeeping
Force</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With PM-UN-Gulf Peace, Bjt
^Eds: SUBs 2nd graf to remove reference to war being deadliest
conflict since World War II. LEAD prospects uncertain. Security
Council goes into open session at 11 a.m. EDT.
^By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As dawn breaks over the Persian Gulf on
Aug. 20, Iran and Iraq's guns are to fall silent after eight years
of war that have claimed the lives of up to 1 million people.
   Peace talks to end the deadly conflict will begin five days
later in Geneva.
   ``The restoration of peace will bring to the peoples of both
countries victories far greater than those of war,''
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar said Monday in announcing
the truce.
   The Security Council meets today to authorize a 350-man unarmed
U.N. peacekeeping force to monitor a cease-fire and troop
withdrawals.
   ``I have been assured by the two parties to the conflict that
they will observe this cease-fire in the context of the full
implementation of Resolution 598,'' the Security Council's
comprehensive peace plan, said Perez de Cuellar.
   ``The governments of the Islamic Republic of Iran and the
Republic of Iraq have also agreed to the deployment of United
Nations observers as of the time and date of the cease-fire.''
   Perez de Cuellar did not announce dates for a troop withdrawal,
prisoner exchange or other elements of the year-old U.N. peace plan.
   The populations and economies of both Iran and Iraq have been
exhausted by a war fought with modern weapons but with tactics that
harked back to the most brutal campaigns of World War I: set-piece
battles, trench warfare, mustard gas attacks, human wave assaults.
   Foreign Minister Ali Akbar Velayati of Iran told reporters on
Monday: ``I wish to declare my government is prepared to accept the
demand of the secretary-general and that of the entire world
community to refrain from any military action on land, sea and air,
starting today. ...
   ``Let me express my sincere hope that today's historic
announcement will be the first step in the implementation of all
provisions of Resolution 598, and the achievement of a just,
comprehensive and honorable setttlement, returning peace and
stability to all the region,'' he added.
   Ambassador Ismat Kittani of Iraq told reporters: ``Now we begin
the arduous but happy march that begins from here. I am sure it
will not be a smooth road, but it will be much more pleasant than
fighting and bloodshed.''
   The cease-fire agreement was announced after a weekend of
feverish negotiations in which Iraq gave up its demand for
face-to-face talks with Iran as a precondition to a truce.
   On July 18, Iran abandoned its longstanding insistence that Iraq
be branded the aggressor in the war as a first step toward peace,
ending a year-long stalemate in peace efforts.
   One provision of Resolution 598 will establish an impartial
commission to judge responsibility for the conflict, and Velayati
made it clear Iran hopes this commission will blame Iraq for
starting it.
   War broke out in September 1980 when Iraq invaded Iran after a
series of clashes along the Shatt-al-Arab waterway that separates
them. The waterway is Iraq's only outlet to the gulf.
   On Monday, the secretary-general's office released a report
saying the gulf peacekeeping mission may include a small naval
patrol for the waterway, the first time the United Nations has
planned to commission a fleet.
   The report estimates the cost of the unarmed peacekeeping force
at $74 million for the first six months, of which $47 million would
be start-up costs. The United Nations will assess its 159 members
for the cost of the mission.
   U.N. spokesman Francois Giuliani said Monday that about 25
nations would send officers to the force to be called the U.N.
Iran-Iraq Military Observer Group.
   He declined to name the countries, but said it was unlikely that
any of the permanent Security Council members _ the United States,
Soviet Union, Britain, France or China _ would send troops.
   If the cease-fire plan takes hold, as diplomats and observers
believe it will, it will be the United Nations' second major
peacekeeping success this year.
   In April, Pakistan and Afghanistan's pro-Moscow regime signed a
peace accord in Geneva for the withdrawal of more than 100,000
Soviet troops from Afghanistan.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
