<NOTE>Eds: Subs Hutchinson, Kan.-datelined item to CORRECT ``renown'' to
``renowned'' in 1st graf.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>HUTCHINSON, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gordon Parks, who rose from poverty in
Kansas to become the renowned photographer and author, is being
honored with the National Medal of Arts.
   Parks was to receive the honor from President and Mrs. Reagan at
a White House today.
   Parks, who was one of 15 children born to poor black farmers,
said growing up in Fort Scott helped propel him into motion
pictures and literature.
   He is probably best known for his novel and motion picture ``The
Learning Tree,'' which is based on his boyhood in Fort Scott.
   ``I had some rough and terrible times as a kid, but if I had to
go again I'd go the same way. Whatever I learned, whatever I
suffered there, has made me what I am,'' Parks said during an
interview with the Hutchinson News.
</TEXT>
