<1ST_LINE>d a PM-BRF--Drug-RingAccountant     08-09 0126</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Drug-Ring Accountant,0128</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drug-Ring Accountant Gets 30-Year Term For Money Laundering</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A smuggling ring accountant who laundered
drug money and funneled more than $50 million in illicit profits to
Colombia's Medellin cocaine cartel was sentenced to a 30-year
prison term.
   Jesus Anibal Zapata was sentenced in federal court Monday on two
counts of conspiracy, four counts of possession and distribution of
cocaine, three counts of unlawful interstate travel and two counts
of money laundering.
   U.S. District Court Judge Robert Takasugi threw out another
conviction on charges Zapata maintained a $10 million-plus
narcotics operation that would have mandated a life sentence.
   Alleged ring leader Pablo Emilion Escobar Gavaria has been
indicted in Los Angeles in the same case, but remains a fugitive.
</TEXT>
