<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel-Raid 4thLd-Writethru a0533 08-09 0536</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Raid, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0533,0549</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Israeli Warplanes Blast PLO Station, Guerrilla Base</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 5 grafs to clarify that guerrilla base and radio
station were attacked, say three people killed were guerrillas,
give duration of raid. Picks up 5th graf pvs ``The base is...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By AHMED MANTASH</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIDON, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli warplanes today blasted a
guerrilla base and a PLO-run radio station, knocking it off the
air. Police said at least three guerrillas were killed and 12
wounded in the attack near this southern port city.
   A police spokesman said six Israeli warplanes fired 26 missiles
in 14 attacks on a building housing offices and studios of the
Voice of Palestine radio and an adjacent guerrilla base southeast
of Sidon.
   He said the two-hour Israeli attack, the longest in Lebanon this
year, began at 10 a.m. The three people killed were at the
guerrilla base, police said.
   The police spokesman said most of the missiles hit the ground
floor of the radio station building.
   An Israeli army spokesman in Jerusalem confirmed the raid. He
said the station was used to broadcast instructions to Palestinians
in the Israeli-occupied territories, where unrest has claimed more
than 200 lives since December.
   ``The base in southeast Lebanon was a radio station used for
propaganda and incitement broadcasts, and to pass orders for
executing terror attacks,'' he said. He spoke on condition of
anonymity in keeping with military regulations.
   All the planes returned safely, he said.
   The police spokesman, who also spoke on condition of anonymity,
said: ``The ground floor, which is the only visible part of the VOP
building, was totally demolished by the first four missiles.
   ``It seems that the Israelis are trying also to demolish the
three underground floors of the radio.''
   Palls of thick black smoke billowed from the building and the
nearby base, about a half mile south of the Mieh Mieh Palestinian
refugee camp on Sidon's southeastern edge.
   Rescuers in a dozen ambulances and fire engines arrived at the
stricken building a half hour after the raid ended and dug into
VOP's three underground floors to rescue anyone who might be
trapped, the spokesman said.
   The radio station, according to the police spokesman, was
founded early in June and beamed special programs to the
Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   The Palestine Liberation Organization, in a statement blared by
loudspeaker vans, called for urgent blood donations at Mieh Mieh
and the nearby camp of Ein el-Hilweh.
   The police spokesman said the raiding jets fired scarlet
balloons to deflect heat-seeking, shoulder-held missiles fired by
Palestinian guerrillas.
   Witnesses in Sidon, 25 miles south of Beirut, said guerrilla
defenders firing their anti-aircraft guns missed the raiding jets.
   One witness, speaking on condition of anonymity, said motorists
deserted their vehicles and sought refuge in orange and banana
groves as the Israeli warplanes roared overhead.
   He said air raid sirens wailed in Sidon, the provincial capital
of south Lebanon, during the attack. Shopkeepers lowered their
shutters and several people deserted businesses and took cover in
basements and bomb shelters.
   It was the 12th Israeli air attack in Lebanon this year. By
police count, 62 people were killed and 81 wounded in the previous
11 raids.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
