<1ST_LINE>r a PM-IndustrialFire     08-09 0253</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Industrial Fire,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Firefighters Contain Magnesium Blaze at Industrial Plant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HENDERSON, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dozens of firefighters doused a magnesium
fire early today at a sprawling industrial plant near the site of a
deadly rocket fuel blast that shook this community three months
ago, authorities said.
   The fire at the Titanium Metals Corp. was reported at 1:50 a.m.
and was under control by 2:40 a.m.
   No injuries were reported in the fire that caused an estimated
$15,000 damage, dispatcher Melanie Dobosh said. The fire erupted
after two ingots of magnesium apparently were placed too close
together, but the exact cause of the blaze is still under
investigation, she said.
   ``The magnesium melted and got into water'' in a drain, Ms.
Dobosh said. The reaction of the magnesium and the water may have
caused some small explosions, she added.
   A Clark County fire official said 12 units were sent to the
plant. Also sent was a team that specializes in fires involving
hazardous materials.
   The plant covers several blocks, dates to World War II and is
located about 20 miles southeast of Las Vegas.
   Henderson residents are still cleaning up from the May 4
explosion at the Pacific Engineering and Production Co. plant, just
three miles from the Titanium facility.
   That explosion, which killed two people and injured 326,
occurred when a series of fires touched off an explosion of
ammonium perchlorate, a critical oxidizer used in rocket fuel for
the space shuttle and various military rockets.
</TEXT>
