<1ST_LINE>r i PM-SovietInspectors     08-09 0286</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet Inspectors,0298</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Inspect Belgian Nuclear Sites</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT J. WIELAARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twenty Soviet officials today inspected
a cruise missile base and repair shop under the superpower treaty
to remove medium-range nuclear missiles from Europe.
   The Soviet inspectors, led by Viacheslav S. Lyebedev, arrived
Monday at Abelag airport in Brussels on a Tupolev-134 of the Soviet
airline Aeroflot. They were welcomed by U.S. military and Belgian
officials.
   The Soviets, divided into two teams, were driven this morning to
Florennes air base, 40 miles south of Brussels, and a repair
factory in Gosselies, 10 miles north of the base.
   In Florennes, which houses the 485th U.S. Tactical Missile Wing,
the United States has deployed 20 cruise missiles since 1985,
including four spares. According to the latest figures, there were
55 missiles at the Gosselies repair plant, which belongs to Sabca,
a Belgian aviation company servicing U.S. cruise missiles.
   Under the treaty, the inspectors may spend up to 24 hours at
each site, with a possible eight-hour extension.
   The inspections are part of the Intermediate-range Nuclear
Forces treaty, under which the United States and the Soviet Uhion
are to destroy within three years all medium-range nuclear missiles
with ranges of between 300 and 3,400 miles. The treaty gives each
party on-site inspection rights for 13 years.
   Under a 1979 NATO agreement, 572 cruise and Pershing 2 missiles
were to be deployed in five European nations.
   Soviet inspectors have visited U.S. missile sites and related
installations in Britain, West Germany, the Netherlands and the
United States. Soviet inspectors have not yet viewed U.S. nuclear
missiles in Italy.
   U.S. inspectors have visited nuclear sites in the Soviet Union,
East Germany and Czechoslovakia.
</TEXT>
