<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-88 1025EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Sudan-Floods     08-09 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Sudan-Floods,0528</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sudan's Prime Minister Declares State of Emergency</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sudan's prime minister has declared a
nationwide state of emergency to cope with the country's worst
floods in 42 years, which have left more than 1 million Sudanese
homeless, Cairo newspapers said today.
   Sudan's capital, Khartoum, was almost completely paralyzed for
the third straight day from power and water supply cutoffs caused
by floods that followed torrential rains last week, the leading
state-owned Al-Ahram said.
   Prime Minister Sadek el-Mahdi announced on state television
Monday night that a six-month state of emergency was in effect to
help his government cope with the destruction.
   In Nairobi, Kenya, Ambassador Omer el-Sheikh of Sudan told The
Associated Press that millions of people have been stranded by
floods in eastern Sudan.
   El-Sheikh said more than 10,000 houses were destroyed in
Khartoum alone _ double the official figure given in the capital
Sunday _ and that he expected the number to increase.
   In London, a spokesman for the Foreign Office who spoke on
condition of anonymity said he had received reports of 11 dead,
some 100 injured and 1.5 million people left homeless. He said he
had no independent confirmation of the figures.
   Al-Ahram and Al-Gomhouria, another Egyptian state-owned
newspaper, said at least 11 people died, some electrocuted by
smashed power cables falling into flood waters.
   On Sunday, the Sudanese government declared Khartoum and three
other cities disaster areas and appealed for international help.
   The newspapers said that in Khartoum, the public transport
system collapsed, universities and schools were shut and some of
the capital's nearly 4 million inhabitants faced starvation after
bakeries closed and food supplies dwindled.
   The state-of-emergency decree enables the government to ban
strikes and demonstrations, make arrests without warrants, tap
private telephones and impose press censorship.
   A one-year state of emergency decreed in Sudan last year ended
only two weeks ago. It had been declared to deal with the effects
of the war against rebels in the south and the deteriorating
economy.
   Egypt responded to Sudan's appeal for help, sending 10 C-130
military transport planes carrying tents, medical supplies and food.
   In Brussels, Belgium, the European Economic Community said today
it had approved $712,000 in emergency aid. The money will provide
tents, blankets and other emergency equipment and will allow
doctors to fly to the African nation.
   Foreign Minister Hussein Abu-Saleh said that in addition to
Khartoum, the eastern cities of Kassala and Showak and the northern
city of el-Damer were declared disaster areas because of floods
triggered by continuous, heavy rainfall Thursday and Friday.
   He said entire villages had been isolated by flood waters.
   Finance Minister Omar Nour el-Dayem said in reports carried
Monday by Egypt's state-owned Middle East News Agency that about 1
million people were homeless after their houses were washed away.
   Sudan, along with most of central Africa, had been suffering
from several years of drought. A 5-year-old civil war in southern
Sudan has contributed to widespread famine since 1985, forcing
hundreds of thousands of people to trek north to Khartoum and
southeast into neighboring Ethiopia.
</TEXT>
