<1ST_LINE>r a PM-OrkinTrial     08-09 0316</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Orkin Trial,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Orkin Convicted of Federal Pesticide Violation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIRK BEVERIDGE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROANOKE, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An exterminating company has been convicted
of violating federal pesticide law for failing to monitor the
fumigation of a house in which two people later died.
   Atlanta-based Orkin Exterminating Co. Inc. could be fined up to
$500,000.
   At a brief hearing Monday, U.S. District Judge James C. Turk
convicted the company of one count of violating federal pesticide
law but agreed to throw out four other charges alleging Orkin had
improperly fumigated the Galax home of Hubert and Freida Watson on
Sept. 25, 1986.
   Orkin had faced fines totaling $1.7 million on all five counts.
Assistant U.S. Attorney Richard Pierce said the maximum fine in the
single conviction, $100,000, could be raised to $500,000 if it can
be proved that the pesticide killed the couple.
   Turk set sentencing for Sept. 6 and ordered a pre-sentencing
report.
   ``Basically what I'm interested in in a pre-sentencing report is
any previous conviction for this type of behavior and the financial
condition of the company,'' the judge said.
   Orkin attorney Sam Wilson declined comment on the ruling.
   An indictment returned by a federal grand jury this spring
alleged the company did not follow labeled instructions on the
pesticide, Vikane, and allowed the Watsons to move back into their
home before it had been thoroughly ventilated.
   Orkin also was accused of removing warning signs before the home
was aired out and failing to test the home with appropriate
monitoring equipment to make sure it was safe.
   Watson, 73, died three days after the fumigation. Mrs. Watson,
65, died four days after her husband.
   Orkin and Dow Chemical Co., the marketer of Vikane, also are
named in a $2.5 million federal lawsuit filed by Signet Trust Co.
on behalf of Mrs. Watson's estate. The wrongful death suit is
pending, court officials said.
</TEXT>
