<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Irish 1stLd-Writethru   08-09 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Irish, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0486,0498</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gun Attacks, Other Violence Marks Internment Anniversary</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with eight police injured, 42
arrests, 80 attacks, clashes outside Belfast, other details. EDITS
to tighten. No pickup.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gunmen fired on security forces
before dawn today as gangs of IRA supporters took to the streets to
mark 17 years since authorities began jailing guerrilla suspects
without trial.
   Eight police officers were injured, none seriously, and 42
people were arrested, according to the Royal Ulster Constabulary,
the province's police force. Four injured civilians were still
hospitalized today but the exact number treated and released was
not known.
   Police said the gangs launched about 80 attacks on security
forces Monday night and early today in a constant barrage of
bullets, bombs, rocks and other missiles. Protesters hijacked cars,
erected barricades across streets and lighted dozens of bonfires.
   Security forces fired plastic bullets to break up the rioters,
including a crowd of several hundred throwing gasoline bombs at
police outside a bus station. On at least one occasion, police
opened fire with live ammunition.
   The violence was concentrated in the predominantly Catholic
western and northern areas of Belfast.
   Outside Belfast, there was less trouble although clashes were
reported in County Armagh and County Down. In Downpatrick, County
Down, a primary school was damaged by fire and there were three
arrests. In Antrim, two houses were set on fire, police siad.
   Britain abandoned internment in December 1975 after worldwide
criticism, but IRA supporters continue each year to mark the
anniversary of its introduction on Aug. 9, 1971.
   In separate attacks, shots were reported fired at a police
patrol and at a police station and a grenade was thrown at an army
barracks.
   A stolen car crashed through a security checkpoint, knocking
down a policeman, who was not seriously hurt. Security forces fired
at the fleeing car, which escaped.
   The violence followed the deaths of two Roman Catholics in
Belfast Monday in a suspected revenge slaying by Protestants for a
new spate of Irish Republican Army attacks.
   In the attack, gunmen firing from a car fatally shot a youth and
a beer deliveryman, both Catholics. The gunmen escaped and
abandoned their car in a Protestant district about two miles away,
police said.
   Police sources and moderate Catholic leaders blamed the attack
on Protestant extremists taking revenge for a series of IRA
bombings and shootings in Northern Ireland, Britain and West
Germany that left six dead and 37 injured last week.
   Police sources said the Ulster Volunteer Force, an outlawed
guerrilla group, is believed responsible. It was the first
Protestant extremist attack in more than a month.
   The killings took place as police chiefs and Protestant
political leaders met to try to devise new security measures
against the outlawed IRA.
   The mainly Catholic IRA wants to unite the predominantly
Protestant province with the Republic of Ireland.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
