<HEAD>Thunderstorms Rip Though Central United States</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 18 grafs to UPDATE with lightning death, new info
on Tropical Storm Beryl, picking up 12th graf pvs, `Today's
forecast ....'
^By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Fierce thunderstorms ranged from Michigan to Kansas today after
much of the central United States was belted by storms bringing
large hail, drenching rains and winds that blew out windows and
leveled trees and power poles.
   Lightning killed a teen-age girl and critically injured her
friend at a Racine, Wis., park.
   In the South, Tropical Storm Beryl moved across New Orleans
today, prompting the National Weather Service to alert 16 coastal
parishes for possibly heavy rains.
   Strong storms ripped through northeast Kansas and northern
Missouri early today but the intensity of many storms began to fade
in early morning.
   In southern Wisconsin, high winds toppled trees across Highway
24 at Muskego, while in Vernon, winds gusted to 60 mph. Streets in
Lake Geneva were flooded by the torrential rain, and at least one
funnel cloud was sighted.
   Strong thunderstorm winds also scattered trees at Roscoe and
Rockton, Ill., as well as in Plainview, Donahue and Walcott, Iowa.
Power poles fell in high winds at West Liberty, Iowa.
   In Kansas City, Mo., strong winds brought down trees and blew
out windows.
   Hershey, Neb., was blasted by winds up to 60 mph and hail the
size of golf balls.
   The storms also brought a deluge of rain. More than 2 inches
fell at Kearney, Mo., and Madrid, Kan.
   In Chicago, rain forced officials to cut short the Cubs' first
night baseball game at Wrigley Field.
   ``This is typical,'' said one disgruntled fan. ``It doesn't rain
all summer long, and then on the first night game ever, it has to
rain.''
   In Racine, witnesses told police that a lightning bolt hit a
tree at Lincoln Park, then apparently traveled through the ground
and struck the two girls Monday afternoon.
   Karla Kay Hedding, 17, died immediately, said Thomas Cloyd,
assistant Racine County medical examiner. Her friend, who was not
identified, was listed in critical condition at Milwaukee County
Medical Complex.
   As Beryl, the Atlantic hurricane season's second named storm,
moved over New Orleans, forecasters said its movement raised hopes
that it might dissipate.
   Earlier, several coastal communities were evacuated as the
storm, which has already forced thousands of oil workers from their
offshore rigs, intensified off the Louisiana-Mississippi Gulf Coast.
   At 8 a.m. EDT today, the Beryl's center was just northwest of
New Orleans at latitude 30.2 north and longitude 90.3 west. Highest
sustained winds were 50 mph.
   Warnings were in effect from Morgan City, La., to Pensacola, Fla.
   Thunderstorms spawned by Beryl poured heavy rain along the Gulf
Coast from southeast Louisiana to Mobile, Ala. Biloxi, Miss.,
received more than 3 inches of rain early today.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms from
Florida and southern Georgia across southern Louisiana; numerous
thunderstorms from northwest Florida to western Louisiana from
Tropical Storm Beryl; scattered showers and thunderstorms through
lower Michigan, southeast Wisconsin, northern Indiana, Illinois,
much of Missouri, Kansas, northern Vermont to northern Maine; and
fair weather throughout the rest of the nation.
   High temperatures were forecast in the 70s over Upper Michigan,
northwest Washington and parts of the California coast; in the 90s
or higher from southern New England to Florida, from the Ohio
Valley across to the central Gulf of Mexico coast, over the lower
half of the Mississippi Valley, through eastern Montana, through
the central Pacific coast and the Great Basin, between 100 degrees
and 105 degrees over Oklahoma, central Texas and across the desert
Southwest; in the 80s through the rest of the nation.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 44
degrees at Yellowstone National Park, Wyo., to 92 degrees at
Phoenix, Ariz..
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 77 partly cloudy; Boston 74 fair; Buffalo 70
fair; Charleston, S.C. 76 partly cloudy; Cincinnati 68 fair;
Cleveland 69 fair; Detroit 77 cloudy; Miami 77 partly cloudy; New
York -- foggy; Philadelphia 72 fair; Pittsburgh 65 fair; Portland,
Maine 68 fair; Washington 72 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 51 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth 87 fair; Denver 63
fair; Des Moines 72 partly cloudy; Indianapolis 73 hazy; Kansas
City 75 cloudy; Minneapolis-St. Paul 66 fair; Nashville 75 fair;
New Orleans 75 showers; St. Louis 84 partly cloudy.
   _West: Albuquerque 67 fair; Anchorage 59 partly cloudy; Las
Vegas 78 fair; Los Angeles 63 partly cloudy; Phoenix 89 fair; Salt
Lake City 61 fair; San Diego 66 fair; San Francisco 54 fair;
Seattle 63 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 77 cloudy; Toronto 73 fair.
</TEXT>
