<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BeachWaste     08-09 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Beach Waste,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Medical Debris Found On North Carolina Beaches</HEAD>
<DATELINE>INDIAN BEACH, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Medical debris like that plaguing
beaches in the Northeast has been found on a North Carolina beach
and police were investigating reports that more material washed up
today, police said.
   No beaches were closed.
   Used syringes and vials such as those used in blood tests were
found in a plastic trash bag that washed up Monday night at Indian
Beach, Indian Beach Police Chief John Stevens said today.
   ``It has blood vials, testing vials, and some used syringes in
it and other medical debris,'' Stevens said. ``I did not detect any
blood. I opened the top of the sack up to see what was in it. There
were no blood samples or anything .... I didn't see any needles. It
appeared the needles had been cut off.''
   Stevens said he was awaiting direction from Tom Hinton,
emergency management coordinator for Carteret County, about
possibly closing beaches.
   ``We don't foresee any problems at this time ...,'' Stevens said.
   Numerous beaches have been closed for varying periods this
summer along the coasts of New Jersey, New York's Long Island and
Connecticut because of medical waste and sewage.
   Because of the high tide, Stevens said he and the police chief
of nearby Pine Knoll Shores were unable to get onto the beach to
look at other materials found today.
   ``All we know is there's some stuff washed up and we don't know
what it contains,'' Stevens said.
   The discoveries are the latest in a series of reports of medical
debris found along North Carolina beaches in recent days.
</TEXT>
