<1ST_LINE>u a PM-CubsLights 2ndLd-Writethru a0581 08-09 0793</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Cubs Lights, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0581,0814</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Baseball After Dark Dawns At Wrigley Field; But Rain Puts Out The
Lights</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 3rd graf, `Three hours ...,' to CORRECT that rain delay
began two hours, NOT three hours, after lights went on. A version
moved on sports wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM C. HIDLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The bright lights of night baseball illuminated
Wrigley Field for the first time in 74 years, but the historic game
was cut short when the rain came and lightning bolts lit up the sky.
   ``I feel like we saw the beginning of history being made, but we
didn't get to see the end,'' lawyer Donald Kurasch said Monday
night, as the heavy rain halted the game in the bottom of the
fourth inning with the Chicago Cubs leading the Philadelphia
Phillies, 3-1.
   Two hours after 91-year-old Cubs fan Harry Grossman declared
``Let there be light!'' and threw the switch that turned on the
towering Wrigley Field lights, the clouds took over.
   The game at the last major-league ballpark with day-only games
was postponed two hours and 10 minutes later, delaying Wrigley's
first official night game until tonight's contest between the Cubs
and the New York Mets.
   Monday's rain was seen as symptomatic of the Cubs' seemingly
endless disappointments to its fans, like when the team blew
potential championships in 1984 and 1969.
   ``It's kind of like the fates are against them,'' said Mike
Quigley, a neighborhood activist who led the fight against night
games.
   Some made out anyway. Scalpers got up to $250 for tickets.
Rooftops with views of the field were rented out for as much as
$1,000.
   Fans with tickets to Monday night's game can exchange them for
any game for which tickets are available or get refunds, the Cubs
said. They won't be able to attend tonight's game; it's sold out.
   The day began with boundless optimism for Cubs fans.
   Throngs filled the Wrigleyville neighborhood early, many
chugging beer. An army of vendors hawked commemorative T-shirts for
up to $15 a piece.
   ``I think it's beautiful,'' said Paula Torres, 62 as she sat on
the stoop across from Wrigley's main entrance in 99-degree heat.
``It seems like everybody's in a good mood despite the heat. I
haven't seen a crabby face yet.''
   Some residents prepared for the worst, organizing patrols
against drunkeness and vandalism.
   ``I never minded the day games because it's daylight and you can
see what the people are doing, but I mind the night games,'' said
Shirley Habbe, 56, who has lived less than a block from Wrigley's
main entrance for 20 years.
   As daylight faded, parts of the neighborhood began resembling a
party.
   On the roof of one apartment building across from Wrigley's
right-field wall, 45 peopled attended a catered party where the
women wore cocktail dresses and the men black ties, tuxedo tops and
Hawaiian shorts.
   About 250 people, many clutching beer cans, gathered behind the
left-field wall to watch the lights being turned on and try to
catch a home run ball.
   In their midst, stood Randy Murphy, who drove 300 miles to
Chicago from Lovington in central Illinois, even though he was not
among the sellout crowd of 39,000 with tickets.
   ``We just couldn't pass this up. This is just incredible. It's a
great big party. You can just go from bar to bar to bar,'' he said.
   Police were prepared with a force of 172 officers, including
mounted patrols and canine units, but few problems materialized.
   Authorities reported at least five arrests, including three for
ticket scalping and two vendor violations. And city officials said
more than 60 illegally parked cars were towed by the start of the
game.
   Ivy-covered Wrigley, built in 1914, held on to its daytime-only
baseball tradition decades longer than any other ballpark in the
nation. The last team to light up _ the Detroit Tigers _ did it 40
years ago.
   City Council voted in February to lift the ban on lights despite
fierce opposition from a neighborhood group known as CUBS _
Citizens United for Baseball in the Sunshine.
   The team has eight night games for this season and 18 for every
year until 2002.
   But Quigley, vice-president of the opposing neighborhood group,
vowed Monday night that Wrigleyville's residents won't give up
their fight, begun in 1981 when the Tribune Co. bought the Cubs and
announced its plans to erect lights.
   If the group fails to halt night games or at least win a curfew
and other restrictions, Quigley predicted, the Wrigleyville
precinct would vote the area dry of alcohol in the spring 1989
municipal election.
   ``I think it would be a real disservice, especially watching
this carnival atmosphere, to give up the fight,'' Quigley said.
</TEXT>
