<1ST_LINE>r a PM-EasterTrial     08-09 0367</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Easter Trial,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trial in Inkster Police Slayings Ends With Murder Convictions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANGELA AHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman and her three sons were convicted of
murder for the slayings of three police officers in a shootout and
motel siege stemming from a bad-check warrant.
   A Wayne County Circuit Court jury deliberated for 17 hours over
four days before returning the verdicts Monday. Alberta Easter and
her sons William Lemons, 44, Roy Lemons, 48, and George Lemons, 46,
all were found guilty of three counts of first-degree murder.
   They were charged in the deaths of Inkster Sgt. Ira Parker, 41,
and Officers Daniel Dubiel, 36, and Clay Hoover, 24, whose
bullet-riddled bodies lay in a motel room while the family held
police at bay for 10 hours.
   The sons also were found guilty of numerous felony firearms and
felonious assault charges.
   Attorneys for the defendants said they would appeal the verdicts.
   ``I think their minds were made up early, and they weren't able
to resist the pressure to convict,'' said Gerald Evelyn, Easter's
attorney. ``I'm disappointed. It's a very tough case to resist the
pressure to do a lot of things the jury did.''
   The defendants displayed no emotions publicly while families and
friends of the slain officers hugged two Wayne County assistant
prosecutors after the verdict was announced.
   ``The survivors and loved ones reminded me every day of what was
at stake,'' Assistant Prosecutor Douglas Baker said.
   The officers had been trying to serve a bad check warrant on
Easter and one of the Lemons when they were shot.
   Easter had claimed both that the officers shot each other while
exchanging gunfire with the family inside the room, and that they
were shot during exchanges between the family and other officers
outside.
   Autopsy reports said the officers were killed within minutes of
entering the motel room. Hoover and Dubiel were shot 29 times each,
one report said.
   Police and the Easter family exchanged gunfire during the night
of July 9, 1987, before the family gave up early the next day. They
have been jailed since.
   Judge Richard Hathaway scheduled sentencing for Sept. 13. The
murder convictions carry mandatory life prison terms.
</TEXT>
