<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PreschoolMolest     08-09 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Preschool Molest,0437</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Three More Child Victims Won't Testify, Jeopardizing 27
Molestation Counts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The refusal of three alleged victims to
testify in a pre-school molestation trial could force the dismissal
of 27 charges, prosecutors said. The defense, however, said the
case is collapsing of its own weakness.
   The children balked because they are traumatized and want to
avoid reviving painful memories, Deputy District Attorney Lael
Rubin said outside court following Monday's surprise announcement.
   Two boys have continuing nightmares and a girl has lost her
memory of all events up to a year ago _ a sign of ``massive
depression,'' Ms. Rubin said. The children were students at the
McMartin Pre-School.
   ``While we have a responsibility to present all of the evidence,
we also have a responsiblity not to increase trauma to kids,'' she
said.
   Without the testimony, trying to prove the allegations against
Raymond Buckey, 30, and his mother, Peggy McMartin Buckey, 61,
would be an ``extraordinarily difficult thing to do,'' Ms. Rubin
said.
   The Buckeys are charged with 99 molestions and one joint count
of conspiracy, although 82 of the counts name only Buckey. Thirty
charges rest on the testimony of the three children who refused to
testify and on another child who declined to take the stand last
month.
   Thus, nearly a third of the remaining charges could be dropped
if the judge finds insufficient evidence to support them.
   The elimination of some witnesses also means the yearlong trial
_ part of a 5-year-old case _ could end within a month, Ms. Rubin
said.
   Following the disclosure, the prosecution called to the witness
stand Kee MacFarlane, the social worker whose interviews with
hundreds of children in the case became a point of controversy in
pretrial hearings.
   Ms. MacFarlane testified that she used games and picture
coloring to get some children talking about their alleged
molestations.
   The jury watched a videotape in which she asked a girl to
identify body parts on naked dolls.
   The defense has contended that the children were coached or
coerced by the social worker or their parents into alleging
molestation.
   Nine children have testified so far in the case that once
focused on 41 youngsters, but Buckey's attorney, Danny Davis, said
outside court he had suspected that some child witnesses would be
dropped.
   ``The remaining three witnesses had more contradicitions and
unbelievable accounts (in their testimony),'' he said. ``They were
a liablity (to the prosecution.)
   ``I think the prosecution case is falling of its own weight.''
</TEXT>
