<1ST_LINE>r a PM-AbortionProtests     08-09 0326</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Abortion Protests,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge: Activists Will Remain In Jail Until They Tell Names</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sixty-three anti-abortion activists using the
names ``Baby Jane Doe'' and ``Baby John Doe'' _ which they say
represent aborted fetuses _ will remain jailed until they tell
police their real names, a judge ruled.
   Police arrested 69 people over the weekend at three abortion
clinics in Atlanta, bringing to 276 the number of protesters
arrested since the series of demonstrations began during the
Democratic National Convention July 19.
   About 170 members of the group sponsoring the protest, Operation
Rescue, remained in jail Monday. Most are charged with criminal
trespass and giving a false name to police.
   Operation Rescue, based in Binghamton, N.Y., has been using a
cable television show hosted by former Republican presidential
candidate Pat Robertson to recruit volunteers to continue filling
the jails.
   On Monday, State Court judge Nick G. Lambros ruled the legal
cases against 63 of them would not proceed until they gave their
real names.
   Bob Fierer, an attorney for the activists, said he will abide by
the order ``unless or until some other court says it is not
correct.''
   Fulton County jail officials said they have spent $66,450 to
hold and feed those arrested; officials say the influx of
protesters is straining already crowded county facilities.
   Operation Rescue says lengthy daily coverage on the ``700
Club,'' Robertson's show on the Christian Broadcasting Network, is
helping attract many abortion opponents to Atlanta.
   ``He is our one link to Christians all across the country that
we have not had from the secular media,'' said the group's
spokesman, Lowell Patterson.
   The 700 Club, a 90-minute daily show with about a half-hour news
segment, has been carrying regular reports on the Atlanta
anti-abortion protests and flashing the Binghamton telephone number
on the screen during the reports.
   Robertson declined to be interviewed, but a spokeswoman said
Robertson contends he is only providing news coverage of an
important event.
</TEXT>
