<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Lions     08-09 0172</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Lions,0178</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Lions in Zoo Die of Drug Overdose</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four lions died at a zoo after
their food was spiked with barbiturates, a police official said
Tuesday.
   The lions went into a coma at the zoo in Taiping, 150 miles
north of Kuala Lumpur, on July 31 and died one by one last week,
said Mohamad Yunus, assistant superintendent of police.
   He said anyone found guilty of committing such an offence under
the animal protection act could be fined up to $4,000 or be jailed
for five years or get both penalties.
   According to zoo veterinarian Kevin Lazarus, Raja, a 12-year-old
male lion, died Aug. 2; two lionesses, Ponni, 20, and Sheba, 9,
died Friday; and another lioness, Elsa, also 9, died Saturday.
   Sheba and Elsa were from Africa, while Raja and Ponni were Asian
lions.
   The Animal Research Institute in Ipoh is conducting postmortems
on the lions. Preliminary blood tests showed the presence of
barbiturates, which zoo authorities do not give to the animals.
</TEXT>
