<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BRF--ControllerLawsuit     08-09 0157</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Controller Lawsuit,0161</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Air Traffic Controller Win Bias Lawsuit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An air-traffic controller who said he lost his
position in a training program because of his race will be
reinstated, his lawyer said.
   Eddie Grant also is expected to receive a cash settlement that
probably will be ``in the six figures,'' said Phillip Wood.
   Grant, who's black, filed a complaint with the U.S. Equal
Opportunity Commission in 1987, contending the Federal Aviation
Administration harassed him and repeatedly denied him promotions.
   Grant, who worked as a controller at Meigs Airport near downtown
Chicago, applied for four transfers to O'Hare between 1982 and 1984
and was denied each time, Wood said. He won a spot in the tower
after he filed a complaint, but ``they promptly washed him out of
training'' after a 10-month stint, Wood said.
   Grant returned to Meigs where base pay is $20,000 a year lower
than O'Hare.
   FAA officials denied any wrongdoing.
</TEXT>
