<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Peat     08-09 0171</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Peat,0175</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ireland Plans to Sell Peat in United States</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Irish Turf Board said Tuesday it
plans to sell pieces of the old sod to nostalgic Americans.
   Irish peat, suitably packaged with shamrocks, could be on sale
in the United States by Thanksgiving, according to the board.
   ``We do not see turf as an everyday product, but as a nostalgic
reminder of Ireland to burn on special occasions such as
Thanksgiving, Christmas or St. Patrick's Day,'' said John Foley,
marketing manager for the state-run group, which sells peat as fuel
in Ireland and Scotland.
   ``We want to sell our product as a piece of Ireland and although
the proposed packaging design has not yet been finalized it will
include shamrocks in some form,'' Foley said.
   The Turf Board, which sees as its potential customers 40 million
people in the United States claiming Irish origins, said it
initially wants to sell Irish turf in supermarkets on the East
Coast. Test marketing will begin shortly, it said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
