<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Egypt-Prisoners     08-09 0292</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Egypt-Prisoners,0302</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Police Kill Man Convicted in Sadat Slaying</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police shot and killed a convict who escaped
last month while serving a life term in the assassination of
President Anwar Sadat, the Interior Ministry said Tuesday.
   A second escaped convict was wounded and arrested, it said.
   Police on Monday shot and killed Mohammed Khames, 40, after the
convict opened fire on them when they ambushed his apartment in the
Maadi suburb of Cairo, the ministry said.
   In a separate incident Monday, police arrested the second
convict, Ahmed Aswani, 31, in the Ghamra area of the city after he
fought them with gunfire and plastic bombs and was wounded.
   Aswani's brother, Tareq, and a police officer also were wounded
in the gunfight, the Interior Ministry said.
   Tareq had taken part in planning the July 17 escape of his
brother, Khames and a third convict, Essam Kemary, 37, from the
Tura prison on the outskirts of Cairo, the ministry said.
   The three convicts used iron bars to force open their cell
doors, then knocked down the prison guards, seizing their rifles
and shooting their way out.
   Eight days after the escape, police shot and killed Kemary in a
gunfight at the apartment where he was hiding with Khames and
Aswani, both of whom escaped.
   The Interior Ministry said police had recently arrested Khaled
Bekheit, the owner of the apartment.
   The three convicts and Bekheit were members of the Moslem
fundamentalist group Jihad, which was blamed for the Oct. 6, 1981,
assassination of Sadat.
   Three convicted assassins were executed by firing squad, another
two were hanged, and more than 120 were sentenced to prison terms.
   Khames, Aswani and Kemary were given life sentences for taking
part in plotting the assassination.
</TEXT>
