<1ST_LINE>r a PM-WesternFires     08-09 0383</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Western Fires,0394</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fires Mostly Controlled in Four Western States</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Officials in Oregon today called off plans to evacuate resorts
threatened by wildfires and tourism in Wyoming's Yellowstone
National Park returned to normal, but crews continued battling
blazes in Montana and Idaho.
   The largest forest fire of Oregon's season moved away from two
lakeside resorts in the Deschutes National Forest when winds
shifted, Forest Service officials said.
   The fire, which had consumed 12,500 acres by this morning,
threatened the resorts Monday; campers and tourists were warned
they might be evacuated.
   ``The evacuation plans we developed are on the back burner at
this point and hopefully they'll stay there,'' said Kathy Solberg,
a Forest Service spokeswoman.
   In Oregon, the only injury reported was that of a pilot whose
helicopter crashed while carrying water to the blaze Monday. The
pilot was listed in fair condition today at a hospital, where he
was treated for a head injury, cuts and bruises.
   In Wyoming, tourists continued pouring into Yellowstone, despite
forest fires covering some 180,000 acres of the park.
   Lower temperatures and higher humidy have curbed many fires.
   ``The fires have slowed down,'' spokeswoman Joan Anzelmo said.
``I know we did not see significant increase in acreage, and all
the fires continue to be contained within the park boundaries.''
   The cooler weather is allowing some smoke to lift, giving
tourists a closer look at some burned acreage where many trees
survived the flames. The south entrance to the park was open all
weekend; Anzelmo said visitation was back up to normal levels for
this time of year.
   In Montana, crews were trying to contain a 630-acre fire south
of Glacier National Park while contending with grizzly bears.
   Nearly 150 firefighters and smokejumpers, backed by aerial
bombers and helicopters, battled the stubborn, wind-blown fire
Monday.
   Extra precautions were ordered with food and sleeping
arrangements because grizzlies roam the area, said fire boss Dave
Bunnell. Firefighters also were told to work in groups, he said.
   In eastern Idaho, fire crews tried to get under control a
1,500-acre blaze in remote, roadless terrain.
   ``We had another pretty good day. Fire crews kept the fire
within control lines, but there are a couple of areas that pose a
threat,'' Targhee National Forest spokesman Gary Cornell said.
</TEXT>
