<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TransplantCampers     08-09 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Transplant Campers,0347</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Transplant Patient Discharged</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 27-year-old woman who camped out in a pickup
truck while awaiting a life-saving liver transplant left the
hospital Tuesday for a nearby apartment.
   Pollie Smolenski, who underwent surgery June 16 and June 21, was
discharged with fanfare from Presbyterian-University Hospital, but
must stay nearby during recuperation, said hospital spokeswoman
Susan Ruth.
   She may return home to Hallie, Ky., in as little as two weeks,
Ms. Ruth said.
   ``I got the second transplant on my birthday and I considered
that a gift of life,'' Mrs. Smolenski, the mother of three
children, said at a hospital news conference.
   ``I have a whole lot more energy now and I'm looking forward to
laying around and then being a mother again,'' she said.
   For now, Mrs. Smolenski and her husband, Dan, will stay six
blocks from the hospital in a $752-a-month apartment donated by the
landlord, National Development Corp.
   The woman, who suffered from a rare liver disorder called
primary biliary cirrhosis, entered the hospital for evaluation May
17 and was discharged June 7, when she moved into a camper atop her
parents' pickup truck as she awaited a call for a liver transplant.
   Her parents, Raymond and Ersley Eldridge, parked the truck in an
empty parking lot at the University of Pittsburgh. The family
bathed with wet sponges and used public toilets in hospitals and
dormitories for more than five days.
   Police officers donated sandwiches and doughnuts. Finally,
campus policeman Jesse Long called university officials for help
when the couple said their daughter was growing weaker in hot
temperatures. University officials put up the family for one night
in a dormitory before the landlords offered the furnished apartment.
   Hospital spokeswoman Jane Duffield said officials had been
unaware the family lacked adequate housing.
   Her husband, whose 31st birthday is Wednesday, said Tuesday that
his wife's release was his present.
   ``You know how the license plates in Pennsylvania say, `You've
got a friend in Pennsylvania?' I believe that now,'' Smolenski said.
</TEXT>
