<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ContraAid 2ndLd-Writethru a0575 08-09 0725</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Contra Aid, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0575,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Byrd Says Democratic Patience Wearing Thin On Contra Aid Bill</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS grafs 4-5, At the, and 9-10, Fitzwater said, with
White House comment.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd said
today there is no room for further compromise with Republicans on
aid to Nicaragua's Contra rebels because ``we've gone as far as we
can go.''
   Byrd, D-W.Va., told reporters he is prepared to press the
Democratic aid plan to a vote and continues to hope it will attract
bipartisan support.
   ``That would send the right message to Central America,'' he
said.
   At the White House, presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said
``we're still hopeful of getting a Contra aid package passed.''
   Speaking to reporters not long after President Reagan met with
Republican congressional leaders, Fitzwater said ``the Democrats
say they want a bill.'' But he also said that ``the language (of
the Democratic bill) is convoluted.''
   Many Republican senators made it clear Monday they do not trust
the Democrats to carry out their side of the bargain. They said the
Democratic aid plan is seriously flawed because it does not contain
adequate resources to deliver stockpiled arms to the Contras and
has no guarantee House Speaker James Wright will permit a vote.
   Byrd was asked if there was any flexibility on his side of the
issue.
   ``No, I don't think so,'' he replied. ``It seems to me we've
gone as far as we can go.''
   Fitzwater said the administration is concerned about what he
called weaknesses in the Democratic bill with respect to systems
for getting assistance delivered to the Contras.
   He said that bill ``would have the impact of saying you can
deliver it in Honduras but not in Nicaragua, and that's where the
troops are.''
   Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole of Kansas, speaking Monday
after a private meeting in which many Republicans objected to the
Democratic plan, said he would take ``one more shot'' at
negotiating a bipartisan aid package.
   However, he added: ``I wouldn't want to be overly optimistic.''
   Byrd also said he hoped some compromise could be reached.
   But Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., said compromise was unlikely
because the debate over aid to the rebels fighting Nicaragua's
leftist Sandinista government ``has been so long, so emotional, so
partisan, that there's little trust.''
   Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., who took part in talks with
Republicans on the compromise legislation last week, said flatly,
``The negotiations are over. I don't think there is any more room.
We've gone as far as we can go.''
   The Democratic plan would permit $27.1 million in immediate
non-lethal ``humanitarian'' aid to the Contras.
   It also would give President Reagan an opportunity to ask
Congress this fall to release some $16.3 million in previously
purchased arms, ammunition and other military supplies now stored
in warehouses in Central America.
   But it also requires Reagan to certify that such military aid to
the Contras is justified because Nicaragua has disrupted the
``peace and stability'' of Central America by taking two of these
three actions: an unprovoked military attack on the Contras,
``blatant violations'' of the regional peace plan, and continued
``unacceptable levels of military assistance by Soviet-bloc
countries, including Cuba.''
   Some senators said Nicaragua's rulers could prevent the military
aid from being released ``just by being good boys for 30 days.''
   Conservative Republicans called on Dole to force a vote on a
Republican alternative which would make $20 million in new U.S.
military aid available to the Contras as well as releasing
previously approved military aid from warehouses and providing the
``humanitarian'' assistance.
   Sources inside the meeting said Army Lt. Gen. Colin Powell,
President Reagan's national security adviser, reported that he has
``serious reservations'' about the plan.
   Byrd said that if progress is not made in reconstructing a
bipartisan alliance on the issue, he will offer the Democratic aid
plan as an amendment to the pending Defense Department
appropriations bill.
   Contra leaders contacted the White House and several GOP
senators Monday morning to declare their unanimous opposition to
that plan.
   Bosco Matamoros, a spokesman for the Contra resistance forces,
said Contra leaders see the Democratic plan as resulting from
``internal politics in the United States which basically seek to
reward (Nicaraguan President) Daniel Ortega for not complying with
the commitments of the peace process.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
