<HEAD>Drink Clampdown Urged After Racegoer Killed in Brawl</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEWMARKET, England (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Authorities are considering a
clampdown on racetrack drinking after a spectator was killed in a
weekend brawl at the famous Newmarket horse track.
   Police arrested nine people in the death of Keith Dance, 24, who
was hit with a bottle during a fight in a parking lot among two
busloads of drunken spectators after Saturday's races.
   Representatives of the Jockey Club ordered a review of the sales
of liquor at race meets. The senior steward of the Jockey Club,
Lord Fairhaven, said he feared that guidelines on drinking and
security needed to be strengthened.
   Other sports, such as soccer and boxing, have banned alcohol
from arenas because of crowd misbehavior.
   Under Jockey Club regulations, racegoers are forbidden to take
alcohol onto the course and drinking is restricted to certain areas.
