<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-88 1333EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DefenseOvercharges     08-09 0432</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Defense Overcharges,430</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Defense Contractors Consistently Overcharge, Audit Shows</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Defense contractors routinely overcharge the
government for spare parts, and the excess charges, although small
in percentage terms, total hundreds of millions of dollars, the
Pentagon said Tuesday.
   An unusually broad internal defense audit found that nearly half
the contracts reviewed involved some measure of overcharging.
   In the majority of instances, the auditors reported, the
overcharges resulted from a military contractor's failure to abide
by a law requiring the company to share with the government the
latest information it has on labor and material costs.
   If the Pentagon receives ``defective'' cost or pricing data in
the course of contract negotiations, the result is almost always an
overcharge to the government, the auditors noted.
   The audit, conducted by the Pentagon's inspector general, took
more than three years to complete and was one of the largest ever
conducted. It reviewed 774 contracts and subcontracts, worth a
combined $54.3 billion, held by 95 companies.
   ``Of the 774 pricing actions audited, 365 (47.2 percent) were
overpriced by $788.9 million,'' the report said.
   ``The principal reasons for the overpricing were that
contractors did not comply with Public Law 87-653, Truth in
Negotiations Act, on 359 of the 774 pricing actions.''
   That level of overpricing amounts to slightly less than 1.5
percent of the total value of the contracts audited, the report
added.
   By law, the Defense Department can recover money overcharged by
contractors, with interest. The government's claims can be
contested by the contractors and the disputes resolved through
negotiations.
   The Pentagon, in releasing the inspector general's audit,
announced the department had so far recovered $283 million of the
$788.9 million identified in the report.
   ``The department will continue to examine all costs questioned
and to recommend appropriate actions,'' the Pentagon added.
   The inspector general concluded his report by suggesting the
Pentagon hire more auditors, recommending the department ``provide
the funding and resources needed to substantially increase the
level of defective price audit coverage provided.''
   The report noted that, historically, the audit agency can
recover about $19 in excess costs for every dollar spent on price
audits.
   That recommendation, however, already has become the subject of
an internal dispute. Robert W. Helm, the Pentagon's comptroller,
said in comments attached to the report he did not view the
findings as adequate justification for the expense of hiring more
auditors.
   He and other Pentagon officials said the current force of
auditors could improve the situation by helping defense contractors
devise more accurate methods of estimating costs for use during
negotiations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880809-0097 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-88 1314EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Ecuador Bjt   08-09 0694</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ecuador, Bjt,0715</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Socialist President Promises to End Pro-US Policy</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto QTO1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MONTE HAYES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>QUITO, Ecuador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rodrigo Borja, the socialist
president-elect, takes office Wednesday committed to ending
Ecuador's pro-U.S. stand, reversing free-market economic policies
and negotiating easier terms on the foreign debt.
   Borja, who leads the Democratic Left party, has said one of his
first acts will be to renew diplomatic ties with Nicaragua's
leftist Sandinista government.
   A U.S. official said privately Washington feels it can work with
the new president. ``Borja may prove to be a problem for the U.S.
at times, but he is no threat to democracy in Ecuador,'' the
official said.
   Relations with Nicaragua were broken in October 1985 by
conservative President Leon Febres Cordero, Washington's closest
ally in South America, whom Borja replaces. Febres Cordero could
not run for re-election becaue the constitution does not permit a
president to serve consecutive terms.
   ``Re-establishment of relations is a sign that our government is
independent and sovereign,'' said Gonzalo Ortiz, official spokesman
of the new administration.
   Borja, a 53-year-old law professor who is a vice president of
the Socialist International, is a longtime political foe of Febres
Cordero and lost a presidential election runoff to him in 1984. He
won the presidency in May, defeating populist candidate Abdala
Bucaram.
   Ecuador, a South American nation of 10 million people about the
size of Colorado, returned to democracy in 1979 after nine years of
civilian and military dictatorships.
   President Daniel Ortega of Nicaragua is among seven Latin
American presidents, most of them leftists, scheduled to attend.
They include Fidel Castro of Cuba, whose trips abroad are not
frequent, and his visit is viewed in Ecuador as an unusual show of
support for the new president.
   Secretary of State George P. Shultz will represent the United
States. Mario Soares, the socialist president of Portugal, also
plans to attend.
   Borja has said he will seek close relations with the
organization of nations that profess non-alignment and end Febres
Cordero's free-market policies, which he blames for the worst
recession since Ecuador began exporting oil in the early 1970s.
   The economy shrank by 3.5 percent in 1987 and the annual
inflation rate is nearly 60 percent, the highest in five years.
Fewer than half the nation's workers have full-time jobs.
   Febres Cordero took pride in meeting obligations on the $9.2
billion foreign debt for most of his four-year term, but no
payments have been made since January and Ecuador is more than $1
billion in arrears.
   Officials of the Febres Cordero government blame the nation's
economic problems on the decline of world oil prices and
earthquakes that crippled the oil industry for six months in 1987.
   The new president has said he will impose exchange controls,
restrict imports to save dollar reserves and control prices of
basic consumer goods to fight inflation.
   He also has announced plans for a more restrictive policy toward
foreign investment and, unless creditors agree to easier terms, a
moratorium on foreign debt payments.
   ``I don't believe the debt is payable under the present
circumstances,'' he said recently.
   Personal animosity between Borja and Febres Cordero has created
problems in the transition of power.
   Febres Cordero said he would not attend the inauguration or
follow the Ecuadorean custom of personally turning over the
presidential sash to his successor.
   ``Since the wellfare of the Ecuadorean people depends on the
next government, may God help them and insure their success,'' he
said Friday. ``But knowing them as I do, I have my doubts.''
   Besides the personal feud, Ecuador's political turmoil in recent
years has included two unsuccessful military rebellions against
Febres Cordero, a kidnapping of the president in which disaffected
paratroopers held him for 11 hours, and an attempt by the
opposition-controlled Congress to impeach him.
   Borja has accused Febres Cordero of trying to sabotage the new
government by creating economic problems before he takes office.
   ``We are concerned by the bankrupt state in which we are
receiving Ecuador,'' he said, and charged the Febres Cordero
administration with creating an 11 percent budget deficit ``to
cause us difficulties'' with inflation.
   Interior Minister Heinz Moeller described the complaints as
``whining.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
