<HEAD>Two Accused of Selling Fake Disney World Tickets</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KISSIMMEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police arrested two people accused of
selling counterfeit three-day passes to Walt Disney World after the
park confiscated about 500 bogus tickets at its gates.
   Police cameras filmed the two selling fake tickets from their
hotel room, and about 100 fake tickets were confiscated following
the arrests of Patricia Trippensee, 45, and Charles Evans, 58, said
Osceola County sheriff's Sgt. Chuck Lavender.
   The two allegedly sold tickets to small distributors and booth
dealers throughout central Florida. The dealers did not know the
tickets were well-made fakes, according to Lavender.
   Disney officials discovered the counterfeit tickets when they
failed to find imprinted security markings. The real tickets sell
for $78 and the fake ones were going for $70, Lavender said.
   Disney customers turning up with counterfeit tickets were given
complimentary one-day tickets.
   Ms. Trippensee and Evans were charged with grand theft and were
being held in the Osceola County Jail on $25,000 bail each.
</TEXT>
