<HEAD>Rescued Iranian Fishermen Transferred</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Five shipwrecked Iranian fishermen rescued by
the USS Vincennes have been transferred to another Navy ship to
await the completion of arrangements for their return to Iran, the
Pentagon said Tuesday.
   The Vincennes, the cruiser that mistakenly shot down an Iranian
airliner last month with 290 people aboard, picked up the five
Iranians on Sunday in the Gulf of Oman, just south of the Persian
Gulf, while on patrol. The men said their fishing boat had sunk and
that they had been floating in a small dinghy for eight days.
   Dan Howard, the Defense Department's chief spokesman, said the
Iranians had been transferred to the guided-missile cruiser USS
Texas, which also is operating in the Gulf of Oman.
   Howard declined to predict how long the men would remain aboard
that vessel, saying the Pentagon had yet to hear from the State
Department about how the men would be returned to Iran. Those
arrangements must be made through diplomatic channels and the
discussions are still in progress, he said.
