<HEAD>Two Admit Trading Alligator Hides For Illegal Alaska Hunts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two men who traded illegal alligator
hides for illegal Alaska hunting trips have pleaded guilty to three
misdemeanor counts of violating federal wildlife laws.
   Under the plea agreement accepted Monday, prosecutors will
recommend fines of at least $10,000 each, but will not oppose
defense requests for probation. Sentencing was set for Oct. 17.
   The maximum penalty under the law is three years in prison and
$300,000 in fines.
   Ira Wendell Blue, 41, and Craig Sellers, 42, acknowledged
arranging to circumvent laws protecting grizzly bears, mountain
sheep and mountain goats. They also said they illegally possessed
alligator hides, which they used, along with the promise of use of
a Florida condominum and auto-race tickets, to trade for guide
services on illegal hunting trips in 1984, 1985 and 1986.
