<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Obit-Ricci     08-09 0229</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Ricci,0237</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Couturier, Perfume-Maker Robert Ricci Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Ricci, a perfume-maker and couturier who
with his mother founded one of France's leading fashion houses, has
died at the age of 83.
   Ricci, president of Couture et Parfums Nina Ricci, died Monday
in his Paris home, a company spokesman said.
   The son of jeweler Louis Ricci, he was born in Paris on July 29,
1905. As a young man, he became interested in maketing and graphic
art.
   In 1932, at age 27, he and his mother, Nina, founded the fashion
house Nina Ricci, and as president oversaw both the business and
creative aspects of the business. His mother, who died in 1970,
provided artistic inspiration.
   The pre-war success of the company was rapid. Nina Ricci had 22
employees in 1932. By 1939, there were 450.
   In 1946, after the war, he created the first Nina Ricci perfume,
Coeur-Joie, followed by L'Air du Temps in 1948, which became a
classic.
   Ricci went international after the war and began diversifying
into other areas, such as accessories, glasses and jewelry.
   Nina Ricci has operations in 130 countries. In 1987, it had
consolidated revenues of $156 million. Perfumes make up 75 percent
of the company's sales, and 70 percent of the perfume division's
sales come from L'Air du Temps.
   Funeral services were scheduled for Thursday at Notre Dame
d'Auteuil church.
</TEXT>
