<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BlackFratFire     08-09 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Black Frat Fire,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Renovation To Begin On Another House For Ole Miss Black Fraternity</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OXFORD, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A black fraternity will make its debut this
fall on the University of Mississippi's all-white Fraternity Row
despite an apparent arson fire because the school will renovate
another house for the group.
   The university has received tentative approval to assume the
obligation of renovating the vacant Phi Kappa Theta fraternity
house, three houses up the block from the Phi Beta Sigma house that
burned Thursday, Ole Miss Chancellor Gerald Turner said Monday.
   ``The morning of the fire, we were in touch with them (Phi Kappa
Theta),'' Turner said. ``We felt like with its being available ...
the most immediate need was to get Phi Beta Sigma on Fraternity
Row.''
   Police patrols have increased since fire destroyed the house
that Phi Beta Sigma members had planned to lease from another
fraternity, Turner said.
   The 20-member black Phi Beta Sigma had been readying the vacant
40- to 50-year-old brick and wood house for the fall.
   Fire officials said they discovered evidence of a fire
accelerant in a closet on the second floor, where the blaze began.
The evidence was turned over Monday to the state Crime Lab.
   The renovation work, estimated to cost $15,000 to $20,000, will
be paid for through a fund drive launched Friday by the
university's Interfraternity Council, Turner said.
   ``There have been a lot of inquiries on how to assist from
within the state and outside, from fraternity groups on campus,
civic groups, alumni and friends,'' said Ed Meek, university
director of public relations. ``I believe we'll reach the $20,000
goal easily.''
</TEXT>
