<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Ferry     08-09 0284</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Ferry,0295</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bodies of Ferry Disaster Victims Cremated</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DILIP GANGULY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KATIHAR, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The bodies of 10 people who died in
India's worst ferry disaster were cremated Tuesday on the banks of
the Ganges River as police fired seven gunshots in honor of the
more than 400 passengers believed drowned.
   Hindu and Moslem priests prayed as the bodies were placed on
wooden logs and set aflame near the river that Hindus consider
sacred. About 1,000 relatives and villagers watched silently.
   The 35-year-old steam-powered ferry overturned Saturday when it
hit a sand bar while crossing the river and hurled at least 542
people into the surging waters about 650 miles east of New Delhi.
   About 100 people swam to shore or were rescued by villagers in
small boats. Only 30 bodies have been recovered and the rest of the
passengers are presumed dead, officials said.
   Most of the passengers were Hindu pilgrims on their way to a
shrine.
   The government blamed the accident on overcrowding and safety
violations, according to officials who spoke on condition of
anonymity. The ferry had a capacity of 160.
   Two steam-powered boats and 70 rescue workers have tried to pull
the vessel from the river bed, but the search has been hampered by
swift currents and rising water levels caused by monsoon rains.
   Asgar Ali, who heads the recovery effort, said bodies are
believed to be trapped inside the ferry, but none have been found
so far. He said many of the bodies were carried away by strong
currents.
   India's worst previous ferry disaster occurred in 1970, when at
least 150 people drowned in the Krishna River in the southern state
of Andhra Pradesh.
</TEXT>
