<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0577 08-09 1017</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0577,920</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede ERIE</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: New in first 10 grafs with Bush comments on Dukakis' record,
predicting erosion of Democratic lead. Edits for transition and
picks up 2nd graf pvs bgng: In a ..., deleting last 10 grafs to
tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush today accused
Michael Dukakis of trying to ``run away'' from a record ``on the
very, very far liberal fringe'' and said his Democratic rival is
losing his lead in the presidential race.
   Bush, at a news conference here, predicted Dukakis would fall
back from the 17-point advantage he has registered in some national
polls.
   ``That is turning around,'' Bush said. ``You watch, in the next
couple of days you'll see evidence of the turnaround on that.'' He
did not elaborate.
   Just six days before the opening of the Republican National
Convention in New Orleans, where he will become the GOP
presidential nominee, Bush said he still has not decided who will
be his running mate.
   ``I'm not close in the sense of like tomorrow making a final
decision,'' the vice president said. Bush has said he wants to keep
it a secret until the final day of the convention.
   Bush spoke at an airport news conference here after a speech
earlier in Erie. Later, he planned to fly to Philadelphia for a
ribbon-cutting at the Polish-American Congress Museum and to take
part in a crime-fighting effort called the ``National Night Out
Against Crime.'' Americans in more than 7,200 towns plan to turn on
porch and house lights as a symbolic message that they intend to
fight for safer neighborhoods.
   Bush did not mention Dukakis in his speech, but went after him
at the news conference.
   ``He's trying to run away from a record in Massachusetts on the
very, very far liberal fringe of the political spectrum, and I have
to pin him down and I have to get him to say what he's really for,'
Bush said. ``And he's unwilling to do that because he thinks he can
preempt the middle.''
   Bush said he was urging speakers the GOP convention to be
positive and to focus on the issues.
   ``But I can't guarantee that somebody's not going to take a
swipe at Michael Dukakis,'' Bush said. ``I have a lot of friends
out there and they didn't like the vicious, personal attacks
(against Bush at the Democratic convention) and I did not react to
them, but I can't control everbody but I'm urging them to stay
positive, as I'm doing.''
   In Erie earlier, Bush blamed liberals in Congress for
undermining the battle against illegal drugs and told a gathering
of police officers, ``Let's get tougher on the criminals.''
   In a speech billed as non-partisan, Bush did not mention Dukakis
by name. But he criticized the American Civil Liberties Union,
whose members he has said include Dukakis.
   He said that to win the war against drugs the nation must be as
committed as it was in World War II ``when the whole nation then
pulled together, one purpose, one cause, everyone working in
exactly the same direction. We've got to plan an attack at every
level of government.''
   Bush spoke before the Pennsylvania chapter of the Fraternal
Order of Police on his last major campaign trip before the
Republican National Convention.
   Trying to forge an image as a hard-liner on law enforcement,
Bush said, ``When it comes to criminal justice our first priority
must be to keep the criminals away from the good and decent people
who want to raise their families in peace and safety.
   ``There are those, like the ACLU, whose first concerns are the
protection of the criminals' rights and the potential abuse of
power by police,'' the vice president said. ``My first concerns are
the protection of law-abiding citizens and the abuse of our system
of constitutional protections by thugs who can go and hire smart
lawyers and find the right judges to set them free.
   ``So let's not take away the guns of innocent citizens,'' he
continued. ``Let's get tougher on the criminals.''
   Bush said that too often police are being denied the ammunition
they need to fight the battle against drugs. ``Congress is full of
rhetorical heroes on the issue of drugs, but when it comes to law
enforcement a lot of the liberals there go AWOL,'' he said.
   Bush said the budget request for the Coast Guard was slashed by
$72 million last year in order to provide more money for mass
transit and Amtrak, resulting in a 55 percent reduction in Coast
Guard air and sea patrols.
   He also blamed ``the liberals in the Senate'' for derailing
sentencing guidelines necessary for implementing a federal death
penalty under constitutional standards set by a 1972 Supreme Court
decision.
   Bush said Americans must insist that judges accept new federal
sentencing guidelines that mandate consistently tougher penalties.
   ``We also need to change the legal technicalities that set
criminals free,'' he said. ``There's something wrong with the
system when the modern-day version of a prison break is crawling
through a loophole.''
   He praised the administration of former Pennsylvania Gov.
Richard Thornburgh, now the attorney general-designate, for
reducing by 94 percent the early release of convicted felons in the
state and said Thornburgh effectively ended the early release or
parole of first-degree murderers.
   Bush called for more money for building prisons and said that
unnecessary military bases should be converted to prisons or
rehabilitation facilities. He also urged that states that have
decriminalized possession of drugs should reverse course.
   ``And to those who say drugs should be legalized I say this _
legalization is just another word for surrender, and surrender is
not in America's vocabulary.''
   One day earlier, Bush praised Jesse Jackson's efforts to compat
drug abuse, saying, ``Anybody who can raise the consciousness of
the young people of this country about staying away from drugs
certainly can have a useful role.'' But he made no promises when
asked if the former Democratic presidential candidate might have a
role in his administration working on the drug issue.
</TEXT>
