<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--Emmy-Disqualification     08-09 0174</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Emmy-Disqualification,0179</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PBS Show `Rumpole' Disqualified in Miniseries Competition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BURBANK, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The PBS-TV show ``Rumpole of the Bailey
Mystery'' has been disqualified as an Emmy nominee in the
miniseries category because it was a number of separate stories
rather than one continuous show.
   It has been replaced with ABC-TV's ``The Bourne Identity,'' said
John Leverence of the Academy of Television Arts and Sciences.
   Producers of ``Rumpole'' incorrectly entered the six-part series
as a miniseries, which tells one story with a beginning, middle and
ending, Leverence said Tuesday. ``Rumpole,'' he said, has a number
of separate stories.
   Also nominated in the miniseries category was ABC's ``Baby M,''
NBC's ``Billionaire Boys Club,'' NBC's ``Gore Vidal's Lincoln'' and
NBC's ``The Murder of Mary Phagan.''
   ``The Bourne Identity,'' which aired May 8-9, was sixth in the
original balloting. It was nominated in two other categories _
single-camera editing and music composition for a miniseries or
special.
   The 40th annual Primetime Emmy Awards will be presented Aug. 28
and will be televised live by Fox Broadcasting.
</TEXT>
