<1ST_LINE>r p AM-CampaignJokes     08-09 0654</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Campaign Jokes,650</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>The Most-Joked-About Candidate: Bush Is the Winner</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Whether he wins the November election or not,
George Bush is way ahead in one contest: Johnny Carson told more
jokes about him than any other political candidate in the first
half of 1988.
   Carson's monologues on ``The Tonight Show,'' considered one
indicator of what people outside politics are thinking, were
analyzed by Daniel Amundson and S. Robert Lichter.
   The two researchers, who also looked at comedian David
Letterman's monologues on ``Late Night,'' published their findings
on political humor in the magazine Public Opinion.
   ``Poor George Bush endured a veritable comedic vivisection,''
the pair wrote. ``The late-night hosts carved up his record, his
campaign tactics and his manhood.''
   Carson, on Bush's speaking ability: ``The last time George Bush
gave a speech someone came up and drew a chalk outline around his
body.''
   In Iowa: ``I think George Bush went too far when he stuffed
straw in his overalls and started to sing `If I Only Had A Brain.'''
   And during Super Tuesday season: ``Down South he went into a
truck stop wearing a pair of overalls, but he had a little
alligator sewn over the pocket.''
   Amundson and Lichter looked at the Carson and Letterman
monologues from Jan. 1 to June 7. They found that Carson was far
more political than Letterman and included jokes about at least one
candidate in nearly every new episode of his show.
   Bush's campaign manager, Lee Atwater, has said he pays close
attention to the Carson monologues ``as a barometer of how the
candidates play in the `real' America beyond the beltway,'' the
highway that encircles Washington, Lichter and Amundson said.
   And Atwater's not the only one.
   ``When Johnny Carson talks, candidates have to listen,'' says
Lichter. ``They listen to hear what America is hearing.''
   Republican contenders were the butt of Carson's jokes twice as
often as the Democrats, with Bush the target of 32 barbs followed
by Bob Dole with 18 and Pat Robertson with 17.
   On the Democratic side, Gary Hart attracted 15 jokes, Dick
Gephardt was the target of nine and Bruce Babbit drew five.
   The lower numbers for the Democrats ``reflect the writers strike
that put `The Tonight Show' on reruns during the peak of Democratic
campaigning in the Midwest and New York,'' the authors said. ``It
certainly doesn't mean they were any less laughable than the
Republicans.''
   The Hart jokes centered on his relationship with model Donna
Rice, starting in January when Carson remarked that ``Gary Hart
made a stunning statement today. He said if he was elected he would
not be the first adulterer in the White House, but he would be the
best.''
   Letterman got into the act, the researchers reported, on the day
President Reagan had his annual physical. ``Reagan says he has the
body of a 20-year-old _ which if I remember correctly is very much
like the Gary Hart campaign slogan,'' the comedian said.
   Amundson and Lichter said most of the jokes focused on gaffes
and personal foibles, Gephardt's appearance and ``the utter
hopelessness'' of Babbitt's quest.
   ``I'm not sure if I want a president who has to draw in his
face,'' Carson said after what the researchers called ``the
mysterious appearance'' of Gephardt's eyebrows before the Iowa
caucuses.
   And when Babbitt endorsed Michael Dukakis, Carson cracked,
``Babbitt lending support to Dukakis is like Sandy Duncan lending
her bra to Oprah Winfrey.''
   Carson disputed Robertson's claim that Planned Parenthood was
formed to create a master race. Obviously that's not true, Carson
said, or we'd have a better class of presidential candidates.
   Conspicuously absent from the barrage of quips was Democratic
nominee Dukakis, a straight-laced candidate. Lichter said he and
Amundson are thinking of continuing their survey through the
general election campaign ``just to see if Johnny Carson can find
something funny about Mike Dukakis.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
