<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Reagan-Education     08-09 0369</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Education,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Expected To Name Successor To Education Secretary</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No time set for announcement</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   White House officials prepared today to
announce a successor to Education Secretary William Bennett amid
indications the job will go to Lauro Cavazos, president of Texas
Tech University, who could become the first Hispanic Cabinet member.
   Administration officials would not discuss plans to announce the
choice to succeed Bennett, who announced in May that he wished to
leave the administration by around mid-September.
   Nor would officials confirm that Cavazos was set to be nominated
for the post, although it was learned that the 61-year-old college
president had traveled from the Texas Tech campus in Lubbock to the
nation's capital.
   Cavazos had been scheduled to appear today at a meeting of Tech
officials and representatives of the state Legislative Budget Board
and the Governor's Budget Office, but did not attend that meeting.
   Neither Bennett nor Cavazos could immediately be reached for
comment.
   Loye Miller, a spokesman for Bennett, declined to comment.
   The Lubbock Avalanche-Journal had quoted sources as saying that
Cavazos was being considered for the job.
   The newspaper said today that it was told by sources in
Washington that Cavazos was ``on a very short list'' of candidates.
   Cavazos, who has served as Tech's president since April 1980,
received the National Hispanic Leadership award of the League of
United Latin American Citizens in July for his work in education.
He was cited for his efforts to reduce the dropout rate among
Hispanic youth.
   Several Lubbock residents told the newspaper that they had been
contacted in the last few days by federal agents conducting a
background check on Cavazos. They were not given reasons for the
queries, which are a routine part of the appointment process.
   Cavazos' possible selection might be considered an effort by
Republicans to court the Hispanic vote in South Texas since he is a
native of that area and a son of a foreman of the Santa Gertrudis
Division of the storied King Ranch.
   Cavazos announced in May that he would resign as president of
Texas Tech in July 1989 and, after a leave, return to teach anatomy
in the medical school, where he has tenure.
</TEXT>
