<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-88 1352EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Korea Bjt   08-09 0669</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Korea, Bjt,0687</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Disappointed South Koreans Will Meet North Koreans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korean officials, disappointed
that North Korea rejected a proposal to work out details for
full-scale negotiations, said they will agree to a meeting on the
communist nation's demand to be co-host of the Olympics, sources
said Tuesday.
   A North Korean letter delivered Tuesday said there was not
enough time to hold ``a preliminary contact and then the full talks
under the present condition where 40 days ... are left until the
opening of the Olympic Games that must be debated as an urgent
agenda item.''
   The Olympic Games start Sept. 17 in Seoul and North Korea has
said it will boycott unless it can be co-host. The International
Olympic Committee refused that demand and said the Olympics are
awarded to a city, not a country.
   The letter from Yang Hyong Sop, chairman of the rubberstamp
Supreme People's Assembly, called for a meeting in Panmunjom on
Aug. 17 that would be limited to discussing logistical
arrangements, with a first full parliamentary meeting to be held in
its capital of Pyongyang on Aug. 26.
   South Korean had called for detailed preliminary talks on
working out an agenda for full-scale negotiations.
   The North Korean letter was addressed to South Korean National
Assembly speaker Kim Chae-sun and delivered at the border truce
site of Panmunjom.
   ``The Aug. 17 meeting is expected to come off as proposed by the
North, but the overall picture of the situation is rather
disappointing,'' said one source at the National Assembly, who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   A few hours after the North Korean letter was delivered,
political party leaders met and said they would send a reply by the
end of this week.
   Lee Dong-bok, chief secretary to the Assembly speaker, said
after the meeting that a notable feature of North Korea's letter is
its stress on the inclusion of ``personages of various parties,
organizations and circles'' as full members of the proposed
parliamentary talks.
   The Hankook Ilbo, a mass-circulation national daily, said, ``Any
agreement can hardly be expected, because (North Korea) insists on
including ``personages of parties, organizations and circles,''
Pyongyang's reference to dissident groups in South Korea.
   Sources in the National Assembly said the tone of the North
Korean letter is not conciliatory and is rather ``rude,'' in sharp
contrast with North Korean proposals in the past.
   ``Dialogue may be opened, but the real fruit of the
parliamentary talks can hardly expected,'' The Chosun Ilbo, an
influential national newspaper, said in a commentary.
   Hankook said North Korea appears to be eager to find a new
excuse to boycott the Olympic Games by making demands South Korea
can hardly accept.
   Both papers noted that North Korea said the talks were urgent
while proposing Aug. 17 as a meeting date. South Korea had earlier
suggested a meeting begin Aug. 11.
   The papers also noted that the date is two days after Aug. 15,
when South Korean radical students plan to march to the border for
talks with North Korean youths on national unfication.
   ``It is obvious that all this is intended to stir unrest in our
society,'' Hankook said.
   South Korea fears the north may use terrorism to try and disrupt
the Olympics. North Korea was implicated in the Nov. 29 bombing of
a South Korean airliner with the deaths of all 115 people aboard.
   Most observers believe there is little chance North Korea will
drop its demand to be co-host of the Olympics and agree to take
part. Such a change would represent a total turnabout after 40
years of bitter rivalry.
   North Korea sees the holding of the Olympics in Seoul as a major
political defeat since both sides claim to be the sole legitimate
government on the Korean peninsula.
   North Korea invaded South Korea in 1950 to start the Korean War.
The two sides technically remain at war since no peace treaty was
signed when an armistice halted fighting in 1953.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
