<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Poland-Protest     08-09 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Protest,0365</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Official Mine Wage Protest Fails To Materialize</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Work went on uninterrupted Tuesday in a
copper mine complex despite a call by the industry's official union
for a brief wage protest there.
   There were conflicting explanations on why the protest did not
take place and about recent developments at the Rudna mine.
   Government officials said the protest was called off by leaders
of the local, officially recognized copper union after they
received a telegram from the Industry Ministry proposing talks.
   Officials of the banned Solidarity trade union, which had urged
workers to ignore the call, said miners simply refused to go along
with the protest.
   Solidarity officials asked miners to reject the call because the
protest focused on wage issues and not safety demands, which the
banned union maintains are at the core of disputes with mine
management.
   Government spokesman Jerzy Urban said Tuesday the official union
called off the protest after receiving the ministry telegram.
   Local Solidarity spokesman Jan Sugalski said the official union
had gone ahead with the protest action, trying to turn off conveyor
belts to force a work stoppage. Sugalski said miners refused to
carry out the orders.
   The local copper workers' union, part of the national federation
of trade unions, on Monday distributed an appeal calling for a
one-to two-hour work stoppage in the copper mining industries of
lower Silesia, said Solidarity advisor Jacek Kuron.
   Kuron said the official union's failure to mention safety
conditions amounted to an attempt to thwart Solidarity-led efforts
to bring changes to the industry.
   He said the wage issue is secondary to safety demands because
management has shown a willingness to meet pay demands.
   The action by the official union appeared designed to head off
protests by Solidarity supporters at the Rudna mine, outside the
town of Lubin.
   An independent mining commission at the Rudna mine has charged
that miners must work at temperatures that exceed industry norms.
   The miners have given management until Aug. 15 to adhere to an
earlier agreement to improve working conditions.
   They threatened protest actions if management did not comply.
</TEXT>
