<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-88 1418EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-ConventionTV 1stLd-Writethru a0615 08-09 0902</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Convention TV, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0615,890</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan Film Again Causes Concerns for Networks at GOP Convention</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of ``Gralnick'' in 7th graf, ``We'll have,
15th graf, ``From this, and 21st graf, ``It's due</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BARR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Reagan II, the movie, is already causing some
concern for networks that got caught in a film controversy at the
Republican National Convention four years ago.
   Despite some grumbling after this year's Democratic National
Convention in Atlanta, the three big networks will give the
Republicans equal time for the four-day GOP convention next week in
New Orleans, though with smaller staffs.
   A filmed tribute to the outgoing president is on the program
Monday, and Vice President George Bush, the expected nominee, will
be featured in another film Thursday.
   ``I'm still waiting for something definitive from the party on
the length,'' said Joe Angotti, executive producer of NBC's
convention coverage. ``There is a Reagan film which I don't feel
obligated to carry, because Reagan is not a candidate.''
   When Reagan was a candidate, in 1984, the three networks parted
company on carrying the 18-minute promotional film shown to the
convention. NBC and CNN carried it all, ABC carried excerpts and
CBS used the time during the film to show its own report on the
Reagan administration's successes and failures.
   This time, CBS may cover the film as a news story, ``using the
journalistic standards we use for other stories,'' executive
producer Lane Venardos said from New Orleans.
   ``We'll have to see it before deciding,'' said Jeff Gralnick,
executive producer for ABC.
   At the Democratic convention, CBS decided not to carry a
six-minute film about presidential nominee Michael Dukakis, filling
the time with commentary and a commercial. ABC, NBC and CNN all
carried that film.
   As of Monday, it wasn't even certain how long the Reagan and
Bush films would run _ Venardos said he had been told that Reagan's
film ran 18 minutes and Bush's 12 minutes, while Angotti said he
had been told that each ran about 20 to 25 minutes.
   During the Democratic convention, ABC News president Roone
Arledge had complained that the carefully orchestrated proceedings
were ``driving people at home not to watch,'' and raised the
possibility of cutting back coverage of the GOP event.
   However, ABC will join NBC and CBS in giving the Republicans an
equal two-hour block of prime time Monday through Thursday, from 9
to 11 p.m. EDT. The Republicans have scheduled some nights to run
past 11 p.m., including the roll call which will nominate Bush as
the party's presidential candidate.
   Venardos said CBS will stay with the roll call at least until
Bush has secured the nomination _ which is expected to be when
Texas casts its votes.
   ``That is really why we are here,'' Venardos said. ``I think
viewers care a lot about seeing and hearing their home state.''
   ``I think you have to play these things by ear,'' Angotti said.
``The more you say in advance about what you might do or not do,
the more trouble you get into.''
   ``From this vantage point, I will say exactly what I said before
Atlanta _ our plans are for 9-11 p.m. We haven't seen a schedule
which tells us what we need to know to make precise plans,''
Gralnick said.
   All three networks will use fewer people to cover the
Republicans than they deployed in Atlanta, and all said that's at
least partly because Republicans have no one comparable to Jesse
Jackson, who was still in the presidential race in Atlanta and made
noises about challenging for the vice-presidential slot.
   ABC is cutting 100 from its staff, CBS is paring 50 and NBC
plans to cut 25 to 30. They will still send hundreds.
   ``We had more delegate reporters last time than we are going to
have here,'' Angotti said from New Orleans. ``We're going to rely
more with our affiliates who are with the delegations to come up
with whatever news there is.''
   Venardos said the smaller staff also reflected ``things we
learned to do more efficiently in Atlanta. ... It wasn't so much
coverage, as how to schedule people more efficiently.''
   ABC is economizing by not taking ``Nightline'' to New Orleans,
and is using one control room instead of two.
   ``It's due to the fact that it's a one-candidate convention,''
Gralnick said. ``There are fewer hotels to cover, fewer candidate
possibiliies, less of a breaking news situation than in Atlanta.''
   Cable News Network plans no cut in its staff of nearly 300, said
network spokesman Kitsie Bassett, and no reduction in coverage time
which extended nearly 70 hours during the Democratic convention.
   CNN will go live at 11 a.m. Monday for the first convention
session.
   With the presidential nomination locked up, the Bush campaign is
banking on the vice presidency to boost ratings. Bush has said he
will not announce his choice until the convention's final day.
   ``I'm for doing anything that will help build a TV audience,''
Lee Atwater, Bush's campaign manager, said Monday.
   The Democratic convention was watched, on average, by less than
a fourth of the nation's homes with television. NBC did best with
an average rating of 7.4, while ABC had 6.9, CBS had 6.5 and CNN
had an average of 2.0 for the evening prime-time hours.
   Each rating point represents 1 percent of the nation's 88.6
million homes with TV.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
