<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SovietInspectors     08-09 0496</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet Inspectors,0513</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Inspect Two Sites As Part of INF Treaty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GOSSELIES, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet officials Tuesday began
counting U.S. cruise missiles at two sites in Belgium as part of
inspections allowed under the superpower arms treaty.
   The first team of 10 Soviet inspectors arrived by bus at the
European Repair Facility at Gosselies, about 30 miles south of
Brussels, to check missiles at a maintenance site.
   They paused for photographs and then went quickly into a
one-story building that is part of the operations run by the
Belgian defense contractor Sabca.
   ``It's a straightforward kind of process,'' said U.S. Embassy
spokesman James Findley. ``This is bean-counting, going in and
looking at what the treaty says are limited and figuring it out.''
   The Soviets, he said, would have a chance to measure unarmed
cruise missiles removed from their canisters for repair or
maintenance.
   ``They may take special measurements and check because this is
the only place they can do it,'' Findley said.
   There was no indication how many missiles were at the facility,
the only one of its kind in Europe set up to maintain and repair
the weapons.
   The number can vary daily. On June 21, there were 55 missiles at
the plant, according to U.S. officials.
   A second team of 10 inspectors went to Florennes Air Base, 10
miles north of the repair facility.
   Sixteen ground-launched cruise missiles and four spares are kept
at the base along with four launchers and eight spares, according
to U.S. officials.
   The sleek, ground-hugging weapons, which arrived in March 1985,
are jet-propelled, winged missiles with advanced guidance systems.
They are 21 feet long.
   The Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces treaty provides the Soviet
Union and the United States with unprecedented review of each
other's facilities.
   The Soviets are visiting 30 sites in the United States and five
Western European countries. U.S. experts are inspecting 133 sites
in the Soviet Union and Eastern Europe.
   Each inspection can last up to 24 hours, with a possible
eight-hour extension.
   The Soviet experts, who arrived Monday, spent the night in a
Brussels hotel and notified authorities Tuesday that they wanted to
inspect the two sites.
   They were expected to spend Tuesday night at the facilities and
return to Brussels on Wednesday. They will leave Belgium later
Wednesday or Thursday.
   The Soviets were taken on a two-hour bus tour of the historic
capital with U.S. Air Force Lt. Col. David MacNamee. He said they
expressed interest in the Gothic and Baroque architecture.
   Belgium is the fourth Western European country visited by the
Soviet teams since the 60-day inspection process began July 1. They
have visited Germany, Britain and the Netherlands. They have yet to
inspect sites in Italy.
   The treaty provides for elimination within three years of all
U.S. and Soviet land-based missiles with ranges from about 300 to
3,400 miles. President Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev signed the treaty in December in Washington.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
