<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leeza Gibbons, co-anchor of the television
show ``Entertainment This Week,'' says she's learned that love at
first sight is possible.
   She and Chris Quinten, an actor on the English soap opera
``Coronation Street,'' will marry in November, she said. They met
two months ago in New Zealand.
   ``I never believed in this love-at-first-sight thing. But I'm a
convert now,'' she said.
   ``We've both spent a decade or more in the fast lane. We've been
exposed to the most eligible people in the world. I think we
know,'' Ms. Gibbons, a South Carolina native, said Monday in a
telephone interview with The Columbia State from her Los Angeles
office.
   She said the wedding will take place ``somewhere in Europe.''
   ``I certainly don't expect my father to throw a big, lavish
wedding,'' said Ms. Gibbons, 31, who previously was married for
three years.
   She said she wasn't sure where the couple would work. ``I don't
want to have a transcontinental relationship. That doesn't make
sense,'' she said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Rex Harrison has made a triumphant return to
the London stage after a four-year absence.
   The 80-year-old Harrison won a rousing ovation Monday from the
first-night audience for his portrayal of the Earl of Loam in a
revival of J.M. Barrie's comedy of manners ``The Admirable
Crichton.''
   Harrison was last on the London stage in 1984 in Frederick
Lonsdale's ``Aren't We All'' with Claudette Colbert.
   He will play eight shows a week in ``The Admirable Crichton.''
The play is about a butler who reverses the roles of master and
servant with the earl when the household end up on a desert island.
   One of Harrison's best-remembered roles is Professor Henry
Higgins in the London and Broadway productions of ``My Fair Lady''
more than 20 years ago.
   Actor Jeremy Irons, who was in the audience Monday, said: ``I
would like to be on that stage when I am 80. Harrison is a
charismatic performer and I greatly admire him because he has a
multitude of tricks up his sleeve.''
   Edward Fox, who plays the butler Crichton, said: ``Playing Rex's
role requires a lot of stamina. He has enormous grit and
determination.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Annuschka, the Ford modeling agency's 1988
Supermodel of the World, gave the animals some competition at the
opening of the Central Park Zoo.
   The 5-foot-9 blue-eyed blonde from Czechoslovakia climbed over a
railing around the seal tank to pose for a photographer at the zoo
opening Monday.
   Annuschka, who uses only her first name professionally, says she
would like to follow in the footsteps of the model Paulina, who
also hails from Czechoslovakia.
   ``Paulina is famous in the whole world,'' she said. ``I wouldn't
mind to be like her.''
   Annuschka, who beat out 31 other women for a $250,000 contract
with Ford, was discovered in a search sponsored by Bloomingdale's
and the Daily News.
   In New York for the first time, Annuschka said she wants to
visit the impoverished South Bronx, a spot not on many tourist
lists.
   ``I heard about that place when I was in Germany,'' she said.
``I'm interested to see what it's like.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Country-western singer Crystal Gayle
underwent emergency surgery for a tubal pregnancy and was making a
good recovery Tuesday, a spokeswoman said.
   Miss Gayle, 37, underwent surgery Monday after suffering side
pains and dizziness, said Delinda McNutt, a spokeswoman for the
singer. Miss Gayle's husband, Bill Gatzimos, drove her to the
hospital on Sunday, Ms. McNutt said.
   ``She is doing fine,'' said Ms. McNutt, who spoke on condition
the name of the hospital not be disclosed.
   The singer, noted for her floor-length dark brown hair, is
expected to remain in the hospital until Friday.
   Miss Gayle was to begin a three-week tour Tuesday, but canceled
all appearances, including singing ``America The Beautiful'' Aug.
18 at the close of the Republican National Convention in New
Orleans.
   Miss Gayle, sister of country star Loretta Lynn, is known for
her hits ``Don't It Make My Brown Eyes Blue,'' ``Talkin' In Your
Sleep'' and ``I'll Get Over You.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has thrown out a lawsuit in
which actress Ginger Rogers accused Italian filmmakers of invading
her privacy in the movie ``Ginger and Fred.''
   U.S. District Judge Robert Sweet ruled Monday that the Federico
Fellini film was artistic expression that ``enjoys the full
protection of the First Amendment.''
   Miss Rogers, 77, famous for the musicals in which she danced
with Fred Astaire in the 1930s, filed suit in March 1986 against
the producer, Alberto Grimaldi, and the distributor, MGM-United
Artists. Her complaint seeking $8 million alleged the movie
depicted her in a false light and infringed on her ``public
personality.''
   The movie, starring Marcello Mastroianni and Giulietta Masina,
is about the reunion of two aging Italian music hall dancers who
once were popular for imitating Astaire and Miss Rogers.
</TEXT>
