<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Drought-Rivers 1stLd-Writethru a0618 08-09 0548</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought-Rivers, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0618,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Eight Rivers Set Record Lows in July</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 16th graf pvs, bgng: _The Appalachicola, to CORRECT
spelling of Apalachicola and Chattahoochee</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eight drought-plagued rivers set records for
low water last month, including all-time records in South Carolina
and Wisconsin, the U.S. Geological Survey reported Tuesday.
   The North Fork of the Edisto River at Orangeburg, S.C., averaged
141 million gallons of water per day for the month, the least
amount of water for any month ever measured in that river in 49
years of recordkeeping.
   And on July 15 the Wisconsin River at Muscoda, Wis., recorded
its lowest one-day flow ever at 1.2 billion gallons. That river has
been measured for 75 years.
   Six other rivers, including the once mighty Mississippi, had
their lowest flows for any July on record, the survey reported.
   Even so, July had fewer record lows than the 33 recorded in June.
   ``Rains have brought some spotty improvement in streamflows and
reservoir levels around the country,'' reported James Ziglar,
assistant secretary of interior.
   But, he added, ``the overall water-resources situation remains
one of concern.''
   ``Perhaps most striking, the Mississippi River itself, pipeline
for nearly half the streamflow in the United States, set a new
monthly low, the lowest July in at least 54 years, and at least 13
percent lower than the record low set in June,'' Ziglar said.
   Flow in the Mississippi at Vicksburg, Miss., averaged 108
billion gallons per day during July, 60 percent below the median
for the month. That flow broke the previous low record of 119
billion gallons per day set in July 1934.
   That also meant the Mississippi remained the nation's second
largest river in July, trailing the St. Lawrence, which averaged
159 billion gallons per day at Massena, N.Y. That was 11 percent
below normal for the St. Lawrence.
   Water flows for the remainder of the nation's Big Five rivers in
July were 75.4 billion gallons per day in the Columbia River at The
Dalles, Ore., 58 percent below normal; 28.7 billion gallons a day
in the Missouri at Hermann, Mo., 41 percent below normal; and 19.8
billion in the Ohio at Louisville, Ky., 38 percent below normal.
   In addition to the record at Vicksburg, the Mississippi as
measured at Keokuk, Iowa, also set a record low for July at 10.6
billion gallons a day, 74 percent below normal.
   Besides the Mississippi, Edisto and Wisconsin rivers, records
for low July streamflows were set on:
   _The Chippewa River at Chippewa Falls, Wis., averaged 707
million gallons a day, 9 percent less than the record set in 1910.
The flow was 65 percent below normal for the month.
   _Altahama River at Doctortown, Ga., was 74 percent below normal
with a flow of 1.15 billion gallons per day, lowest in 56 years of
records.
   _The Apalachicola River at Chattahoochee, Fla., was the lowest
in 59 years of recordkeeping, with an average of 3.8 billion
gallons per day.
   _The Sturgeon River at Sidnaw, Mich., recorded a flow of only 5
million gallons per day, lowest in 47 years and 90 percent below
normal.
   _Oconto River at Gillette, Wis., had its lowest July in 76
years, averaging 149 million gallons per day, 47 percent below
normal.
</TEXT>
