<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Paraguay-Babies     08-09 0217</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Paraguay-Babies,0223</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Embassy Says Report of Baby Trafficking is False, Slanderous</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Embassy on Tuesday rejected
as false and slanderous a report that babies were sold to Americans
for adoption and then dismembered, with their hearts and livers
going to organ banks.
   ``There does not exist the slightest evidence ... that any
adopted infant from any part of the world has been used in that
way,'' the embassy said in a statement.
   The statement followed news reports that police raiding a house
last week found seven infants _ presumably born of Brazilian
mothers _ and several pregnant women who apparently intended to
give their babies up for adoption.
   The infants, aged three months to six months, were taken to a
hospital. Police detained three men and a woman.
   Judge Angel Campos denounced the international ``trafficking''
of infants, and speculated that some might be dismembered in the
United States for their organs, which could be sold for hundreds of
dollars.
   The embassy statement said a similar allegation was made in 1987
by Honduras' secretary-general of Social Welfare, Leonardo Villeda
Bermudez, who subsequently acknowledged he had no proof.
   The same allegation later cropped up in Guatemala, but that,
too, was false, the statement said, alleging that communist
newspapers were behind the rumor.
