<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     08-09 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0297</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The American Accordionists Association is
gathered for its 50th anniversary jubilee, and members say those
who only associate their instruments with old Lawrence Welk shows
are full of hot air.
   ``All people see on TV is accordions playing polkas, and they
think that's all the accordions can do,'' said Anthony Chism, a
25-year-old classical-accordion virtuoso from California. ``But
there's so much freedom with the sound. If you could see what's
going on with the air inside the accordion, it would boggle your
mind.''
   At least 1,000 accordionists gathered this week from around the
world for the convention.
   Music store owner Alex Carozza was ready to write off the
instrument in 1980, when it accounted for only 10 percent of his
store's sales.
   Now it accounts for 35 percent, he says.
   ``The young people are beginning to talk accordion again,'' said
Maddelena Belfiore, a New Jersey accordion teacher who is vice
president of the International Confederation of Accordionists.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>KERNVILLE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There wasn't a bathtub in sight for the
first-ever official ``Rubber Ducky Race.''
   Instead, the 150 contestants floated, bobbed and weaved
two-tenths of a mile through the rapids and deep pools of the upper
Kern River about 150 miles north of Los Angeles.
   The Kern Valley Exchange Club raised $2,000 for charity as
businesses and individuals sponsored ducks in Sunday's race at $20
apiece.
   ``I knew he'd win when I bought him,'' Jeannie Vonch said of
winner ``Raunchy Vonchy.''
   ``He was right out front the whole way,'' she said.
   ``People asked me what I credited the duck's speed to, and I
told them wheat germ oil and Cutty Sark,'' she said.
</TEXT>
