<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nagasaki     08-09 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nagasaki,0469</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nagasaki Marks 43rd Anniversary Of Atom Bombing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Church and temple bells tolled in Nagasaki as
thousands of people stopped in the streets Tuesday to remember the
moment 43 years ago when the United States dropped an atomic bomb
on the Japanese city.
   The city's mayor urged the government to clarify whether U.S.
ships are bringing nuclear weapons into Japan.
   At 11:02 a.m., the moment when the bomb exploded in a burst of
blinding light, bells tolled as many people on the streets and in
shopping centers paused for a minute of silence.
   Nagasaki became the target of the world's second atomic attack
on Aug. 9, 1945. The United States dropped the first atomic bomb on
Hiroshima three days earlier. Japan surrendered about a week later
to end World War II.
   At Peace Park, near the point where the bomb exploded, about
20,000 people gathered for an annual service. Under a hot sun,
people poured water over a memorial tablet to recall the cries of
victims suffering from thirst and burns.
   Families presented a list of 2,295 names of bomb victims who
died during the past year, bringing to 77,462 the number of
post-war victims of nuclear radiation. Their names are inscribed on
a vault near the park's peace statue.
   In the evening, about 2,000 Roman Catholics with candles walked
through areas of the city once destroyed by the bombing, a church
official said.
   Officials estimate up to 70,000 people died immediately from the
explosion and the accompanying fire storms and radiation. About
70,000 residents still suffer from side effects of the plutonium
bomb, doctors and social workers say.
   In the bombing of Hiroshima, an estimated 70,000 to 140,000
people died. About 350,000 people in Japan hold certificates
showing they were victims of the atomic bombings in the two cities.
   Since the war Japan has followed a policy of ``three non-nuclear
principles'': no possession, manufacture or introduction into the
country of nuclear weapons.
   Speaking at the ceremony in Peace Park, Nagasaki Mayor Hitoshi
Motoshima criticized his government for allowing U.S. ships to dock
in Japan without verifying whether they carry nuclear weapons.
   ``The Japanese government should independently check whether
U.S. ships are carrying nuclear weapons when they call on Japanese
ports, and make clear that it still is observing the three
non-nuclear principles,'' Motoshima said.
   The Nagasaki bombing destroyed almost everything within a radius
of more than half a mile, including 1,326 buildings and homes. It
also demolished 23,500 homes and buildings outside that radius,
according to a report by the city.
   The ancient port city of 450,000, has been rebuilt, with modern
office towers and tree-lined avenues replacing the rubble-strewn
landscape.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
