<DOCNO> AP880809-0134 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-88 2008EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Amish-Fine     08-09 0274</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Amish-Fine,0282</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Amish Man Who Broke Sign Law Offered Community Service Work</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRESTON, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge has given an Amish man two weeks
to perform five hours of community service or face a charge of
criminal contempt for refusing to display a slow-moving-vehicle
sign on his horse-drawn buggy.
   The charge could mean a $700 fine or up to 90 days in jail.
   Fillmore County District Court Judge O. Russell Olson's ruling
Monday postponed action on a contempt charge stemming from Dan D.
Hershberger's failure to pay a $20 fine. At an Aug. 29 hearing,
Olson said he would determine whether Hershberger performed the
community service within the Amish community.
   ``There's no sense in getting into criminal contempt for
non-payment of a $20 fine,'' the judge said.
   Minnesota law requires non-motorized vehicles to display an
orange sign outlined in red at night, and to carry it at all times.
The Amish, who contend that displaying the bright signs is against
their religion, are allowed to use a black triangle outlined in
white on their buggies and wagons during the daytime.
   Last year, another judge ruled that Hershberger violated a state
law for not having the proper sign on his horse-drawn buggy.
   The judge stayed imposition of a $20 fine on condition that
Hershberger not violate that law during the next six months.
   But Hershberger was arrested a second time and ordered to pay
the fine. He refused. Prosecutors in April charged him with
criminal contempt of court, a misdemeanor.
   Olson said he modified the original sentence to permit community
service because that option had been available in other cases
involving Amish defendants.
</TEXT>
