<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-88 1548EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Gulf 1stLd-Writethru a0680 08-09 0653</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Gulf, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0680,620</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US May Provide Logistical Support for UN Group</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds 3 grafs with new convoy, no reports of fighting</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States is prepared to provide
logistical support to the United Nations peacekeeping force that
will monitor a cease-fire between Iran and Iraq to take effect Aug.
20, the administration said Tuesday.
   Shortly after the U.N. Security Council approved the
establishment of the 350-member force, State Department spokeswoman
Phyllis Oakley said none of the 15 council members would contribute
troops to the force, but ``we intend to be as helpful as we can.''
   The force will be funded out of U.N. peacekeeping accounts
through special assessments.
   At the White House, spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the
administration welcomed the cease-fire announcement Monday by U.N.
Secretary General Javier Perez de Cuellar and would bear ``its fair
share of the cost'' of the observer force, including transportation
and equipment.
   ``It is our understanding that there will be neither U.S. nor
Soviet troops in the observer force,'' he added.
   ``It has been a major aim of the United States to bring this war
to an end,'' Fitzwater said. ``We now look forward to the
implementation . . . in all its parts'' of a U.N. Security Council
resolution calling for such a cease-fire.
   Mrs. Oakley expressed hope that the cease-fire would lead to
rapid progress toward a final settlement and to the restoration of
peace and security in the Persian Gulf region.
   ``We strongly support the secretary general's call for both
sides to exercise maximum military restraint until the cease-fire
is in place,'' she said.
   The Iran-Iraq situation was the subject of a meeting late Monday
involving Deputy Secretary of State John Whitehead and an Arab
League delegation headed by Saudi Foreign Minister Saud Al-Faisal.
   It was agreed by participants at the meeting that the ``states
in the region have a vested interest in getting Iran and Iraq back
on their feet,'' said a U.S. official, insisting on anonymity.
   Earlier Tuesday, Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci said the
United States will withdraw most of its naval forces from the
Persian Gulf only when it is convinced that the cease-fire has
taken effect.
   ``I would think we'd have to wait until the cease-fire actually
takes hold, and probably after that a prudent period to make sure
that it stays in effect,'' Carlucci said on NBC-TV's ``Today''
program.
   ``We have no desire to keep our ships, our people, there any
longer than necessary. At the same time, we don't want to put them
in any danger,'' he said in a separate interview on ``CBS This
Morning.''
   The United States has maintained a force of close to 30 warships
in the Persian Gulf to guard against attacks on oil tankers and
other neutral shipping by Iran and Iraq. Since June 1987, many
Kuwaiti tankers have carried American flags and been protected in
convoys of U.S. naval ships.
   More recently, the U.S. Navy was ordered to protect all neutral
shipping that comes under attack in the gulf.
   The United States will probably maintain a presence of three to
five ships in the region _ about what it has had there since the
1940s _ ``but that depends on the threat,'' Carlucci said on CBS.
   At the Pentagon, meantime, chief spokesman Dan Howard said the
U.S. Navy had completed its 54th convoy operation of the year early
Tuesday, with the guided-missile frigate Nicholas escorting the
reflagged Kuwaiti tanker Chesapeake City up the gulf to Kuwait.
   ``The journey was uneventful and there was no unusual air or sea
activity reported,'' Howard said.
   The spokesman said the Defense Department had not received any
reports of fighting Tuesday between Iran and Iraq either on land or
water, but added: ``I do not have a definitive report that all
hostilities have ceased. I can't speak to that one way or another.''
</TEXT>
