<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Congressman-Cuba     08-09 0179</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Congressman-Cuba,160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuba Reissues Visa to Rep. Mica</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Dan Mica, D-Fla., who was refused
permission by Cuban authorities last month to visit the island, has
been granted a visa and planned to fly to Havana on Tuesday, his
office said.
   Cuba abruptly revoked the visas it had given to Mica and several
aides last month in retaliation for a reception held by a U.S.
diplomat in Havana which was attended by human rights activists.
   Mica had intended to go to Cuba to investigate possible security
violations at the U.S. Interests Section in the Swiss Embassy in
Havana. He is chairman of the House Foreign Affairs subcommittee on
international operations.
   The State Department protested the cancellation of the visas,
calling it a ``great discourtesy'' to a member of Congress.
   An aide to Mica said the visas were reissued without explanation.
   Mica decided to visit the Interests Section, which represents
U.S. interests in Cuba in the absence of formal diplomatic
relations, after four U.S. Marine guards were withdrawn in June for
fraternizing with two Cuban women.
</TEXT>
