<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-88 1601EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Gulf-Iran     08-09 0641</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf-Iran,0660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>In Streets of Tehran, A Wary Mood</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEHRAN, Iran (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's acting commander-in-chief, Hashemi
Rafsanjani, said Tuesday his nation is seeking a comprehensive
peace but must remain vigilant in the face of Iraqi ``mischief.''
   He reflected the relieved but wary mood on the streets of the
war-weary capital.
   Rafsanjani said Iran won't initiate any military actions against
Iraq in light of the U.N. secretary-general setting Aug. 20 as the
cease-fire date in the war.
   But he said that the soldiers should maintain their vigil
against possible Iraqi attacks.
   ``The armed forces should not, from today, be the initiators of
any kind of military and armed moves,'' said Rafsanjani, who also
is speaker of Iran's parliament, in a statement read over Tehran
Radio. ``But just like always, (Iran) will be ready to give an
appropriate response to the mischiefs of the enemy.''
   Rafsanjani's message said that the Islamic Republic ``has
decided to create a lasting and comprehensive peace in the region
and will continue its path,'' but that it is faced ``with enemies
whose claims, promises and agreements cannot be trusted.''
   He said the Iraqis ``might resort to any agression and crime
during the few days left until the cease-fire date and even after
that.''
   ``Islamic Iran is proud before God for performing its holy duty
of protecting justice, and the Iraqi Baathists should answer God
and the people as to why they kindled the fire of war and what tney
gained from it,'' Rafsanjani said.
   In the streets of Tehran, Iranians greeted the announcement of
the cease-fire date in the 8-year-old Iraq-Iran war with a sense of
relief mixed with skepticism that it will mean lasting peace.
   Most learned that the shooting is to stop only at 7 a.m., when
the news came over Tehran Radio. The announcement at the United
Nations in New York came to late for the principal morning
newspaper, Jomhuri Islami.
   ``Hopefully it means peace,'' said a hotel employee in the Laleh
Hotel, the former Intercontinental. ``But celebrating? After so
many martyrs?''
   Another English-speaking man who introduced himself as a
telephone operator was smiling broadly. ``I just learned it 10
minutes ago. Sure, I will celebrate tonight with my family. I will
have a bottle of coke. You know, there is no drinking in our
country.''
   In the sprawling bazaar, the mood was still depressed among some
who lost heavily in speculating on a further rise of the free
dollar rate against the rial. The dollar had dropped to almost one
fourth of its value two months ago but seemed to have stabilized at
about one third.
   ``But most businessmen here think that things will be better in
a few months and that people's life will be much easier,'' one
merchant said.
   A Western diplomat who declined to be identified said
expectations have been running high among residents after Iraq
accepted the cease-fire without precondition.
   ``They will be disappointed, normalization will take much
time,'' he said.
   At a gas station where cars were filled up without having to
wait, a man said, ``Let us hope that this will hold, that there
will not be new fighting after two weeks.''
   The reaction was much more subdued than in Iraq, where people
poured in the streets in the middle of the night to celebrate their
``victory'' and the government declared a three-day holiday.
   A French-speaker, who said he studied political science at
Tehran University before he joined the communications services,
said ``The Americans will come back now, I am sure. I don't think
it will take more than a few months.''
   But on the 15-foot barbed-wire topped walls surrounding the vast
grounds of the former U.S. Embassy, bold English and Farsi writing
painted years ago still boasted: ``We will make America face a
severe defeat.''
</TEXT>
