<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghanistan     08-09 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0483</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Abandon Afghanistan's Second-Largest City</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nearly 7,000 Soviet troops have
abandoned Kandahar, which used to be Afghanistan's second-largest
city, leaving the devastated provincial capital in the hands of
Afghan forces, diplomats said Tuesday.
   Most of the 6,750 Red Army troops were evacuated from Kandahar
by air Aug. 4-7, but a huge column of armor and heavy equipment
continues to wind its way cautiously north through western
Afghanistan, according to the reports.
   Western diplomatic sources in Islamabad, quoting witnesses, said
the last soldier _ an officer _ drove his jeep up to a waiting
Ilyushin-76 transport plane, walked up the ramp then tossed his
keys back in the seat for the Afghans to drive away.
   Kandahar's population of 200,000 has dwindled to 20,000 in the
10 years of war, according to Western estimates.
   Kabul's Marxist government recently admitted that nearly 70
percent of the city's buildings has ``been damaged or razed to the
ground.''
   If Moscow sticks to the withdrawal timetable set forth in the
Geneva accord signed in April, half of its more than 100,000 troops
should be out of Afghanistan by Aug. 15.
   Western diplomats, quoting dispatches from Kabul, said Kandahar
has been left to 3,000 ``young and apprehensive'' Afghan troops to
face continuing rocket and ground attacks by determined Moslem
guerrillas.
   The Kabul government has invited 50 foreign correspondents to
the capital to witness the ceremonial withdrawal of the first
Kabul-based Soviet units. It marks the Aug. 15 halfway point of a
total pullout from Afghanistan to be completed by Feb. 15.
   Diplomats said the two departing 500-man, 100-vehicle units are
just a fraction of the 20,000 Soviet troops believed to be
defending the heavily fortified city.
   Large units of Soviet and Afghan troops moved west into the
Paghman plains last week to dislodge 4,000 Mujahedeen insurgents
who threatened to disrupt the Aug. 4-7 visit of Soviet Foreign
Minister Eduard Shevardnadze and the Aug. 15 pullout ceremonies,
diplomats said.
   Heavy fighting has cost about 100 lives on each side, according
to their estimates.
   Security was so tight during Shevardnadze's stay that upon his
departure, his Tu-154 plane was protected by eight Mi-24 helicopter
gunships, plus jets above the cloud cover, all dropping clusters of
flares to ward off any guerrilla anti-aircraft missiles.
   Witnesses said the plane corkscrewed eight times skyward in a
steep climb before it reached a safe altitude to set a bearing for
Moscow.
   Western diplomatic sources said they believed his visit was to
reassure Afghan communists of the Kremlin's continued support and
to report on his talks with Pakistani Foreign Minister Sahabzada
Yaqub Khan, whose country backs the guerrillas with Washington's
help.
   Western, Pakistani and guerrilla sources predict Kabul's
communist regime will fall quickly in the absence of Soviet
military might.
</TEXT>
