<1ST_LINE>r a AM-JudgeAcker 1stLd-Writethru a0612 08-09 0795</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Judge Acker, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0612,0814</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jurist Scolded In Klan Case Offers To Ban Himself From All
Government Cases</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 3rd graf with 3 grafs to update with U.S. attorney's
filing Tuesday; picks up 4th graf pvs, `During the...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By HOYT HARWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge who was chastised by a
higher court for showing bias in favor of Ku Klux Klansmen in a
race violence case has offered to ban himself from litigation
involving the federal government.
   But so far, U.S. District Judge William M. Acker Jr., 60, has
not drawn any public call for such blanket disqualification.
   Acker, appointed to the bench by President Reagan in 1982,
scheduled a hearing on the issue for Friday.
   U.S. Attorney Frank Donaldson on Tuesday filed a response on
behalf of the government in which he said the United States ``has
at this time insufficient information to determine and no reason to
believe that Judge Acker's proposed general recusal is either
necessary or appropriate.''
   Donaldson, who said the Justice Department will not be
represented at the hearing, said it is the government's view ``that
the matter of recusal is better left for consideration on a
case-by-case basis.''
   Acker's rulings against the Justice Department in the Klan
litigation prompted the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals to
remove him from the case in a bluntly worded order.
   ``During the course of this litigation,'' wrote 11th Circuit
Judge Frank M. Johnson of Montgomery, ``Judge Acker's position has
become hardened against the government, and he has evidenced a
commitment that clearly reflects that he is no longer able to view
these cases impartially.''
   Acker had ruled that the actions of several Klansmen, accused of
violating the civil rights of marchers in a violent confrontation
at Decatur in 1979, did not justify what Acker said were improper
tactics used by the Southern Poverty Law Center in Montgomery,
which Acker branded ``a counter-vigilante group.''
   The center had sued the Klansmen, then gave their testimony to
the Justice Department, which used it to obtain indictments against
them. Acker ruled the testimony inadmissible evidence and then did
not follow 11th Circuit instructions to admit it as evidence.
   Morris Dees, director of the center, said his organization would
take no position on Acker's qualifications to preside over
government cases.
   Dees, whose center over nearly two decades has handled a number
of highly publicized civil rights and death penalty cases, said
center attorneys will not attend Friday's hearing.
   ``We've never had any experience with Judge Acker in any other
case,'' Dees said.
   Kenneth J. Gomany, one of the attorneys for the Klansmen, said
he plans to attend the hearing ``to submit any kind of briefs in
support'' of the judge.
   ``I think he is a good and fair judge and he's ruled against our
clients and against the government on occasion. More often than
not, he's ruled against our clients. All in all, he's been
impartial,'' said Gomany.
   ``This court is neither seeking praise nor condemnation,'' Acker
wrote in June when he scheduled the hearing, ``but feels it is
necessary that it create a forum for frank and serious discussion
of a very serious subject, namely: `Should a judge whose position
is hardened against the government sit on the government's cases?'
''
   Acker's clerk said she was not aware of any briefs filed in
advance of the hearing.
   The controversy began in 1979 in Decatur, when a march by the
Southern Christian Leadership Conference ended in a bloody
confrontation with Klansmen, who beat police with clubs when
officers tried to keep them away from the marchers. Shots were
exchanged and several people were injured, none fatally.
   An initial Justice Department investigation ended without
indictments. But the Southern Poverty Law Center filed a civil
action against 50 Klansmen, seeking financial damages and bans on
Klan actions.
   The center took testimony from Klansmen, then made it available
to federal investigators, who used it to obtain indictments against
nine Klansmen in 1984. Acker, however, blocked the testimony,
saying it was inadmissible in the government's case.
   Acker said the Klan is ``a vigilante group which undoubtedly,
from time to time, violates the constitutional rights of citizens.''
   ``However, one vigilante group does not justify the creation and
operation of (a) counter-vigilante group in violation of the
constitutional rights of the first group.''
   ``To tolerate a rape of the rights of the Klan would be a
recognition that some sort of double standard exists for the
application of constitutional protections,'' he said.
   The government appealed and the 11th Circuit ruled that the
testimony should not be suppressed.
   The 11th Circuit ordered Acker's removal from the case when the
government filed a second appeal, arguing that he had failed to
follow the circuit court's directions.
</TEXT>
