<HEAD>Clinton Speech Remembered</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis, the
Democratic nominee for president, and Arkansas Gov. Bill Clinton,
who nominated him, took part in a light moment as the National
Governors' Association closed out its meeting Wednesday
   Dukakis and Clinton stepped to the podium to make a presentation
to Gov. Thomas Kean of New Jersey, who will be the keynote speaker
at the Republican National Convention next week in New Orleans.
   Throughout the meeting, governors needled Clinton about his long
speech at the Democratic convention.
   Dukakis turned to Kean and presented him with a plastic shopping
bag and said, ``Just in case you have the same kind of problem he
(Clinton) did, we thought you might want to take this.''
   Inside the bag was an hourglass.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Wright To Presidential Candidates: Steer Clear of Dirty Politics</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Speaker Jim Wright on Tuesday called on
the presidential candidates to keep their campaigns from ``going in
the gutter.''
   ``The American people deserve a serious discussion of serious
issues,'' said Wright, D-Texas. They get disgusted, he said, when
politicians ``descend to the level of sideshow barkers or rumor
mongers.''
   ``I hope that we can rescue it from going in the gutter,''
Wright told reporters at his regular press briefing.
   ``The people are entitled to a high level of debate, not
impugning motives of one another,'' Wright said.
   Wright, who was chairman of the Democratic National Convention
last month, is under investigation by the House Ethics Committee,
which is looking into allegations of violations of House rules in
his personal financial dealings.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>GOP Convention Information Only a Phone Call Away</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If you can't get to a newspaper, radio or
television to learn the latest Republican National Convention news,
starting Friday you'll be able to get it by picking up the phone.
   A 24-hour service, RNC-INFO _ 762-4636 _ will tell callers about
convention schedules and even information about traffic jams and
storm clouds in New Orleans.
   Callers will also be privy to world news, sports, financial news
and the national weather.
   The service is being provided free to the public by BellSouth
Corp. The company provided a similar service for the Democratic
National Convention in Atlanta, but it was limited to the press, a
spokeswoman said. That service received about 10,000 calls.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>N.C. Companies Sending Pork Rinds to New Orleans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENSBORO, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two North Carolina food companies will
flood the Republican National Convention next week with a
Southern-fried snack that Vice President George Bush says is his
favorite _ pork rinds.
   Carolina Fine Snacks of Greensboro and Goodmark Foods of Raleigh
are producing 13,000 bags of Grand Old Porkrinds for the delegates.
   Bush's taste for fried pork skins was made public last month
when reporters asked him how the real man differed from his
less-than-hearty image.
   ``I like pork rinds, but that doesn't fit the mold,'' Bush
responded.
   Labels on the special convention pork rinds carry the warning,
``Not to be consumed by wimps.''
   ``We thought this would be fun to do, and we were hungry for the
exposure,'' said Phil Kosak, a co-owner of Carolina Fine Snacks.
``We produce high quality pork skins. Of course, some people
consider that a liability. Some say the worse the quality, the
better the pork skin.''
</TEXT>
