<1ST_LINE>r i AM-NATO-Carlucci     08-09 0644</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-NATO-Carlucci,0661</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Officials, Back From Moscow, See No Sign Of Soviet Military
Reduction</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. officials saw no signs during last
week's trip to Moscow of a reduction in Soviet military forces or
spending, despite Soviet assurances of a new defense policy, an
American official said Monday.
   The official, who accompanied U.S. Defense Secretary Frank
Carlucci on the trip but who spoke on condition of anonymity, said,
``It does not seem to us evident yet that there is any change in
force structure or resources that the Soviets are committing to
their military effort.''
   The official was in Brussels to brief the North Atlantic Council
on Carlucci's four days of talks with Soviet Defense Minister
Dmitri T. Yazov and unprecedented tours of secret Soviet military
bases. The council, the highest decision-making body of the North
Atlantic Treaty Organization, is made up of representatives of the
16 countries in the alliance.
   The U.S. official told reporters the Americans discussed the
Soviets' so-called defensive doctrine, under which emphasis would
be placed on defending territory rather than seizing or holding it.
   ``When we look at their forces,'' he said, ``the things that
bother us for example is their heavy emphasis'' on tanks,
artillery, engineer bridging units and airborne forces.
   He said these are the type of troops that would be used to grab
territory.
   ``Now,'' he said, ``the Soviets say they are changing to a
defensive doctrine and they don't have that objective. ... We made
clear to them that we must pay attention specifically to what their
capabilities are.''
   ``We would welcome seeing changes ... away from those kinds of
forces that would help us relieve our concerns about the offensive
capabilities of the Soviet army,'' he said.
   He did say, however, that Soviet officials provided some
evidence that military exercises ``seem to be shifting ... to
reflect'' the new doctrine.
   ``We don't dismiss the utility of that or changes of that kind
on the Soviet side,'' he said.
   Soviet authorities also told their American counterparts they
were putting together a better accounting of their defense
spending, the official said.
   ``We don't have anything concrete as to whether or not they are
in fact applying less resources to the military or not right now,''
he said. ``We don't see evidence of that in terms of what you can
see in their own production output and other efforts.''
   He said Soviet officials did not dispute U.S. estimates that
Moscow spends 15 percent to 17 percent of its economic output on
the military. U.S. defense spending amounts to about 6 percent of
the gross national product, the total value of goods and services
produced by the economy.
   The official said the two delegations also discussed ways to
prevent accidental shootings or other serious incidents between the
two countries' forces during peacetime. In 1985, a U.S. military
observer was shot and killed in East Germany while making what
American authorities said was a proper tour of the area.
   The first meeting of a working group on preventing such
incidents was scheduled to meet in the fall, the official said. No
date or place has yet been set.
   This was the third meeting between Carlucci and Yazov. They met
last March in Switzerland and again at the Moscow summit in June.
   The U.S. official said the United States was not expecting
dramatic changes in its military ties with the Soviet Union.
   ``It would be, I think, unfounded to anticipate a sea change in
our relationships with them in the military area,'' he said.
   ``These discussions in and of themselves, do not change the
security situation that we have to face. ... We find no grounds in
these contacts we have had for unilaterally altering our military
structure or our defense posture or the need for readiness or
defense spending.''
</TEXT>
