<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-88 1735EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-OceanDumping     08-09 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ocean Dumping,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Votes Ban on Dumping of Sludge in Atlantic Ocean</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Medical Waste Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate, spurred by fears about sludge and
medical waste washing onto East Coat beaches, voted 97-0 on Tuesday
passage of a bill which bans the dumping of sludge in the Atlantic
Ocean.
   The action sends the measure to the House, where a similar bill
is on the floor awaiting final action.
   The bill bans the dumping of municipal sludge off the coasts of
New York and New Jersey after 1991 and orders the closing of a
sludge dump site 106 miles off the New Jersey coast. That location
is the only site where sludge currently can be legally dumped.
   The site is used by six sewage authorities in New Jersey and
three in New York, including the city of New York.
   Before approving the bill, the Senate added an amendment by Sen.
Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., which bans the disposal of all medical
waste in oceans or streams. It also approved another amendment, by
Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J., providing a five-year prison
sentence for anyone caught violating that ban.
   Both amendments were approved by voice vote without any audible
dissent.
   Dodd told his colleagues that because of medical waste washing
up on his state's beaches, ``last week, virtually every Connecticut
beach was shut down because of medical waste during one of the
hottest spells in the state's history.''
   ``We're moving closer to the day when we'll stop using the ocean
as a sewer,'' said Lautenberg, one of the co-sponsors. ``Sludge
dumping is a throwaway approach to our waste problem and
contributes to the overall ocean pollution problem.''
   Sen. Bill Bradley, D-N.J., agreed. ``We're treating the oceans
as a cesspool,'' he told the Senate.
   Congress first ordered an end to the ocean dumping of sewage
sludge in 1972. Five years laters, Congress directed that the
dumping be ended by 1981. But the nine municipalities in New York
and New Jersey successfully sued in federal court to ignore that
deadline.
   ``We need a firm deadline, in the law, to ban the ocean dumping
of sewage sludge,'' said Lautenberg. ``Only then will alternatives
be put in place. Only then will the dumping stop.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880809-0151 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-88 1740EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-GallupPoll     08-09 0472</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gallup Poll,470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gallup Poll Funds Smaller Dukakis Lead</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis slipped to a
seven-point lead over Republican George Bush in a Gallup poll
released Tuesday, relinquishing the boost in support he gained from
the Democratic National Convention.
   Dukakis received 49 percent backing in the survey of 1,004
registered voters, compared to 42 percent for Bush. The national
poll, conducted Friday through Sunday, had a three-point margin of
error.
   A Gallup poll two weeks ago, just after the convention, gave
Dukakis a 17-point lead, and he maintained that lead in a CBS
News-New York Times poll done July 31-Aug. 3. Before the
convention, Dukakis led by six.
   Poll analysts have characterized the double-digit Dukakis lead
as a temporary bounce created by news coverage of the Democratic
convention, and said they expected Bush to recover the ground as
the race progressed.
   ``It was just a question of when it would happen,'' said Larry
Hugick, political poll chief for Gallup. ``It has happened.'' Next,
he said, if history is a guide, Bush should draw even with Dukakis
after the GOP convention.
   Analysts affiliated with both parties reacted cautiously to the
suggestion Dukakis' lead may have slipped even before the
Republicans' convention next week.
   ``I expect fluctuations back and forth. Those things don't
surprise me right now,'' said Irwin ``Tubby'' Harrison, the Dukakis
campaign pollster. ``I'm not paying a lot of attention to the ups
and downs in polls.''
   ``It's interesting because it's the first poll showing movement
in that direction,'' said Lance Torrance, a leading Republican
pollster. ``But it needs to be confirmed by at least one or two
other national polls.''
   Torrance hypothesized that the finding could simply reflect
public interest in Bush's impending selection of a running mate.
   ``We can conjecture that some of the vice presidential naming
game has advanced the normal convention bounce ahead of time,'' he
said. ``There's been no spectacular event that could have caused
this.''
   Torrance said the question is whether Bush simply rebounded
early, or the Republican convention will propel him to an even
closer race. Measuring from Dukakis' big post-convention lead, he
said, ``Bush has to get seven points back just to be 10 points
down. To go into Labor Day 10 points down still gives you a
relatively formidable task.''
   Harrison, similarly, said the polls will take on greater
significance after Labor Day, when voters begin to know the
candidates better and to focus more on the issues. In that vein, he
said, Dukakis' early lead meant little.
   ``These are not men, even yet, about whom the public knows a
great deal,'' Harrison said. ``There's a different national poll
out every day. It's subject to great discussion. But I've found in
the past it doesn't make much sense.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
