<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Angola     08-09 0443</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Angola,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Official Says Internal Angolan Peace Needed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A top State Department official said Tuesday
the absence of progress toward an internal political settlement in
Angola could block final agreement on the withdrawal of all foreign
forces from that country.
   While expressing optimism based on recent recent talks among
outside parties, Assistant Secretary of State Chester Crocker said
the unresolved civil war in Angola ``could hamper and postone''
efforts to reach a troop withdrawal agreement.
   Crocker spoke as South Africa prepared to begin a three-week
pullout of its troops in Angola on Wednesday under terms of a
cease-fire reached with Angola and Cuba.
   The accord, in which Crocker has served as mediator, also sets a
Nov. 1 starting date for a U.N. plan to grant independence to
Namibia from South African colonial rule.
   Angola's Marxist government has been fighting anti-communist
guerrillas for the past 13 years. That issue is not formally on
agenda for the series of talks that began in May involving South
Africa, Cuba, Angola and the United States. The main purpose of the
talks has been the withdrawal of foreign forces.
   The parties next will attempt to reach agreement on a timetable
for the withdrawal of the estimated 50,000 Cuban troops from
Angola. South Africa has linked its withdrawal plan to Cuba's
consent to an early pullout of its troops.
   ``It would be tragic if this moment is not seized to bring peace
to Angolans themselves as well as bringing peace to southwestern
Africa in the sense of ending the cross border conflict,'' Crocker
told a news conference.
   He said it would mean continued Soviet military support for the
Angolan government and continued American backing for the UNITA
rebels.
   The absence of progress toward an internal settlement in Angola,
he added, would have a ``direct bearing'' on the willingness of
Cuba and South Africa to compromise on the troop withdrawal
question.
   Crocker said he has made it clear to the parties that the United
States does not look on its support for UNITA as ``something to be
traded as a bargaining chip'' in the negotiations on Cuban
withdrawal.
   The United States has been providing the UNITA rebels with about
$15 million in assistance annually. Crocker said the Soviets,
meanwhile, have been sending about $1 billion a year in military
aid to their Angolan ally.
   The administration has strongly supported the concept of
national reconciliation talks between UNITA and the Angolan
government. But Angolan authorities thus far have maintained that
the best solution is for the UNITA forces to surrender their arms
and take part in a national reconstruction effort.
</TEXT>
