<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Democrats-Deregulation     08-09 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Democrats-Deregulation,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Democrats Say Reagan Deregulation Efforts Went Too Far</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Democratic leaders accused the Reagan
administration Tuesday of allowing its efforts to deregulate the
economy to go so far that the safety of American consumers is being
threatened.
   In a report released the week before the Republican National
Convention in New Orleans, the Democrats accused the administration
of lax enforcement of laws, inadequate staffing and financing of
regulatory agencies, and a failure to oversee industry aggressively.
   The study cited problems with the airline, railroad, banking and
maritime industries as well with children's products, food and
workplace safety, the environment, drug abuse and fire safety.
   ``We are at greater risk today when we eat, travel, go the
beach, drink water, deposit money in the bank or buy toys for our
children than we were seven and a half years ago,'' said Rep. Dan
Glickman, D-Kan., who oversaw the House Task Force on Safety that
produced the study.
   Among the report's conclusions were that Reagan has not
sufficiently financed the Coast Guard, kept up with expansion of
the airline industry or actively enforced consumer protection laws.
   ``Our society has paid an enormous price for this
administration's ideological attempts to undo a century's worth of
consumer protection,'' said Rep. Tony Coelho of California, the
House Democratic whip.
   At their news conference on the report, Democrats released a
statement from Michael Dukakis, their party's presidential
candidate, who pledged that if elected he would ``restore to
America's families the safety and protection they deserve.''
   Transportation Secretary Jim Burnley criticized the study.
   ``The highly partisan attack today by members of the House Task
Force on Safety was full of inaccuracies and distortions,'' he said
in a written response.
   He blamed congressional Democrats for not providing adequate
budgets for the Coast Guard or the Federal Aviation Administration.
</TEXT>
