<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-88 1805EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Shultz-Attack     08-09 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz-Attack,0472</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Department Sends Investigators</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER McFARREN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LA PAZ, Bolivia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State Department specialists will help
investigate the bombing of the motorcade carrying Secretary of
State George P. Shultz, the U.S. Embassy said Tuesday.
   A leftist guerrilla group calling itself the Simon Bolivar
Commando claimed responsibility for the Monday explosion, which
investigators said they believed was intended to frighten rather
than kill. Three cars were damaged but no one was injured.
   CIA Director William H. Webster said drug traffickers probably
were behind the attack.
   ``In terms of the way it was done, and the amount of explosives
that were used, it ... probably came from narcotics dealers who are
protesting the vigorous legislation and action the Bolivian
government is taking,'' Webster told reporters during a visit to
Toronto, Canada.
   He said the CIA had no specific warnings of an attack on Shultz,
but ``there was a lot of security down there.''
   Shultz flew to Costa Rica from La Paz on Tuesday, with a stop in
Santa Cruz, Bolivia, to meet with former President Hugo Banzer.
   Police said the bomb consisted of several sticks of dynamite
buried by the roadside and connected to a detonator by more than 40
yards of cable. The explosion hurled rocks and chunks of pavement
at cars in the motorcade, only four of which were armored.
   One of those damaged was the armored car carrying Shultz's wife,
Helena.
   Callers to local news agencies, purporting to speak for the
Simon Bolivar Commando, described the group as ``anti-imperialist
and indigenous.''
   They also claimed responsibility in its name for a bombing
earlier this year at the home of the La Paz jail warden and an
explosion during a visit by King Juan Carlos of Spain in April 1987.
   U.S. and Bolivian investigators said they had information on the
group and believe it is responsible for bank robberies and bombings.
   Other anonymous callers claimed responsibility on behalf of a
group called the Pablo Zarate Wilca, but police discounted the
claim.
   Bolivia has had few instances of political violence in recent
years. The few bombings reported generally have caused no injuries.
   Labor and left-wing political groups had condemned the Shultz
visit as interference in Bolivia's internal affairs.
   Farmers and labor have criticized U.S. aid in fighting the drug
trade and reducing the coca leaf crop because it threatens the
livelihoods of nearly 350,000 farmers who grow coca, the raw
material for cocaine.
   A Bolivian law that took effect two weeks ago would phase out
production on 90 percent of coca plantations and impose stiff
penalties on cocaine producers and traffickers.
   The U.S. government has 40 military trainers, drug enforcement
and border patrol agents working with Bolivian police in the
anti-drug campaign.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880809-0156 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-88 1808EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-DroughtRelief     08-09 0601</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drought Relief,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Approves $3.9 Billion Drought Relief Package</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House approved a $3.9 billion aid package
for drought-stricken farmers Tuesday and sent the measure to
President Reagan, who made known he intends to sign it.
   ``We have kept the faith,'' House Agriculture Committee Chairman
E. ``Kika'' de la Garza, D-Texas, said as the House approved the
bill, 383-18. ``To all who will be helped by this legislation, our
promise has been kept.''
   The House devoted only brief debate to the measure, which
emerged from a House-Senate conference committee last week and won
Senate approval on Monday. Congress raced to put the legislation on
Reagan's desk before it begins a three-week break Friday.
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater told reporters hours
earlier there was no doubt that Reagan will sign the measure.
   Provisions call for government payments to farmers who have lost
more than 35 percent of their crops because of drought, hail,
excessive moisture or related damage, such as that caused by
insects. The payments would be equal to 65 percent of their losses
over the 35 percent threshhold level.
   Additional payments would be available for the farmers hardest
hit by the blazing sun and lack of rainfall that have darkened
fields in the midcontinent.
   Farmers who have received government income-support payments in
advance would not have to repay them in many cases under the
legislation.
   Those receiving payments would be required to purchase federal
crop insurance for their 1989 crops.
   The measure would make feed assistance available for producers
of many varieties of livestock, including cattle, sheep, goats,
pigs, poultry, horses used for food or in food production and fish
used for food.
   Bills involving major farm subsidies have come in for
substantial criticism on fiscal grounds from urban lawmakers in
recent years. But the drought measure escaped such complaints for
the most part.
   Rep. Bob Walker, R-Pa., did complain about a $5.5 million
authorization contained in the measure for a temperature control
system on the Sacremento River near Shasta Dam in California to aid
salmon spawning.
   ``So the bill is going to take care of yuppies, too, and make
sure their salmon mousse supply is not interfered with?'' Walker
said. He grumbled that the public is ``sick and tired of Congress
using every sort of emergency to pork barrel.''
   De la Garza replied that the drought could be even worse in
California next year than it is now.
   The legislation is a bipartisan product that was produced in
record time _ about six weeks _ with lawmakers hurrying to finish
their work and win the president's approval before any second
thoughts about the expense set in or the bill accumulated so many
special-interest provisions that it would be impossible to pass.
   ``This bill is the product of a tremendous concerted effort to
produce relief for drought-stricken farmers,'' said Rep. Edward R.
Madigan, R-Ill., the ranking Republican on the House Agriculture
Committee.
   Lawmakers and the administration believe the measure can be paid
for with funds that the government will save because of the drought.
   Income-support payments, known to farmers as deficiency
payments, increase in proportion to the size of the producer's crop
yield. The drought has reduced these yields and thus slashed the
amount that the government will be required to spend.
   By some estimates, the savings could be as much as $7 billion.
   Farmers whose yields are reduced by more than 75 percent will
come in for increased government payments under the legislation.
   These payments will be equal to 90 percent of losses over that
75 percent level.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880809-0157 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-88 1809EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-GulfWar-Glance     08-09 0480</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gulf War-Glance,0509</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Summary of Gulf News</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A cease-fire is scheduled to begin Aug. 20 in the 8-year-old
Iran-Iraq war, which has killed or wounded more than 1 million
people. Here, at a glance, are developments Tuesday in the efforts
to end the war:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>UNITED NATIONS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The financially strapped United Nations created a $74 million
observer corps to monitor the truce between Iran and Iraq, but
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar said, ``I simply do not
have the money'' to pay for it.
   Marrack Goulding, undersecretary-general in charge of
peacekeeping operations, said the General Assembly probably would
be summoned to special session this week to assess the membership
for funds.
   Twenty-five countries will provide 350 unarmed observers. The
five permanent Security Council members _ the United States,
Britain, China, France and the Soviet Union _ will not provide
personnel because the United Nations wants to avoid involvement by
the major powers.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>IRAQ</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   In Baghdad, state television announced Monday's cease-fire
declaration after midnight, declaring victory in the war and three
days of celebration. Fireworks exploded over the Tigris River and
tens of thousands of rounds of ammunition were fired into the air.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>IRAN</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Iranians greeted the announcement of the cease-fire date with a
sense of relief mixed with skepticism that it will mean lasting
peace.
   In Tehran, Iran's acting commander-in-chief, Hashemi Rafsanjani,
said his nation is seeking peace but must remain vigilant in the
face of Iraqi ``mischief.'' Rafsanjani said Iran won't initiate any
military actions, but soldiers should maintain their vigil against
possible attacks.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>U.S.-GULF</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   At the White House, spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the
administration welcomed the cease-fire announcement and would bear
``its fair share of the cost'' of the observer force, including
transportation and equipment.
   ``It has been a major aim of the United States to bring this war
to an end,'' Fitzwater said. ``We now look forward to the
implementation ... in all its parts'' of the U.N. Security Council
resolution calling for a cease-fire.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>CARLUCCI</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci said the United States will
withdraw most of its naval forces from the Persian Gulf only when
it is convinced that the cease-fire has taken effect.
   ``We have no desire to keep our ships, our people, there any
longer than necessary. At the same time, we don't want to put them
in any danger,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>NAVY-GULF</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Chief Pentagon spokesman Dan Howard said the U.S. Navy had
completed its 54th convoy operation of the year with the
guided-missile frigate Nicholas escorting the reflagged Kuwaiti
tanker Chesapeake City up the Persian Gulf to Kuwait.
   Howard said the Defense Department had not received reports of
fighting Tuesday between Iran and Iraq, but added: ``I do not have
a definitive report that all hostilities have ceased. I can't speak
to that one way or another.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
