<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Hamadi 1stLd-Writethru a0674 08-09 0743</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hamadi, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0674,0765</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hamadi Confesses To Hijack, Says He Wouldn't Do It Again</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERT one graf after 10th graf pvs, ``The court ...
CLARIFYING that three others still at large. Picks up 11th graf
pvs, Hamadi, clean-shaven ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NESHA STARCEVIC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mohammed Ali Hamadi confessed
Tuesday he helped hijack a TWA jetliner to Beirut in 1985, but said
he is ``not ready to do something like that again'' and denied he
killed the U.S. Navy diver aboard.
   In a statement read in court, Hamadi said the four hijackers
were trying to force the release of Lebanese Shiite Moslems
imprisoned in Israel. Shortly after the ordeal was over, Israel
released approximately 700 Shiites.
   ``The decision to hijack the plane came after everything else
failed,'' Hamadi said in his surprise confession. ``There was no
other way to free the prisoners other than the means chosen.''
   Thirty-nine Americans were held captive for 17 days and U.S.
Navy diver Robert Stethem was killed. His body was thrown onto a
Beirut airport runway.
   Hamadi is being tried on charges of air piracy and murder in the
June 1985 TWA hijacking. The U.S. government also has indicted
Hamadi on charges of air piracy and murder.
   Hamadi denounced Israel for ``illegal conduct'' in Lebanon,
condemned the United States and said another hijacker had killed
Stethem. One of Hamadi's lawyers said Hamadi felt sorry for
``everyone who suffered harm.''
   In reflecting on the hijacking, Hamadi told the court: ``I am
not ready to do something like that again.''
   ``As I took part in the action, that happened out of the belief
that there was no other way to get the release of those imprisoned.
Now, I'm of the opinion that that's not the case,'' Hamadi said.
   Under West German law Hamadi can be convicted of murder even if
he did not actually fire the shots that killed Stethem, but one of
his lawyers said the court would have to prove the hijackers' plans
might have included possible murder.
   ``The court can convict him as a participant in the murder but
it has to prove that he knew what he was doing,'' said Gabrielle
Steck-Bromme.
   Three other hijacking suspects remain at large.
   Hamadi, clean-shaven in an open-neck shirt, read calmly and
clearly for about 45 minutes while Richard and Patricia Stethem,
parents of the slain diver, listened attentively to an interpreter.
   The Stethems, from Waldorf, Md., made no gestures visible to
reporters through the bulletproof glass that separates them from
Hamadi, the judges and the rest of the court.
   ``If this act which I committed is against the law, then it is a
result of illegal conduct on the part of Israel,'' said Hamadi. He
said the hijackers picked a U.S. aircraft ``because the United
States is the greatest ally and supporter of Israel.''
   Hamadi said that Hassan Iz-al-Din was in charge of the hijacking
and had been demanding a negotiator before shooting Stethem.
   ``The pistol was in his (Iz-al-Din's) hand,'' Hamadi said. ``I
didn't use it. Our orders were not to harm anyone, but I couldn't
convince him not to shoot.''
   Mrs. Steck-Bromme was asked how Hamadi felt about the Stethems'
presence in court.
   ``He feels sorry for everyone who suffered harm through the
hijacking,'' Mrs. Steck-Bromme said.
   The lawyer noted that Hamadi's age at the time of the hijacking
remains at issue and could determine whether the court will treat
him as a juvenile, young adult or an adult.
   But even if the court determines he was a juvenile, it could
decide to sentence him as an adult and hand down a maximum life
sentence.
   The judge asked Hamadi to ask his parents to come from Lebanon
to testify about his age, then recessed the trial until Sept. 6.
   Michael Senz, another of Hamadi's lawyers, said he hoped the
confession would lead to more lenient treatment.
   ``The court could now decide not to summon all American
witnesses because no identification is necessary,'' Senz said.
   West German television speculated that Hamadi's confession could
lead to speedy release of a West German hostage in Lebanon. But
government and foreign ministry spokesmen said they had no
information about any release.
   One West German, Alfred Schmidt, was released in September 1987,
but the second, Rudolf Cordes, remains a hostage.
   Cordes is believed to be held by Hezbollah, a radical
Iranian-backed Shiite Moslem group thought to be holding other
Western hostages in Lebanon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880809-0160 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-88 2057EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Angola 1stLd-Writethru a0636 08-09 0846</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Angola, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0636,0866</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Africans Ready For Withdrawal But Rebels Say They'll Fight
On</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 6 grafs to include number of Cuban troops and
report they pulling back; picks up 6th pvs `But the' and edits 10th
graf pvs `The accord announced' to conform</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   .
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South African soldiers
prepared Tuesday to withdraw from Angola as part of a peace accord,
but their rebel allies threatened to fight until they are included
in peace talks.
   South Africa will begin a three-week pullout of its troops in
Angola on Wednesday under terms of a cease-fire reached with Angola
and Cuba. The accord also sets a Nov. 1 starting date for a U.N.
plan to bring independence to South-West Africa, also known as
Namibia.
   An estimated 3,000 South African soldiers are in Angola and Cuba
has an estimated 50,000 soldiers in the country.
   In Zimbabwe, which has close ties to Angola, the national news
agency said Cuban troops in southern Angola were being pulled back
to positions north of the 16th parallel, roughly 90 miles north of
the Namibian border, as part of the agreement.
   The accord, announced Monday, was reached in five rounds of
U.S.-mediated peace talks among South Africa, Cuba and Angola. The
region's two main guerrilla armies were excluded.
   Spokesmen for the South-West Africa People's Organization, which
has fought for Namibian independence since 1966, said it would join
in a truce in the territory starting Sept. 1. SWAPO is believed to
have a strong chance of taking power in free elections envisioned
under the U.N. independence plan.
   But the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola
(UNITA), which has receievd South African and U.S. aid in its
13-year war against Angola's Cuban-backed government, said its
50,000 guerrillas would continue to fight until the country's
Marxist leaders agree to negotiate a power-sharing arrangement.
   ``If the MPLA (Angola's ruling party) doesn't accept this, the
armed conflict will continue,'' UNITA spokesman Alcides Sakala told
The Associated Press in Lisbon, Portugal. ``We will be back at
square one.''
   Sakala said UNITA was not concerned by South Africa's pledge to
halt aid to the rebels or by a possible cutoff of U.S. aid.
   ``Our guerrillas are spread all over the country,'' Sakala said.
``We have enough supplies and popular support to continue this war
for many, many years.''
   The accord announced in South Africa, Cuba and Angola is
contingent on a successful outcome of a sixth round of talks the
week of Aug. 22 to set a mutually agreeable timetable for
withdrawal of the Cuban troops from Angola.
   South African commentators expressed cautious optimism Tuesday
that a final settlement was in sight.
   ``As the winter dawn broke over the northern border of
South-West Africa this morning, there was a very real hope that,
for the first time in many years, peace would come to the troubled
southwestern region of Africa,'' said the state-run South African
Broadcasting Corp.
   ``It is not the end of many years of conflict, but hopefully it
is the beginning of the end,'' the television said.
   South Africa's chief representative in Namibia,
Administrator-General Louis Pienaar, told a meeting of white
farmers the accord was ``an answer to prayers.'' He suggested that
moderates and conservatives in Namibia form a coalition to oppose
SWAPO if independence elections take place.
   Pienaar called for the drafting of an independence constitution
that would protect democracy, private enterprise and ``the
first-world community'' _ a reference to the 70,000 whites in the
territory of 1.3 million people.
   The far-right Reformed National Party urged Namibian whites
Tuesday to resist the peace plan ``to prevent this beautiful and
good country from lapsing into poverty, malpractices and suffering
as has happened elsewhere in Africa where communist tyranny stepped
in.''
   SWAPO, which has pledged to allow multiparty democracy if it
took power in Namibia, said in a statement it will ``do its level
best to help in making the peace process in the southwestern
African region irreversible and successful, provided the Pretoria
regime also shows the political will to do the same.''
   The group said a military commission would be formed by South
Africa, Cuba and Angola to monitor the cease-fire.
   South Africa has invited U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de
Cuellar to visit the region. The U.N. chief's spokesman, Francois
Giuliani, said Tuesday the invitation was ``under consideration.''
   A potential problem in the granting of independence to Namibia
is funding. The cost has been estimated at $600 million, and a
senior U.N. official said Monday that the cash-strapped body may
have trouble financing a cease-fire observer team it will send to
the Persian Gulf.
   Another unresolved issue is South Africa's demand that Angola
close down bases of the African National Congress, the main
guerrilla group fighting to end white rule in South Africa.
Pretoria says there are seven ANC bases in Angola.
   Tom Sebina, an ANC spokesman in Lusaka, Zambia, said Tuesday
that South Africa ``is merely seeking some diversion from the talks
... The ANC camps are not connected with the talks.''
</TEXT>
