<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Conflicts-Glance     08-09 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Conflicts-Glance,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Status of Five Wars</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Angola, AM-Gulf Rdp</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Some international conflicts this week appear headed toward
resolution. Others hold the promise of settlement, but negotiations
are stalled. Here, at a a glance, is the status of some major wars
around the world:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>IRAN-IRAQ</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   A cease-fire takes effect Aug. 20 in the 8-year-old Persian Gulf
War, which has killed or wounded more than 1 million people. The
cease-fire will be monitored by a United Nations observer force.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ANGOLA</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   South Africa will begin pulling its troops out of Angola on
Wednesday, Aug. 10. The pro-Western UNITA guerrillas, who with
South African help have fought the Cuban-supported Marxist
government of Angola, say they will continue their war until
Angolan leaders agree to negotiate a power-sharing arrangement.
   In neighboring South-West Africa, also known as Namibia, a
United Nations plan to grant independence to the South
African-ruled territory has a starting date of Nov. 1. The
Angolan-supported SWAPO guerrillas, fighting since 1966 for
Namibian independence, say they will join in a truce Sept. 1.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>AFGHANISTAN</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Half the estimated 120,000 Soviet troops backing Afghanistan's
Marxist government against anti-communist rebels are to be out of
that country by next Monday, under accords signed in April. The
Soviets are to withdraw all their military units by next Feb. 15.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>CAMBODIA</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Communist Vietnam, whose troops prop up a Cambodian government
against Marxist and non-Marxist resistance groups, said last month
it would pull its forces out by early 1990. But no significant
progress was reported in subsequent peace negotiations, between
representatives of the Vietnamese and Cambodian governments on one
side, and Cambodian resistance leaders on the other.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>NICARAGUA</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Peace talks between the leftist Sandinista government and the
U.S.-backed rebels, known as Contras, have been suspended since the
last session broke up in disagreement June 9.
   The Sandinistas have arrested opposition leaders, shut down
opposition media outlets and expelled some U.S. diplomats. The
Contras have elected new hard-line political leaders and have been
accused of carrying out attacks in the countryside in violation of
an informal cease-fire.
   The U.S. Congress has yet to reach agreement on resumption of
suspended aid to the Contras.
</TEXT>
