<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Sunia     08-09 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sunia,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Schedules Disciplinary Hearings Against Sunia in Fraud Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House ethics committee will take the first
step Sept. 7 in disciplinary proceedings against Fofo I.F. Sunia,
the Democratic delegate from American Samoa, the panel said Tuesday.
   The committee said the disciplinary hearing also will consider
the case of Sunia's administrative assistant, Matthew K. Iuli.
   Both men pleaded guilty in U.S. District Court on Aug. 3 to
charges they conspired to defraud the government. They were accused
of operating a payroll padding scheme that netted $130,920 from
paychecks issued to ghost employees.
   Iuli also pleaded guilty to a second charge of filing a false
payroll authorization form.
   The panel said it has determined that the offenses in the
criminal case also were violations of House standards of conduct.
   Disciplinary hearings are conducted so the committee can
determine what action to recommend to the full House.
   The House can impose penalties ranging from a reprimand _ an
expression of disapproval _ to expulsion.
   A resolution by the panel, officially the Committee on Standards
of Official Conduct, said the disciplinary recommendation would be
made public.
   In the criminal action, defense attorney Earl Silbert had told
U.S. District Judge Stanley Harris that Sunia would resign before
sentencing, which was scheduled for Oct. 4.
   Sunia could receive a five-year sentence and a possible fine of
$250,000.
</TEXT>
