<HEAD>Iraq Celebrates, Declares Victory in Gulf War</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Gulf Rdp Bjt
^Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to include more celebrations Tuesday night
and early Wednesday; PICKS up 5th pvs `A woman'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq declared victory Tuesday in the war
with Iran and the sky over the Tigris River blazed with fireworks.
   When the announcement of a cease-fire was read over state
television soon after midnight Monday, exuberant Iraqis fired tens
of thousands of rounds of ammunition into the sky.
   The television urged Iraqis to ``celebrate the great victory
achieved by Iraq'' on ``the greatest day of all.'' It declared
three days of celebration to mark the end of the 8-year-old war,
which killed or wounded more than 1 million people and cost the
combatants hundreds of billions of dollars.
   It also appealed for a halt to the shooting, which caused an
undisclosed number of casualties, but to no avail.
   Gunfire continued 24 hours later. ``This is the pressure of
pent-up emotion which has built for eight years,'' Iraqi writer
Jabra Ibrahim Jabra told a visitor as shots sounded in the streets
outside his home Tuesday night.
   Streets throughout the capital were gridlocked with horn-honking
cars into the early hours Wednesday as Iraqis jumped from their
vehicles to dance in the streets, or dangled from windows or car
rooftops.
   After the announcement on television, a man at the entrance of
the Rashid hotel shouted ``The war is over! Victory for Iraq!'' and
gazed at the flashes overhead.
   A woman beside him said: ``The war is over, praise be to God!''
   Tracers, flares and machine-gun bullets streamed into the air
for hours after the announcement. The crack and stutter of firing
filled the night.
   ``Here, take this!'' joyful security men told a reporter,
thrusting a loaded Kalashnikov assault rifle at him. The guards
later fired the gun into the air, laughing with other security men
across the street who also were shooting.
   A car in the hotel parking lot had a new bullet hole in its
hood. Children scampered about collecting empty cartridge casings.
   Celebrants danced on the beds of pickups and waved palm fronds
from car windows. People beat drums and sang as others danced in
the streets.
   Later Tuesday, a day after U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez
de Cuellar announced that a cease-fire would begin Aug. 20, the
ruling Baath Socialist Party organized processions in Baghdad.
   Marchers waved pictures of President Saddam Hussein. They raised
Iraqi flags beside banners reading ``The Hero of Peace, President
Saddam Hussein'' and ``Masses of Baghdad Congratulate the Hero of
Victory.''
   In what the official Iraqi News Agency called the ``Communique
of Communiques,'' the president proclaimed the three-day holiday
and said: ``In the name of all Arabs and mankind, we call on Iraqis
to celebrate this great victory.''
   For the first time in nearly eight years, Iraq did not issue a
daily war communique. The last one, No. 3288 on Monday, reported
only minor skirmishes.
   Hussein attended a morning celebration at Grand Festivities Park
in Baghdad. The news agency said Sheik Jaber al Ahmed al Sabah,
emir of Kuwait, telephoned congratulations and declared Thursday a
day of celebration in Kuwait.
   The official news agency said soldiers fired 10,000 artillery
rounds to celebrate. It said 101 shots were fired in joy during
each of the five Moslem prayer times Tuesday in 17 Iraqi cities and
governorates.
   Moslem are required to face Mecca, birthplace of the prophet
Mohammed, and pray each day at dawn, noon, afternoon, evening and
night.
</TEXT>
