<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru a0685 08-09 0762</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0685,0781</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Troops Kill Arab, Bomb Radio Station In Lebanon</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with new reports that 21 Palestinians wounded,
soldier injured, and changes to conform grafs 1-5. Picks up 4th
graf pvs `A military spokesman', DELETES 9th pvs `The rebellion',
which moved up, and DELETES outdated 15th `The army said nine'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MASHA HAMILTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers fired on young Palestinians who hurled
stones and bottles Tuesday, killing a teen-ager, hospital officials
said. Israeli aircraft bombed a radio station in Lebanon that the
army said broadcast PLO propaganda.
   A second Palestinian died and two were seriously burned after
arsonists set fire to a shack at a construction site in a Jewish
suburb of Tel Aviv, police reported. Officials did not rule out the
possibility that the attack was linked to Arab-Israeli tensions.
   Up to 21 Arabs, including a 9-year-old boy, were reported
wounded by gunfire as the Palestinian rebellion in the occupied
West Bank and Gaza Strip began its ninth month.
   An army spokesman reported 13 Palestinians wounded but Arab
hospital officials said put the number at 21. The army said a
soldier was slightly injured when Palestinians stoned an army
outpost near Jenin in the West Bank.
   At least 238 Palestinians have been killed in the uprising,
which began Dec. 8, and four Israelis also have been slain.
   A military spokesman said the air force destroyed a PLO-run
radio station and an ammunition storehouse in southern Lebanon in
what was Israel's 12th air raid this year.
   The spokesman said the radio station, founded in early June, was
used to broadcast instructions to Palestinians in the occupied
territories.
   ``The base ... was a radio station used for propaganda and
incitement broadcasts, and to pass orders for executing terror
attacks,'' he said, speaking on condition of anonymity in keeping
with military regulations.
   In Lebanon, a police spokesman said three guerrillas were killed
and 12 wounded in the raid. He said the base belonged to Fatah,
Yasser Arafat's main wing of the Palestine Liberation Organization.
   Tuesday's violence in the occupied lands coincided with a
sweeping strike observed by most of the 1.5 million Arabs in the
territories and called for by underground leaders to mark the ninth
month of the Palestinian ``intefadeh,'' Arabic for ``uprising.''
   In the latest fatality, 14-year-old Hussein Swei was fatally
shot in the head during a clash between troops and dozens of Arab
youths hurling stones and bottles in the West Bank town of
Qalqilya, 40 miles north of Jerusalem, a spokesman at a United
Nations clinic said.
   An army spokesman denied the boy was shot by troops. He said a
doctor at the clinic told army investigators there were no signs of
a bullet wound on Swei's body. He did not identify the doctor.
   Palestinian youths took the body from the clinic and, despite a
curfew imposed on Qalqilya, buried it in the town's cemetery, Arab
witnesses said.
   Hundreds of Palestinians attended the burial, chanting PLO
slogans as they carried the body wrapped in a Palestinian flag,
witnesses told The Associated Press. Troops surrounded the cemetery
but no clashes were reported.
   Curfews also were in effect Tuesday on the West Bank refugee
camp of Tulkarm, the town of Husan and two Gaza Strip refugee camps.
   Police, meanwhile, arrested three Palestinians from the Gaza
Strip suspected of killing 65-year-old Rachel Weiss, of the Shafir
collective farming settlement, last week.
   Regional police commander Tuvia Golan told Israel army radio the
three youths, all aged 17, acted out of anti-Israeli feelings but
also intended to rob the woman.
   On Monday night, arsonists torched a shack in the Tel Aviv
suburb of Or Yehuda housing three Palestinian construction workers,
police said. All three were seriously burned and one died early
Tuesday of his wounds.
   Police refused to rule out the possibility that the attack was
related to Israeli-Arab tension. However, Arabs in the past also
have used violence to try to prevent fellow Palestinians from
working at jobs in Israel.
   Arab merchants shuttered their shops and many of the 110,000 who
work in Israel stayed home from their jobs, Arab news reports and
witnesses said. The strike was ordered by the PLO-linked leadership
in its underground Leaflet No. 23.
   Also Tuesday, disturbances were reported as American-born Rabbi
Meir Kahane's anti-Arab Kach Party held a news conference in Tel
Aviv to name its candidates for November's elections.
   Members of the leftist Mapam Party demonstrated outside and
police were summoned to the site after a bomb threat.
   Kahane's party calls for expelling all Arabs from Israeli-held
territory.
</TEXT>
