<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Shultz 1stLd-Writethru a0767 08-09 0546</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Shultz, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0767,0557</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shultz Back In Central America For Third Time</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 9th graf: Shultz met with... to update with meeting in
Honduras and flight to San Salvador.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By REID G. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George P. Shultz returned to Central
America on Tuesday for talks with the presidents of Costa Rica,
Honduras and El Salvador about the region's conflicts and the
leftist Nicaraguan government.
   The secretary of state, who escaped harm in a bomb attack on his
motorcade Monday in Bolivia, played an hour of tennis with Foreign
Minister Rodrigo Madrigal Nieto and had breakfast with President
Oscar Arias before going to Honduras. It is Shultz's third visit to
the area since June.
   Asked why his trips were so frequent, Shultz said he wanted ``to
reinforce an economic opening and political freedom'' in Central
America.
   He said he briefed Arias on his trip to South American, and the
Costa Rican president reported on his efforts to enforce the
Central America peace plan of Aug. 7, 1987.
   Arias is the plan's author and won the 1987 Nobel Peace Prize
because of it, but Central America's civil wars continue.
   During his first visit in June, the secretary tried to persuade
El Salvador, Honduras, Costa Rica and Guatemala join the United
States in a declaration accusing the Sandinistas of failing to live
up to the peace plan.
   He failed to get the signatures of the four foreign ministers at
a meeting Aug. 1 in Guatemala City, to which Nicaragua was not
invited. The declaration released simply reiterated support for
democracy and progress in the region.
   Costa Rica and Guatemala objected to a strongly worded statement
accusing the Sandinistas of failing to initiate democratic reforms
in Nicaragua and of cracking down on opposition groups. Leaders of
the two countries were said to feel that might cause the
Sandinistas to adopt an even tougher stance.
   Shultz visited with Guatemalan President Vinicio Cerezo last
week after the foreign ministers' conference. On Tuesday afternoon,
he spent two hours with Honduran President Jose Azcona Hoyo in
Tegucigalpa and flew to San Salvador for talks with Salvadoran Vice
President Adolfo Castillo Claramount.
   Castillo is substituting for President Jose Napoleon Duarte, who
is undergoing chemotherapy for terminal liver cancer in
Washington's Walter Reed army hospital.
   Honduras and El Salvador are close U.S. allies in Washington's
effort to isolate the Sandinista government, which the Reagan
administration considers a threat to security in Central America.
   The United States has poured military and economic aid into El
Salvador for eight years to help it fight a leftist guerrilla
insurrection. Washington also aids Honduras and Nicaraguan rebels,
known as Contras, who have supply and staging bases in Honduras
near the Nicaraguan border.
   Shultz has visited Argentina, Uruguay and Brazil as part of a
10-day tour of Latin America that began Aug. 1.
   Hew is to be in Quito, Ecuador, on Wednesday for the
inauguration of President Rodrigo Borja, a socialist lawyer, who
replaces conservative Leon Febres Cordero.
   A bomb exploded Monday amid Shultz's motorcade as he and his
entourage were driving into La Paz, capital of Bolivia. The windows
of the car carrying his wife, Helena, were shattered and two other
cars were damaged but no injuries were reported.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
