<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     08-09 0368</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0377</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Beryl Moves Inland, Rain Elsewhere in Eastern Half Of Nation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Tropical storm Beryl moved inland Tuesday and weakened to a
tropical depression, spreading rain across the South, and rain also
fell from the Great Lakes to the southern Plains and over part of
the Midwest.
   Beryl was south of Baton Rouge and was expected to move to the
west and northwest into Wednesday. Its highest sustained wind speed
was down to 40 mph during the afternoon and to 35 mph by evening. A
storm is designated a tropical storm when its wind speed hits 39
mph.
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered over the lower
Mississippi Valley and along the central Gulf Coast in association
with Beryl, but much of the heaviest rainfall was over the Gulf of
Mexico.
   Alabama's offshore Dauphin Island got 11.6 inches of rain during
the 24-hour period up to 7 a.m. Tuesday.
   Showers and thunderstorms were scattered along a stationary
front that extended from the lower Great Lakes through the central
Plains into the southern high Plains. But much of the rainfall was
fairly light.
   Thunderstorms developed from east-central Illinois into northern
Indiana.
   Elsewhere, showers and thunderstorms developed along Florida's
eastern coast and showers and thunderstorms were scattered along
the southern Atlantic Coast.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 57
degrees at Arcata, Calif., to 103 at Altus, Okla., and Dallas-Fort
Worth, Waco and Wichita Falls, Texas. The nation's low Tuesday
morning was 30 degrees at Jackson, Wyo.
   For Wednesday, showers and thunderstorms, some with locally
heavy rain, were forecast from the lower Mississippi Valley into
the central Gulf Coast. Showers and thunderstorms also were
expected to be scattered into the southern Atlantic Coast and
Florida. Scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast from
northern New England through the lower Ohio Valley into the middle
Mississippi and lower Missouri valleys.
   Highs in the 70s were predicted along the Pacific Coast; in the
upper 90s to around 100 over south-central Kansas through the
southern Plains into the Rio Grande Valley of Texas; between 100
and 110 across the desert Southwest; and in the 80s or 90s across
much of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
