<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BRF--BaldnessDrug     08-09 0148</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Baldness Drug,0151</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Upjohn One Step Away From Final FDA Approval For Baldness Drug</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KALAMAZOO, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A baldness remedy developed by the
Upjohn Co. is one step closer to final federal approval, company
officials announced Tuesday.
   The Kalamazoo-based pharmaceutical company said it received an
``approvable letter'' Tuesday from the U.S. Food and Drug
Administration for its topical minoxidil preparation for the
treatment of male pattern baldness, developed under the trade name
Rogaine.
   An approvable letter is ``historically the last step before
final approval'' for marketing, company spokesman R.D. LaRue said.
   LaRue said the letter means the scientific data submitted by the
company have been approved, leaving only label language to be
worked out. He would not speculate when final approval may be
granted.
   Minoxidil was developed as a blood pressure treatment, but
Upjohn noted about 10 years ago that some users experienced
increased hair growth.
</TEXT>
