<1ST_LINE>r a AM-IndustrialFire     08-09 0359</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Industrial Fire,0369</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fire at Nevada Plant Causes Nervous Moments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT MACY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HENDERSON, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bright magnesium fire caused a series
of small explosions and scared residents of this community early
Tuesday, only months after an explosion destroyed a nearby plant
that made a rocket fuel component.
   No one was injured in the pre-dawn blaze at a Titanium Metals
Corp. plant, but some residents fled the area briefly after they
were awakened by as many as six small explosions.
   Police, unsure of the nature of the problem, began to evacuate
nearby residents but allowed them to return less than an hour later
after firefighters brought the blaze under control.
   Plant Manager Bob Ritchey said the fire posed no danger to
workers or residents.
   ``Everybody's spoiled by PEPCON,'' Ritchey said. ``If somebody
sneezes, everybody runs for cover.''
   Ritchey referred to a series of explosions at a Pacific
Engineering & Production Co. plant less than three miles away that
killed two people, injured 326 and caused $73 million in propery
damage May 4. That plant was one of two in the country making
ammonium perchlorate, an oxidyzer in solid rocket fuel.
   Fire department dispatcher Melanie Dobosh said Tuesday's fire
apparently started after some magnesium ingots melted and came into
contact with water in a drain. The reaction of the metal and the
water caused the small explosions, she said.
   Magnesium is used in the manufacture of titanium.
   The fire occurred outside an abandoned building at the plant,
Ritchey said. Dobosh estimated damage at $15,000.
   The fire was reported at 1:50 a.m. and was under control by 2:40
a.m., dispatcher Jim Martin said. Officials said 60 firefighters,
including a team specializing in fires involving hazardous
materials, came to the scene and smothered the fire with salt.
   ``It produced a cloud of pretty foul-smelling smoke, but it was
not toxic,'' Ms. Dobosh said. ``It was not as bad as what it
sounded like it was.''
   The plant covers several blocks and dates to World War II,
making it one of the oldest in Henderson, an industrial community
of 55,000 people 20 miles southeast of Las Vegas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
