<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Canada-Gulf     08-09 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Gulf,0276</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Canada Will Send 385 Military Personnel To Persian Gulf</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OTTAWA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Canada will contribute 385 military personnel to
the U.N. peacekeeping force that will monitor the cease-fire
between Iran and Iraq, Foreign Minister Joe Clark and Defense
Minister Perrin Beatty said Tuesday.
   The number includes 15 officers who will form part of the
headquarters staff in the 350-member U.N. force or take border
observer positions.
   The other 370 Canadians will be responsible for communications
for the 25-nation peacekeeping force. The communications role will
be phased out later when a civilian group takes over that function.
   Some of the Canadians will arrive Wednesday in the Persian Gulf
region as part of the U.N. advance team. The communications
contingent will start arriving Friday.
   Clark and Beatty said the cease-fire was ``a vital first step in
efforts to end the eight-year Iran-Iraq war.'' It is scheduled to
begin Aug. 20.
   The ministers said Canadian involvement ``is consistent with our
traditional commitment to the United Nations peacekeeping
operations and reflects the high regard in which Canadian Forces
peacekeeping personnel are held by the international community.''
   Canada has played a role in 17 peacekeeping missions since the
end of World War II, starting in 1949 to ease tensions between
India and Pakistan.
   The ministers praised U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de
Cuellar ``for his unstinting efforts that have brought the prospect
of peace to the region of the gulf.''
   They also urged Iran and Iraq to approach peace talks Aug. 25 in
Geneva ``with a spirit of openness and the intention of moving
resolutely toward a complete and final accord.''
</TEXT>
