<HEAD>Thornburgh Says Goodbye Again</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS Thornburgh's title at the Kennedy School in last
graf.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General-designate Dick Thornburgh
returned to his old law firm Tuesday to say goodbye, again, to his
law partners and staff.
   Thornburgh, 56, governor from 1979 to 1987, visited the downtown
office of Kirkpatrick & Lockhart, where staff members prepared
punch and cookies for a brief gathering.
   Thornburgh was about a half-hour late for the function because
he also attended a fund-raising luncheon for Vice President George
Bush.
   Thornburgh, a graduate of the University of Pittsburgh School of
Law, has been associated with the law firm off and on for 30 years,
rejoining it most recently when he left the governor's office in
January 1987.
   Thornburgh also recently was director of the Institute of
Politics at the Kennedy School of Government at Harvard University.
He was nominated by President Reagan to succeed Edwin Meese III as
attorney general.
