<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-88 2109EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bush 1stLd-Writethru a0760 08-09 0917</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0760,940</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush Says He's Gaining on Dukakis</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: to UPDATE with ``National Night Out'' appearance in
Philadelphia, INSERT two grafs after 19th pvs, ``And Bush...some
furlough,'' picking up 20th pvs, ``Democrats on ...crime fight.''
^By TERENCE HUNT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush, commenting as
aides pointed to encouraging new poll figures, said Tuesday,
``Watch and you'll see these surveys turn around.''
   Bush did not cite any figures to back up his claim that he was
catching up to Michael Dukakis. However, Sheila Tate, his press
secretary, noted a Gallup poll that said Dukakis' lead has dropped
from 17 points just after the Democratic convention to seven
points, 49 percent to 42 percent.
   ``That is turning around,'' Bush said of Dukakis' advantage.
``You watch, in the next couple of days you'll see evidence of the
turnaround on that. ... Things are moving. We're beginning to get
them in focus.''
   Bush also renewed his criticism of Dukakis, accusing his
Democratic presidential rival of trying to run away from a record
``on the very, very far liberal fringe.''
   Dukakis, when told of Bush's remarks, said merely, ``There he
goes again,'' harking back to a line that then-candidate Ronald
Reagan used to great effect in a debate with President Carter in
1980.
   Just six days before the opening of the Republican National
Convention in New Orleans, where he will become the GOP
presidential nominee, Bush said he still has not decided who will
be his running mate.
   ``I'm not close in the sense of like tomorrow making a final
decision,'' the vice president said. Bush has said he wants to keep
his decision a secret until the final day of the convention.
   Attacking Dukakis, Bush said his opponent was trying to avoid
being specific on issues.
   ``He's trying to run away from a record in Massachusetts on the
very, very far liberal fringe of the political fringe of the
political spectrum and I have to pin him down,'' Bush said.
   ``He thinks he can preempt the middle,'' Bush added.
   The vice president spoke at an airport news conference in
Pittsburgh after a speech and private fund-raiser earlier in Erie.
   Bush later cut the ribbon to open a Polish-American cultural
center in Philadelphia and, before a crowd of hundreds in a
downtown street, paid tribute to Roman Catholic Cardinal John Krol
of Philadelphia as ``an inspiration to all of us in public life or
private life.''
   He also said there was a ``special link between Poland and the
United States of America.''
   In Erie, Bush addressed the Pennsylvania lodge of the Fraternal
Order of Police, drawing loud applause with lines such as, ``So
let's not take away the guns of innocent citizens; let's get
tougher on the criminals.''
   He said the nation should band together to fight illegal drugs
with the same fervor as was demonstrated in World War II.
   Bush said states that decriminalized possession of drugs
``should recriminalize it.''
   Asked later if he felt that possession of marijuana should be
made a felony, Bush said, ``I would be very tempted to make it
strong, to make it a felony.'' He said he would be interested in
what law enforcement officials felt.
   Saying his speech was non-partisan, Bush did not mention Dukakis
by name. But he criticized the American Civil Liberties, of which
he has said Dukakis is a member, saying its ``first concerns are
the protection of criminals' rights and the potential abuse of
power by police.''
   And Bush, who has criticized the prison furlough program in
Massachusetts, said he was angered by ``the arrogant face of a
criminal, back on the street once more because of a permissive plea
bargain or some furlough.''
   Bush stressed his anti-crime theme again in an appearance
Tuesday night at the ``National Night Out Against Crime,'' where he
switched on a giant lightbulb in downtown Philadelphia in a
symbolic message that people intend to fight for safe neighborhoods.
   ``For those who commit drug related murders and for those
kingpins who are poisoning our kids the penalty shoudl be death,''
the vice president told an audience of about 200, adding that the
death penalty should also apply to people who kill police officers.
   Democrats on Capitol Hill called a news briefing to ridicule
Bush's comments on crime-fighting.
   ``George Bush thinks that hanging around with all the criminals
in the administration makes him tough on crime,'' said Rep. Charles
Schumer, D-N.Y.
   ``Since 1981, this administration has failed to support one
nickel going to state and local law enforcement,'' said Rep.
Charles Rangel, D-N.Y., chairman of the House narcotics committee.
   Bush said he was urging speakers at next week's Republican
convention to be positive and to focus on the issues.
   ``But I can't guarantee that somebody's not going to take a
swipe at Michael Dukakis,'' Bush said. ``I have a lot of friends
out there and they didn't like the vicious, personal attacks
(against Bush at the Democratic convention) andI did not react to
them, but I can't control everybody but I'm urging them to stay
positive, as I'm doing.''
   Bush added, ``There's a lot of people out there that want to go
after 'em. There's a lot of people that feel it was a very unfair,
totally negative tune there.''
   Emphasizing policy differences, Bush said of Dukakis, ``When he
says he's against the death penalty for everything, the country has
a right to know it. I happen to think some crimes are bad enough,
you should.
</TEXT>
