<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-88 2342EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-HUDMoneyBill 1stLd-Writethru a0742 08-09 0177</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-HUD Money Bill, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0742,150</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House Votes $59 Billion for Housing, Independent Agencies</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lede to correct day of vote to Tuesday sted Wednesday</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House passed and sent to the Senate on
Tuesday a compromise spending bill providing $59 billion for the
Department of Housing and Urban Development and 16 independent
agencies.
   The House vote was 373-30. A similar overwhelming margin was
expected in the Senate.
   The House Democratic leadership said the fiscal 1989
appropriations bill for HUD and other agencies is consistent with
the budget summit agreement worked out last year by Congress and
the White House.
   Highlights of the bill include $7.2 billion for low-income
housing assistance, $1.6 billion for public housing operating
subsidies and $1.4 billion for housing vouchers for low-income
families.
   The bill also would provide $10.7 billion for the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration, including $900 million for a
space station, and funds for the Environmental Protection Agency,
the Veterans Administration, the National Science Foundation and
the Consumer Product Safety Commission, among other agencies.
</TEXT>
