<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-88 2357EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AbortionProtests     08-09 0442</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Abortion Protests,0456</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dozens Accept Release On Bail, But Others Persist</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARC RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An anti-abortion protest in which activists are
staying in jail by refusing to give their names ebbed as dozens
were released on bail, but an organizer vowed there would be more
demonstrations.
   A total of 63 protesters gave their names to authorities Monday
and Tuesday and were released on bail, said J.D. Hudson, director
of the city's Correctional Center. The center has served as the
initial holding facility for the 276 protesters arrested since
demonstrations began during the Democratic National Convention July
19.
   The releases left only 22 protesters in the city jail.
   Another 63 protesters have been bound over to State Court and
are being held in Fulton County jail. They have claimed to
represent aborted fetuses and have identified themselves only as
Baby John Doe or Baby Jane Doe. The others have been released
sporadically since their arrests.
   The protesters have been held on charges of criminal trespass or
giving a false name to police.
   Lowell Patterson, spokesman for Operation Rescue, the group that
organized the anti-abortion protests, said there will be a new
round of demonstrations.
   ``I think you can expect the next one in the morning,'' he said,
but declined to give details.
   Patterson said the protesters who identified themselves and were
released had made only a short-term commitment to the group's
effort. Those remaining in county jail are prepared to remain
indefinitely, he said.
   The demonstrators were fingerprinted after their arrests as a
matter of routine but authorities said Monday they were not using
the prints to try to identify them.
   The protesters have put a strain on Fulton County's already
crowded jail, officials said.
   Maj. A.M. Alexander, assistant director of the county jail, said
the facility is at capacity.
   The protesters still in city jail were scheduled for a court
hearing Wednesday, and they could be transferred to the county jail
then.
   If more protesters are arrested, ``they most likely will have to
start sleeping on the floor, because we are at capacity,''
Alexander said. ``We'll still feed them, we'll give them medical
treatment. But they'll sleep on the floor.''
   Patterson said daily coverage of the protests on the ``700
Club,'' former presidential candidate Pat Robertson's cable
television show, has helped attract more anti-abortion activists to
Atlanta.
   ``He is our one link to Christians all across the country that
we have not had from the secular media,'' said Patterson.
   Hudson said the city has spent $61,000 to jail the
demonstrators, and sheriff's Chief Deputy Bob Poole said the county
has spent about $66,000 so far.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
