<DOCNO> AP880809-0183 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-88 2205EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-CubsLights     08-09 0424</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cubs Lights,0437</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Historic First Game Under Lights, Part II</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CLIFF EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rain washed out Wrigley Field's first game under
the lights, but folks in the surrounding Wrigleyville neighborhood
said true Chicago Cubs baseball fans showed up Tuesday night.
   Monday's game between the Cubs and Philadelphia Phillies _ the
first at night in the stadium's 74-year history _ was postponed
after heavy rain fell with the Cubs leading 3-1 in the bottom of
the fourth inning.
   But the Cubs gave night baseball another chance when they faced
the New York Mets under the lights Tuesday at 7:05 p.m. And this
time, there wasn't a rain cloud in sight.
   Also missing were the T-shirts with blinking lights, the Cubs
batting helmets with flashlights taped on top, and hords of
merrymakers who came looking for history Monday night.
   ``Last night was celebrity night and historic-event seeker's
night,'' said Sherwood Williams, the Chicago Police Department's
deputy chief of special functions.
   ``Tonight is real fan night ... tonight we have real Cubs fans
who support the team all season long, through thick and thin.''
   Zeke Closen, 69, a retired engineer from Peoria, said he felt he
was seeing history made Tuesday night.
   ``The ones who came last night said `we saw the first night
game,''' he said. ``But ask them what the score was or who won. I
feel like I'm seeing the first night game.''
   Monday's game came 40 years after the Detroit Tigers lighted up
for night baseball and left Wrigley Field the only day-only holdout.
   Still, some opponents said the aborted game proved that their
fears of rowdy fans and illegal parking were on target.
   ``There was all this screaming and cursing,'' said Gus Oing, a
20-year Wrigleyville resident who lives less than a block from the
stadium.
   ``Who wants to hear that? Does all that noise and racket have
anything to do with baseball?''
   Chicago police put 172 officers on Wrigleyville duty Monday,
including mounted and canine patrols, and they planned the same
number Tuesday, said police Capt. John Manley.
   Police arrested 35 people Monday for disorderly conduct or
public drinking, three for ticket scalping, one for fighting in the
ballpark and one for theft, Manley said.
   Mike Quigley, vice president of Citizens United for Baseball in
the Sunshine, or CUBS, said after Monday's game that his group
might seek to have the precinct housing Wrigley Field declared dry
of alcohol next spring unless night games are halted or a curfew
and other restrictions are imposed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
