<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Panama 1stLd-Writethru a0772 08-09 0551</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Panama, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0772,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Envoy in Panama To Assess Situation</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDS: Inserts grafs 8-12, beginning, ``In Panama xxx with comment
from Noreiga, others in Panama</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior State Department official has flown
to Panama for talks with U.S. diplomats and leading Panamanians
about the political situation in that country, the department said
Tuesday.
   Deputy spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley said Morton Abramowitz, who
heads the department's bureau of intelligence and research, was
sent to Panama. She gave no other details.
   Other officials, who spoke only on condition they not be
identified, said Abramowitz's visit does not represent a renewal of
the U.S. effort to pressure Panamanian military leader Manuel
Antonio Noriega to relinquish power.
   That effort collapsed last May when Noriega balked at the terms
proposed by U.S. envoys. The State Department called off
negotiations and said no further talks would be held.
   It was not clear whether Abramowitz planned to meet with
representatives of the Noriega-led government, which the United
States has refused to recognize since it took office nearly six
months ago. The U.S. government recognizes ousted President Eric
Arturo Delvalle as the legitimate authority in Panama.
   The officials attached no significance to the fact that
Abramowitz is making the trip during the same week when Noriega
will observe the fifth anniversary of his accession as commander of
the Panamanian Defense Forces on Aug. 12.
   In Panama, Noriega called Abramowitz' visit ``not only part of
the aggression against Panama but also (of that) against Latin
America.''
   He spoke with reporters after an hour-long meeting Tuesday with
Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega.
   The visit, he said, shows ``a lack of respect that only shows
how in Latin America they (American government officials) impose
force and injustice on those who are weaker.''
   A senior Panamanian military official, who asked not to be
identified, said Abramowitz met with local opposition leaders about
a plan against the government.
   He said it included street disturbances by secondary students in
Panama City and Colon, on the Atlantic Ocean end of the Panama
Canal, and attacks on Noriega and other government leaders. The
object is to force the resignation of Manuel Solis Palma, named
interim president after Delvalle's removal, the source said.
   A U.S. Embassy spokesman said Abramowitz would be in Panama
``several days.''
   The spokesman said he would meet with ``people with many points
of view'' but did not confirm the report of talks with opposition
leaders.
   The Reagan administration had been trying in May to work out an
agreement under which Noriega would resign as defense chief on that
anniversary.
   Ambassador Juan Sosa, a leader of anti-Noriega forces in
Washington, has said he believes Noriega may use the anniversary to
make an important announcement, possibly to launch his candidacy
for presidential elections next May.
   Noriega, indicted on drug smuggling charges by two federal grand
juries in Florida six months ago, gave a warm welcome Monday to
visiting Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega, who said that Panama
and Nicaragua ``are under attack by imperialist policies'' of the
United States.
   The administration has attempted through economic and diplomatic
pressure to force Noriega's departure. It was reported two weeks
ago that President Reagan had a approved a covert plan that
involved encouraging opposition political activities aimed at
discrediting Noriega.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
