<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-88 0613EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WKD--RecordReviews Adv00   08-09 0593</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-WKD--Record Reviews, Adv 00,0621</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv00</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Anytime</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>In the Groove: Record Reviews</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Joy'' (Elektra) _ Teddy Pendergrass
   
   ``Joy'' is a steamy set of soul songs that never overheats, due
to the restraint of the tempos, arrangements and Teddy Pendergrass'
delivery.
   Even when Pendergrass sings of ``explosions of ecstacy flowing
from you and me'' (on ``2 a.m.''), his cooing manner is such that
the words would probably slip right past Tipper Gore.
   The song titles _ ``Can We Be Lovers,'' ``I'm Ready,'' ``Love Is
the Power'' _ show that Pendergrass is obsessed with the same thing
as Prince, but Pendergrass is less overt.
   The accompaniment steers clear of lead guitars or horns that
would clash with Pendergrass' smooth style. Drums, bass and
low-profile keyboards dominate. The closest thing to a frill is
three female backup singers; Pendergrass plays off them when he
raps (briefly enough to avoid being corny) and when he improvises
nicely on the chorus of ``Through the Falling Rain.''
   The eight love songs on ``Joy'' are all played at mid-tempo.
Pendergrass' message is clear: this is music for romancing, not
dancing.
   _ By Steven Wine, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   
   ``Brian Wilson'' (Sire) _ Brian Wilson
   
   The story's so irresistible, you almost want to will it to be
true.
   Brian Wilson, Rock 'n' Roll Hall of Fame member and erstwhile
Beach Boy, releases his first solo LP after 20 years of being
nearly incapacitated by mental illness. Can the lost genius ever be
found?
   Not really.
   In one respect, this new album is a triumph. Few people honestly
expected Wilson to ever again release listenable music of any form,
so anything more is gravy.
   But let's be honest. Despite some pleasant moments, ``Brian
Wilson'' can't compare with any of the early '60s Beach Boys
classics, nor a lot of other good music happening today.
   It's a nondescript album that floats by without any songs
grabbing hold and shaking out any reaction. Frankly, both the
Smithereens and XTC alter-egos Dukes of Stratosphear have written
better Brian Wilson tributes in the past year than Wilson himself.
   Back when he was young, Wilson's classic ``In My Room'' spoke
universally to teen-agers who occasionally need to escape into
themselves and not feel childish about it.
   But a generation has passed, and Wilson still hasn't left his
room. In ``Love and Mercy,'' he talks of ``lyin' in my room'' and
seeing ``a lot of people out there hurtin' and it really scares
me.'' The prescription, love and mercy, isn't much different from
what the Beatles suggested 21 years ago.
   ``Baby Let Your Hair Grow Long'' suggests a troubled girl may
cure her problems with an adjustment in grooming. A naivete that
seemed charming 25 years ago is less so now.
   And, musically, what once seemed effortless is now labored. Too
many rhythms are ponderous and the Phil Spector touches in the
production mostly sound dated.
   There are some high points: ``Walkin' the Line,'' with the vocal
help of Terence Trent D'Arby, is breezy and warm, and ``Meet Me in
My Dreams Tonight'' is a pretty fantasy song. Wilson's old Beach
Boy mates don't appear, but the a capella ``One for the Boys'' is a
worthy tribute.
   And the eight-minute concept song, ``Rio Grande,'' is not the
disaster that its length and lyrics suggest.
   No, Brian Wilson doesn't embarrass himself with this effort. But
don't throw away your old Beach Boy albums.
   _ By David Bauder, Associated Press Writer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Release Anytime</NOTE>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
