<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2takes   08-09 0487</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 takes,0508</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate has approved a $3.9 billion
drought-relief bill designed to aid farmers and ranchers battered
by one of the driest growing seasons on record.
   The legislation, the most expensive disaster relief measure ever
enacted for agriculture, was expected to receive final legislative
approval in the House as early as today. President Reagan is
expected to sign it into law within days of receiving it.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Labor Secretary Ann McLaughlin announced a
$14.8 million plan to meet the emergency survival needs of
thousands of migrant and seasonal farm workers left without money
or jobs because of the drought.
   Mrs. McLaughlin said Monday she has authorized migrant worker
programs operating under Labor Department grants to use up to 15
percent of their current funding for services such as health care,
transportation and temporary shelter. The agency said that could
mean up to $9.5 million may be spent.
   She said another $5 million has been set aside from a reserve
account to be used for migrant workers hurt by the drought.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Detroit News and Detroit Free Press will
be allowed to merge their business and production operations
because the Free Press was in danger of financial failure stemming
from years of steady and apparently irreversible losses, Attorney
General Edwin Meese III said.
   In approving the application for a joint operating agreement on
Monday, Meese rejected the recommendation of a Justice Department
administrative law judge who said the newspapers' pricing policies
were unrealistic.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS Inc., which owns fewer television stations
than either of its two main broadcast competitors, said it has
agreed to buy an independent television station in Miami for $59
million.
   CBS said Monday the agreement to acquire WCIX-TV from TVX
Broadcasting Group Inc. also calls for it to assume certain program
obligations, which a CBS spokesman said were valued at about $13
million.
   The deal would give CBS five stations, while the parents of the
NBC network own seven and the ABC network own eight.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interco Inc. has rejected as inadequate a
sweetened $2.68 billion buyout offer from a Washington-based
investor group, and took moves to strengthen its defenses against
an unwanted takeover.
   The manufacturer and retailer of apparel and furniture stated
that in addition to rejecting the $70 a share merger proposal
offered earlier Monday by City Capital Associates, its board of
directors approved a plan to sell the company's apparel division,
which accounts for nearly a fourth of its sales.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hollywood producers and scriptwriters are
scrambling to regroup after a 22-week strike that idled thousands
and devastated the fall television schedule.
   Production companies began work Monday on the fall season after
the Writers Guild of America membership approved a new contract.
The fall season's start will be delayed, perhaps until mid-October
or later.
</TEXT>
