<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stadd   08-09 0531</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st add,0554</2ND_LINE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's biggest airline company, Texas Air Corp., has
reported its second-quarter net loss widened sharply, while Trans
World Airlines Inc. said its profit after taxes nearly doubled.
   Texas Air said Monday its net loss widened to $255.9 million
from a loss of $27 million in the second quarter of 1987. The
company blamed a significant part of the loss on government
investigations of alleged safety problems at its two main
subsidiaries, Continental Airlines and Eastern Airlines.
   TWA said its profit almost doubled from a year earlier, largely
due to a cash payment it received from a lawsuit against the estate
of its former owner, the late Howard Hughes.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A defense lawyer for Nelson Bunker Hunt has
denied the Texas oil tycoon and his two brothers were part of a
conspiracy to corner the world silver market, and pointed to their
billion-dollar loss as proof of their innocence.
   Hunt and his two younger brothers are being sued for $150
million by Minpeco SA, a South American silver concern that claims
the Hunts manipulated the world silver market between 1979 and 1980.
   Paul J. Curran noted in closing arguments to a federal jury
Monday the Hunts lost more than $1 billion when the silver market
collapsed in 1980.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seat belt use has curtailed the number of
traffic fatalities, but there is no clear-cut evidence that belt
use laws have reduced the number of injuries in highway accidents,
an insurance industry study claims.
   The report Monday by the Highway Loss Data Institute outlined
the results of a study of automobile accident injury claims before
and after the enactment of mandatory auto seat belt use laws in
eight states.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan is expected to sign
legislation to require nuclear power companies to take a bigger
financial responsibility for damages arising from a reactor
accident, an administration official said.
   ``It is likely that he will sign it,'' said the Office of
Management and Budget official, who spoke Monday on condition of
anonymity.
   The proposed 15-year renewal of the 1957 Price-Anderson Act won
final congressional approval Friday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Airlines will pay $70,000 to resolve
a government complaint that it discriminated against flight
attendant applicants based on their citizenship status, the Justice
Department says.
   The settlement announced Monday will cost the air carrier
$53,000 in back pay and $17,000 in federal civil penalties.
   The agreement will affect 33 applicants who qualified as
``intending citizens,'' but whom American refused to consider for
employment _ either because they could not produce an alien
registration card or because their cards had expiration dates.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market posted its third straight loss Monday. The Dow
Jones average of 30 industrials, down 14.94 points last Thursday
and Friday, fell another 11.73 to 2,107.40.
   The dollar finished higher against most major currencies despite
concerted central bank intervention to stem its rise.
   Bond prices were mixed.
   Corn, oat and soybean futures plunged their permitted daily
limits; livestock and meat futures were mixed; energy futures
advanced; precious metals fell; and stock-index futures retreated.
</TEXT>
