<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     08-09 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Surge on News of Gulf Cease-Fire</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The announcement of an imminent cease-fire in
the 8-year-old war between Iran and Iraq has boosted oil futures
prices.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the contract for September
delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S.
crude oil, advanced 61 cents Monday to close at $15.87 a barrel.
   Prices of refined oil products traded on theexchange also
soared. Wholesale heating oil for September delivery jumped 1.46
cents a gallon to finish at 44.50 cents, while wholesale unleaded
gasoline for September rose 1.42 cents to 46.65 cents.
   U.N. Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar announced that
Iran and Iraq would begin a cease-fire in their Persian Gulf war on
Aug. 20. The news followed several days of intense diplomacy that
ended a deadlock in nearly two weeks of U.N.-mediated truce talks.
   ``The notice of a cease-fire was the primary positive,'' said
Fred Demler, an economist for Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   Many oil traders believe the cease-fire will lead to more
cohesion within the 13-nation Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries, of which Iran and Iraq are members. That could lead to a
reduction of overproduction by they and other OPEC members.
   But other traders are more skeptical. They warn that Iran and
Iraq will badly need oil revenues after the war to rebuild their
ravaged economies, and will be tempted to continue to exceed their
official OPEC production quotas.
   Demler said the advance in futures prices also was fueled by
technical market factors.
</TEXT>
