<1ST_LINE>r f PM-TreasuryBills     08-09 0176</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Treasury Bills,0182</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yields on Short-Term T-Bills Hit Pre-Crash High</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities rose in the government's latest auction to the highest
level since before the October stock market crash.
   The Treasury Department sold $6.8 billion in three-month bills
at an average discount rate of 6.94 percent on Monday, up from 6.89
percent last week. Another $6.8 billion was sold in six-month bills
at an average discount rate of 7.26 percent, up from 7.15 percent
last week.
   The rates were the highest since Oct. 13, when three-month bills
sold for 6.96 percent and six-month bills averaged 7.34 percent.
   The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors
_ 7.16 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling
for $9,824.60 and 7.64 percent for a six-month bill selling for
$9,633.00.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said the average yield
for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index for making
changes in adjustable rate mortgages, rose to 7.89 percent last
week from 7.85 percent the previous week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
