<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-88 0157EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-CBS-TVStation Bjt   08-09 0608</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CBS-TV Station, Bjt,0626</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CBS Agrees To Buy Independent TV Station in Miami</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS Inc., flush with cash from sale of major
non-broadcasting assets, says it plans to look for more prospects
in the wake of its agreement to purchase an independent television
station in Miami for $59 million.
   CBS said Monday that its agreement to acquire WCIX-TV from TVX
Broadcast Group Inc. of Norfolk, Va., also calls for it to assume
certain program obligations, which a CBS spokesman said were valued
at about $13 million.
   Laurence A. Tisch, CBS president, in announcing the deal said
``we are continuing to evaluate other potential properties with an
eye toward further acquisitions.''
   Financial analysts said the deal seemed good for CBS and Tisch,
who had been faulted for failing to buy more stations with the $3
billion amassed by selling assets such as its records and magazine
businesses.
   On Wall Street, CBS stock slipped 12{ cents a share to $162.87{
on the New York Stock Exchange.
   The purchase of the station, which is subject to regulatory
approval, would allow CBS to maintain its presence in the
fast-growing Miami television market at only a fraction of the
price a network affiliate likely would have commanded. Miami is the
nation's 16th largest TV market.
   CBS was outbid last year in an effort to buy its Miami
affiliate, WTVJ, by General Electric Co.'s National Broadcasting
Co., which offered $270 million. WTVJ still carries CBS programs
under an affiliation agreement that ends in January, when it is
expected to become an NBC affiliate.
   Peter Appert, a media analyst for the investment firm C.J.
Lawrence, Morgan Grenfell Inc., said the WCIX purchase ``looks like
an excellent deal.''
   ``They bought a new network affiliate station for an incredibly
low price,'' he said.
   Appert said independent stations command lower prices because
they have higher programming costs, attract smaller audiences and
generate lower advertising revenue. Affiliates get some programming
from the network and often can charge higher ad rates for programs
such as local news that may appear just before network programs, he
said.
   Barry Kaplan, media analyst for Goldman, Sachs & Co., said
buying an independent station ``might send a dangerous signal'' to
CBS affiliates who have a competing independent station in their
market.
   ``There might be a risk in any market where there is a VHF
independent,'' he said. A VHF station is one operating on Channels
2 through 13.
   But Philip Jones, vice president and general manager of KCTV in
Kansas City, Mo., and a former head of the CBS affiliates board,
said there were only a handful of markets where that situation
existed. ``It sounds to me like it's a smart buy,'' he said.
   Affiliates had been urging Tisch to buy a few stations to
demonstrate his commitment to the network. Tisch told them he
wanted to do so, but that the asking prices were too high.
   CBS owns television stations in New York, Los Angeles, Chicago
and Philadelphia that reach 19.4 percent of the country's viewers.
With WCIX, its stations would reach 20.8 percent of the country.
   NBC's parent has seven stations reaching 22.4 percent of the
country; Capital Cities-ABC Inc. has eight stations reaching 24.4
percent.
   Federal Communications Commission regulations limit network
companies to owning a maximum of 12 stations reaching 25 percent of
the country.
   CBS also announced Monday that WPEC-TV in West Palm Beach, Fla.,
would become a CBS affiliate in January. The station is now an ABC
affiliate, and the signing is seen as helping CBS reach an audience
north of Miami where the WCIX signal is weak.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
