<HEAD>Dollar Steady In Calm European Trading, Gold Falls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was holding steady in calm European
trading late this morning, and traders said they generally expect
the market to take a one-day breather before pushing the U.S.
currency higher.
   Gold prices fell.
   Traders said there was some light profit-taking following
Monday's gain, but that market sentiment still calls for a higher
dollar.
   ``The dollar is fundamentally strong. We could see just a minor
decline before it takes off again,'' one Rome trader said. ``We are
probably in a phase of rest in anticipation of a new rally.''
   In London, the British pound was quoted at $1.7050, compared
with $1.7022 Monday.
   Other dollar rates at mid-morning, compared with late Monday's
rates, included: 1.8968 West German marks, down from 1.9000; 1.5850
Swiss francs, down from 1.5857; 6.3975 French francs, up from
6.3950; 2.1403 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1435; 1,399.40 Italian
lire, down from 1,399.50; 1.2105 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2097.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends before Europe's begins,
the dollar fell 0.39 yen to a closing 133.58 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted higher at 133.70 yen.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $430.80 a troy ounce,
down from late Monday's $432.25. At mid-morning today, the city's
five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $428.25.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $428.20, down from $432.00 late
Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $3.39 to close at a bid $430.61.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.69 a troy
ounce, down from Monday's $6.78.
</TEXT>
