<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0242</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Down; Share Prices Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar edged down slightly against the Japanese
yen today, while share prices dropped for the third straight day on
the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
   After opening at 133.62 yen, down from Monday's close of 133.97
yen, the dollar remained in a narrow range between 133.52 and
133.73 yen in slow trading. It closed at 133.58 yen, down 0.39 yen
from Monday's close.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, a 109.06-point loser Monday, lost 82.76 points, or
0.29 percent, to close at 28,170.36.
   Volume traded on the first section of the exchange was a light
650 million shares. The volume has plunged drastically since Monday
when it declined to 650 million shares, the first time the daily
volume traded fell below 1 billion shares since July 25.
   Dealers said investors were not active in the market because
Japan is entering a major holiday season.
   ``As seen in the low volume, the market is not moving
energetically and only limited shares are being traded,'' said a
dealer at a Tokyo securities firm, speaking on condition of
anonymity. ``This situation will likely continue until mid-August.
   ``Most foreign fund managers seem to be out of town for vacation
and there are not many people left in Tokyo who can move a large
amount of funds,'' the dealer added.
</TEXT>
