<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-88 0749EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-LoveCanal     08-09 0680</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Love Canal,0707</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Love Canal's Next 10 Years Will Be As Important As Its First
Decade</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Tuesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DARREN DOPP</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NIAGARA FALLS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ten years after Love Canal was
declared a national disaster area because buried chemicals were
oozing to the surface, the largely abandoned neighborhood remains
at the center of environmental debate.
   The former chemical dump that forced hundreds of families from
their homes has been fenced off and surrounded with clay and
plastic liners to prevent chemicals from leaking into groundwater.
   Corroding drums of chemicals have been separated and complex
runoff monitoring and collection systems have been built.
   But even though the contamination has been largely contained and
state officials have begun to talk about restoring the neighborhood
to residential use, critics think Love Canal and hundreds of
similar sites throughout the nation will remain potential disasters
until a safe disposal method is found.
   ``We've spent the first 10 years catching up on the sins of the
past,'' acknowledged EPA spokesman James Marshall, who noted that
the discovery of Love Canal's threat was largely responsible for
federal toxic waste cleanup legislation.
   ``The future will have to be spent changing industrial processes
and people's attitudes about waste generation,'' Marshall said.
``In many ways the next 10 years will be more important than the
first.''
   Love Canal, an abandoned waterway project, was used by the
Hooker Chemical Co. to dispose of thousands of pounds of chemical
wastes in the 1940s. Hooker made herbicides and pesticides.
   In the 1950s, the canal and its contents were covered and homes
and an elementary school were built. It wasn't until the early
1970s that people began to notice foul smells in their basements
and oily puddles in their yards.
   They also began to notice higher-than-usual incidences of
miscarriages, birth defects, cancer, leukemia, neurological
disease, allergies, epilepsy and suicides.
   But government was slow to react. It took mass protests and town
meetings turned into near riots to prod the state into action.
   On Aug. 7, 1978, President Carter declared a state of emergency
at Love Canal.
   Eventually, 728 homes in a 50-block area were evacuated and the
elementary school and 228 of the houses were torn down.
   The state and federal governments filed multimillion-dollar
lawsuits against Hooker. The cases are still being pursued against
the company's parent, Occidental Chemical Corp.
   Today, inside the fenced dump, crews in protective suits carry
out small projects to shore up containment walls or check
monitoring wells.
   Outside the fence, houses are boarded up and decaying.
   A few are still inhabited.
   ``We always hoped they'd decide that it was safe to live here
and that things would return to normal one day,'' said William
Stevenson, a retiree who stayed in his house two blocks from the
dump site.
   Some 175 other families are awaiting the results of a state
habitability study before returning. State Health Commissioner
David Axelrod is to decide the habitability question this fall.
   If Axelrod determines that the area is habitable, the state will
have to assume liability for those who return, said former resident
Lois Gibbs, now a Washington-based environmental activist.
   ``Will the deeds carry health warning labels?'' she said.
   Gibbs said environmental groups would sue to block resettlement,
arguing that no one knows what levels of exposure to the chemicals
are safe.
   If Love Canal is declared unsafe, it would set a precedent for
people living around toxic waste dumps nationwide. The cost of
relocating those people and cleaning those dumps would be
astronomical, she said.
   The state, however, has vowed not to leave Love Canal a vacant
field as a symbol of environmental disaster.
   ``We have a vision of Love Canal as a usable landscape again,''
state Environmental Conservation Commissioner Thomas Jorling said
recently.
   EPA spokesman Marshall said habitability decisions are being
made across the country, though none are of the same magnitude as
Love Canal.
   ``No situation is risk free,'' he said. ``You can't expect to be
part of a highly developed, industrial society without weighing
risks and ultimately living with them.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880809-0207 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-88 0756EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-DetroitNewspapers-Chronology     08-09 0499</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Detroit Newspapers-Chronology,0522</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>A Chronology Of Events Leading to Partial Merger Of Detroit
Newspapers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are major events leading to Monday's
approval of a joint operating agreement for The Detroit News and
Detroit Free Press:
   May 9, 1986: The Free Press and News apply to the Justice
Department for a limited antitrust exemption allowing a
cost-cutting combination of advertising, circulation and business
operations while news and editorial departments remain separate.
   July 23, 1986: The Justice Department's antitrust division
recommends that Attorney General Edwin Meese II order a public
hearing, saying the papers have not proved the need for a JOA.
   Aug. 22, 1986: A deadline for public comment is extended after
Mayor Coleman Young, unions representing newspaper employees and
some members of Congress call for public hearings.
   Feb. 25, 1987: Meese says he will appoint an administrative law
judge to conduct a hearing.
   May 29, 1987: Young and five unions obtain 30,000 pages of
documents from the newspapers detailing cost-cutting efforts, loss
projections and other items.
   June 1, 1987: The Free Press and News file written testimony
saying the Free Press lost $17 million in 1986, the News lost $12.7
million, and cost cuts or price increases would not save the Free
Press.
   June 30, 1987: The challengers submit exhibits and testimony
that the Free Press does not meet the test of a failing newspaper.
   Aug. 3, 1987: Administrative Law Judge Morton Needelman begins a
hearing in Detroit.
   Aug. 10, 1987: Gannett Co. Inc. Chairman Allen Neuharth
testifies that the News will spend whatever is necessary to defeat
the Free Press if a JOA is denied.
   Aug. 12, 1987: Knight-Ridder Inc. Chairman Alvah H. Chapman Jr.
testifies that he will recommend closing the Free Press if a JOA is
denied. The hearing ends Aug. 24.
   Sept. 23, 1987: The Justice Department's antitrust division
again recommends rejection of a JOA, saying the papers failed to
prove the Free Press is failing.
   Dec. 29, 1987: Needelman recommends that Meese reject the JOA.
   Jan. 10, 1988: ``I am worried. The Free Press could die,'' Free
Press Publisher David Lawrence writes in a front-page column. He
asks readers to write, hundreds respond, the paper runs excerpts.
   Unions call the column a ``corporate propaganda advertisement
mouthing the Knight-Ridder line.''
   Jan. 21, 1988: The Knight-Ridder board votes to close the Free
Press if a JOA is denied.
   Feb. 7, 1988: A mailers union drops its opposition to the JOA in
return for job protection, buyouts and severance pay.
   Feb. 11, 1988: Young drops his opposition, saying a JOA is
better than a one-newspaper town.
   Feb. 15, 1988: Unions representing press workers drop opposition
to the JOA.
   Feb. 16, 1988: Officers of Teamsters Local 372, the largest
union, and unions representing typographers and photoengravers drop
their opposition, leaving the Newspaper Guild of Detroit and the
antitrust division as the remaining opponents.
   July 25, 1988: The Newspaper Guild Local 22 drops its opposition
to the JOA.
   Aug. 8, 1988: Meese approves the JOA.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880809-0208 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-88 0819EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-HuntBrothers-Silver     08-09 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hunt Brothers-Silver,0387</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Hunts' Lawyer: No Evidence of Silver Conspiracy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A defense lawyer for Nelson Bunker Hunt says
there's no evidence that the Texas oil tycoon and his two brothers
were part of a plot to corner the world silver market nearly 10
years ago.
   Hunt and his two younger brothers are being sued for $150
million by a South American silver concern that claims the
Dallas-based Hunts manipulated the world silver market between 1979
and 1980.
   In his closing argument to the jury Monday at federal court in
Manhattan, Paul J. Curran noted that the Hunts lost more than $1
billion when the silver market collapsed in 1980.
   ``Where is the evidence they made a profit?'' Curran asked the
six-member civil jury. ``If they were part of a conspiracy, it was
one spectacular failure.''
   The Hunts' Placid Oil Co. and their three individual trusts,
which control Penrod Drilling Co., are in bankruptcy proceedings.
   Curran said the Hunts were victims just like other silver
investors.
   ``They believed too much in silver. They played and they paid,''
said Curran.
   Minpeco S.A., a mineral marketing company owned by the Peruvian
government, claims in a federal civil action that the brothers _
Nelson Bunker Hunt, 62; William Herbert Hunt, 59, who also has
extensive real estate holdings, and Lamar Hunt, 56, owner of the
National Football League Kansas City Chiefs _ conspired
unsuccessfully with several Middle East businessmen to corner the
world silver market.
   The trial before U.S. District Judge Morris E. Lasker began in
February.
   Lawyers for Minpeco claim the Hunts and their Middle Eastern
co-defendants were responsible for the sharp rise in silver prices
from about $9 an ounce to more than $50 an ounce between September
1979 and January 1980.
   Minpeco had a large short position in the silver futures market,
which meant it would make money on dropping silver prices and lose
money on rising prices.
   Minpeco claimed it lost more than $100 million due to
skyrocketing silver prices that fell back to about $10 an ounce in
March 1980.
   Six financial institutions accused of participating in the
alleged conspiracy have settled with Minpeco for a total of $64.6
million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880809-0209 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-88 0852EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-SnowflakeEnvelope     08-09 0175</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Snowflake Envelope,0181</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Postal Service to Offer Stamped Envelope for Cards</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Postal Service will offer a new type
of pre-stamped envelope this year, hoping to pick up some extra
holiday business.
   The envelope is to be produced in a new, 5-inch by 7{-inch size,
which officials say will accommodate many cards, invitations and
similar items.
   The envelopes will be pre-printed with 25-cent first-class
postage in the form of an embossed snowflake, white on a green
background. It will also carry the statement ``First Class'' in
green and ``25 USA'' and the legend ``Holiday Greetings'' printed
in red.
   The new envelopes, the first new size to be issued in a
quarter-century, will go on sale Sept. 8 in Snowflake, Ariz., and
the following day in the rest of the country.
   The price will be 30 cents per envelope, although discounts will
drop the cost to about 27 cents on quantities of 500 or more. In
addition, the envelopes can be ordered with a pre-printed return
address for an added fee.
</TEXT>
