<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-88 0904EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-ElDoradoMotor     08-09 0150</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-ElDorado Motor,0157</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ElDorado Motor To Sell Division</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ElDorado Motor Corp. plans to sell its
small-bus manufacturing division to a recreational vehicle producer
in Ohio.
   The Minneaopolis-based company, which employs about 600 people,
has reached an agreement in principle to sell the division to Thor
Industries for an undisclosed amount.
   The bus division accounted for about $28 million of ElDorado's
$75.5 million in sales during fiscal year 1987, said Gregory
Stewart, company president. ElDorado makes small and midsize buses
such as airport and rental car company shuttle buses.
   Stewart said the company expected to lose money in the fiscal
year that ended June 30. The company lost $106,000 in 1987.
   Thor, which is based in Jackson Center, Ohio, had profits of
$12.6 million on sales of $165 million in 1987.
   Stewart said that Thor did not plan to move the bus division out
of Minneapolis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
