<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Britain-InsuranceRates     08-09 0249</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Insurance Rates,0259</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Insurers Slash Cargo Rates in Persian Gulf</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Insurers on Tuesday slashed by up to 33 percent
their rates for insuring cargoes in the Persian Gulf, following the
announcement of a firm date for a cease-fire between Iran and Iraq.
   The cuts are the first since the possibility of a cease-fire
between the two countries was announced three weeks ago.
   United Nations Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar on
Monday announced that the truce would begin Aug. 20.
   The Lloyd's of London insurance market and the Institute of
London Underwriters announced that the insurance rate for cargoes
going to most places in Iran was cut to 0.375 percent of the value
of the shipment, effective immediately, from 0.5 percent.
   The rate for insuring oil going to both the northern and
southern areas of the Gulf was cut to 0.25 percent from 0.375
percent of its value.
   Rates for air cargo to Iran and Iraq also were reduced to 0.25
percent from 0.375 percent.
   The two institutions' joint War Risks Rating Committee said,
``The reductions have been made in consequence of the recent
substantial improvement in the casualty experience and the
encouraging news concerning efforts to bring an end to the fighting.
   ``It is anticipated that a further review will take place when
it becomes clear that an effective cease-fire has been agreed.''
   David Larner, a spokesman for Lloyd's said, ``One could expect
them to come down further if the cease-fire is seen to hold.''
</TEXT>
