<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-88 0956EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-China-SellingLand     08-09 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-China-Selling Land,0399</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japanese Company First Foreign Firm to Lease Land in China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Japanese company on Monday became the first
foreign firm to ``buy'' land from the Chinese government in public
tender bidding.
   The official Xinhua news agency said Sun Enterprises Ltd. of
Japan beat out five other firms to win rights to use a
12,900-square-meter (139,320-square-foot) plot in Shanghai's
Hongqiao economic development zone for 50 years.
   The report said the company will pay 104.16 million yuan ($28
million) for the land. It plans to construct apartment and office
buildings, restaurants, stores and recreational facilities there.
   The selling of land-use rights is the latest, and one of the
more controversial, measures taken by the Beijing government to
raise badly needed capital for economic development.
   Last month the city of Shenzhen, a special economic zone across
the border from Hong Kong, held China's first land auction, with
two Chinese companies winning the bidding for property development
sites.
   Land in socialist China technically all belongs to the state,
but economists are now arguing that a market in land-use rights
will bring in needed capital, bring about a more efficient use of
land and speed up urban development.
   In the countryside, family farms that were rehabilitated with
the start of agricultural reforms in 1979 usually have 10- to
15-year contracts for farming a plot of land, but normally do not
pay rent to the state.
   In the cities, most Chinese factories and buildings occupy land
without charge for unlimited periods.
   The National People's Congress, China's legislature, paved the
way for land-use sales last April when it amended the constitution
to eliminate a prohibition against leasing land and added the
sentence ``land-use rights according to legal regulation can be
transferred.''
   Some rural areas now allow residents not using their land to
lease it to more ambitious farmers needing larger tracts. The
government at the end of last year also named seven urban areas
that may experiment with land-use sales: Shenzhen, Shanghai,
Canton, Tianjin, Hainan, Fuzhou and Xiamen.
   Communist Party General Secretary Zhao Ziyang, however, stressed
recently that public ownership will remain dominant in China. His
statement appeared to be meant to assuage other party leaders
worried that China was losing its socialist character with the
emergence of thriving private enterprises and the selling of state
land.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
