<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet10am     08-09 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 10am,0410</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market moved sharply lower today in
reaction to news that the Federal Reserve boosted its key bank
lending rate, but then recovered somewhat.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which fell about 23
points following the announcement, was off 10.66 at 2,096.73 in the
first half hour of trading.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 4 to 3 in the overall tally
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 346 issues up, 469
down and 585 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board came to 56.49 million shares as of 10
a.m. on Wall Street.
   The Fed announced it was hiking the discount rate to 6.5 percent
from 6 percent shortly after the market opened. The increase, which
traders had been anticipating, marks the first change in the rate
since Sept. 7 and put the rate at its highest in more than two
years.
   The Fed, in a statement, said its decision ``reflects the intent
of the Federal Reserve to reduce inflationary pressures'' and ``was
taken in light of the growing spread of market interest rates over
the discount rate.''
   The boost is expected to send a variety of other interest rates
higher, including those on credit cards and mortgages.
   Analysts said they expected an initial selloff following the
news but were cautiously optimistic that the market could weather
the increase.
   ``Since last week's unemployment figures, we've been hearing the
drumbeat that the Fed would have to tighten,'' said Larry Wachtel,
first vice president at Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. ``Now
we'll wait to see whether the Street prepared for it.''
   Last week the Labor Department reported better-than-expected
employment data for July and also revised June data upward.
   Among actively traded issues, General Electric was unchanged at
41{; Boeing was off { at 60; IBM was off ] at 122}, and American
Express was unchanged at 28.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell
0.92 to 151.60. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down 1.21 at 303.02.
   On Monday the Dow Jones industrial average fell 11.73 to
2,107.40.
   Declining issues outnumbered advances by about 7 to 5 on the
NYSE, with 565 up, 774 down and 589 unchanged. Big Board volume
came to 148.80 million shares, against 113.40 million in the
previous session.
</TEXT>
