<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet11am     08-09 0465</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 11am,0486</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market fell sharply today in reaction
to news that the Federal Reserve boosted its key bank lending rate,
but analysts were optimistic the market could weather higher
interest rates.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was off 27.39 at
2,080.01 in the first hour and a half of trading.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 15 to 4 in the overall tally
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 261 issues up, 968
down and 506 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board, augmented by dividend-related moves and
computer-triggered sell programs, came to 95.17 million shares as
of 11 a.m. on Wall Street.
   The Fed announced it was hiking the discount rate to 6.5 percent
from 6 percent shortly after the market opened. The increase marks
the first change in the rate since Sept. 7 and put the rate at its
highest in more than two years.
   The Fed said in a statement that its decision, which likely will
be mirrored in other interest rates like those on credit cards and
mortgages, ``reflects the intent of the Federal Reserve to reduce
inflationary pressure.''
   Analysts said they expected an initial selloff following the
news but were cautiously optimistic that the market could digest
the increase in a matter of days.
   ``Some (investors) already are reacting positively, feeling that
the sooner the medicine is administered, the quicker the patient
will recover,'' said Michael Metz, vice president and technical
anlayst at Oppenheimer & Co.
   With the dollar was up sharply on the announcement, analysts
predicted more foreign funds will shift into dollar-denominated
instruments and support stocks and bonds.
   While analysts had expected the Fed to tighten its reins on the
money supply this week, few expected a change in the discount rate,
which is the most dramatic move the Fed can take. Most were
anticipating the Fed to push up the federal funds rate, the
interest banks charge each other for overnight loans.
   ``The feeling was that the Fed would use the federal funds rate
rather than take this sudden, draconian measure,'' Metz said.
   He noted, however, that the action ``enhances the credibility of
the Fed'' among those who thought the central bank would refrain
from making any decisive move before November's presidential
election.
   Among actively traded Big Board issues, Houston Industries fell
] to 31| with more than 33 million shares changing hands as traders
moved to capture the company's dividend.
   Elsewhere, General Electric was down ] at 41[; IBM was off | at
122{; Ford Motor fell | to 52], and American Express was down \ at
27}.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell
1.63 to 150.89. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down 1.93 at 302.30.
</TEXT>
