<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   08-09 0376</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0388</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mostly higher
today on the Chicago Board of Trade in reaction to a private crop
analyst's prediction of a sharp drop in corn and soybean production.
   The widely-followed analyst Conrad Leslie of Chicago pegged 1988
soybean production at 1.48 billion bushels, compared with actual
production of 1.91 billion bushels last year. Leslie estimated U.S.
corn production this year at 4.28 billion bushels, compared with
7.06 billion bushels harvested last year.
   Leslie's numbers fell near the low end of other private
estimates that have been released in advance of the Agriculture
Department's estimate on Thursday. In its July crop report, the
USDA pegged 1988 soybean production at 1.65 billion bushels and
corn production at 5.2 billion bushels.
   Although traders are eagerly awaiting the USDA report, which
will be based crop conditions as of Aug. 1, the official numbers
may have little market impact, said Cathy Leow, an assistant vice
president in charge of grain futures trading at Thomson McKinnon
Securities Inc. in New York.
   ``When the USDA comes out with its number, people are most
likely going to say it's too high because the survey was taken
prior to the extreme heat we experienced last week,'' Ms. Leow said.
   In early trading, wheat was 3 cents to 4 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.80 a bushel; corn was 2{
cents to 3 cents higher with September at $2.99 a bushel; oats were
1 cent lower to 1 cent higher with September at $2.74 a bushel; and
soybeans were 3{ cents to 14 cents higher with August at $8.54 a
bushel.
   Cattle futures were mostly higher while pork futures were mixed
in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .30 cent to .40 cent higher with August at
68.85 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent lower to .43 cent
higher with August at 79.60 cents a pound; hogs were .15 cent lower
to .30 cent higher with August at 45.67 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .10 cent lower to 1 cent higher with August at 33.15
cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mostly lower on Monday.
</TEXT>
