<DOCNO> AP880809-0219 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-88 0632EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-Australia-Wine Adv13-14   08-09 0884</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Australia-Wine, Adv 13-14,0913</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 13</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 14</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions Aug. 13-14 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Wine Joins List of Australian Fascinations</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WINSOR DOBBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crocodile Dundee might prefer to knock
back a beer, but wine drinkers around the world are toasting their
fascination with life Down Under by sipping more Australian wine
than ever before.
   The explosion of interest in Australia's premium labels has
resulted in some shortages and higher prices, as vintners struggle
to keep pace with rising demand both here and overseas.
   Frost and hailstorms in some parts of South Australia prior to
the 1988 vintage also have cut into supplies.
   ``Many Australians are drinking better quality wine,'' said
leading wine writer Huon Hooke of the Sydney Morning Herald. ``They
want quality product, but much of that product is committed
overseas.''
   Contributing to the popularity of Aussie wines is the general
bull market for things Australian, including actor Paul Hogan and
his carefree Crocodile Dundee character. Ironically, Hogan can be
seen in American television commercials, turning up his nose to
fine wine tasting in favor of a frothy glass of beer.
   Also aiding the Australian industry is a trend away from
European wines after the Chernobyl nuclear disaster sparked fears
of fallout across Europe and scandals over illegal additives
scarred the Austrian wine industry.
   Statistics show domestic consumers are drinking a better class
of wine and deserting the taditional cask, or boxed wine. Wine
sales in a country previously noted for its beer drinking have
doubled over the past decade to 329 million liters last year.
   The increased popularity of premium wines has led to price rises
of up to 30 percent locally and arguments from Australian retailers
that producers should supply the local market ahead of the
lucrative export markets of Sweden, the United States and Britain.
   The winemakers, looking to the future, are continuing to export
enthusiastically.
   Australian wine is a competitor for Californian wine in many
markets. It is particularly popular in northern Europe, accounting
for 10 percent of all wine imports into Sweden _ 7 million liters
in the 1986-87 financial year.
   Britain imported 4.5 million liters that year, and the figure is
expected to rise considerably in 1987-88.
   The Australian Wine and Brandy Corp., the government-funded
marketing authority, said exports to Japan were up 62 percent last
year to 2.7 million liters.
   ``Dollar for dollar we offer the best value quality wine
available around the world,'' said Brian McGuigan, managing
director of the high-profile Wyndham Estate Group.
   The Australian Bureau of Statistics reports that wine exports
now total over 30 million liters annually, almost 10 percent of the
total production.
   ``We are having great difficulty in meeting the demand for our
wines,'' said Jim Williams, director of trading for Penfolds, which
makes Grange Hermitage, Australia's world-class red wine. Penfolds
is the largest winemaking group in Australia and the largest
exporter.
   Grapes have been grown in Australia since the first fleet of
convict settlers arrived from England in 1788. The industry has
been revolutionized over the past 20 years with the introduction of
new technology, which led to the production of high-quality table
wines.
   ``But there is a great deal of resentment in the United
Kingdom,'' warned Chris Anstee, a spokesman for the Lindemans
Group. ``Dealers feel they are being cheated, having made an
initial investment in promoting Australian wine and being told
Australia cannot meet the demand.''
   That echoes complaints at home.
   ``Countries like Argentina and Chile are ready to service our
consumers if the local industry can't meet local demands,'' said
Lance Hogan, a buyer for a bulk distribution company.
   Industry analysts predict the under-supply of premium products,
which retail from around $5 U.S. domestically, could last for three
to four years. They also predict exports could rise to 25 percent
of production within five years.
   But some experts in the industry believe the current premium
shortage will be short-lived and has been aggravated by the unusual
weather.
   ``We have better, cheaper land here than anywhere in the
northern hemisphere and our production costs are less,'' said
McGuigan.
   ``The current shortage, mainly of Chardonnay, is a temporary
aberration. With the potential we have, we can't afford to stand
still. We are the world's vineyard of the future.''
   There are now some 500 wineries spread across the country. Among
the premier wine-producing districts are the Barossa and Clare
valleys and McLaren Vale in South Australia, the Yarra Valley in
Victoria and the Hunter Valley in New South Wales. There are
numerous other small areas where grapes are grown.
   Despite tight supplies, some winemakers believe now is the time
to cultivate new customers. The Rosemount Estate Group, headed by
former international winemaker of the year Philip Shaw, has set up
offices in Ignacio, Calif., and Britain, and is currently exporting
to Japan, Canada and Sweden, among others.
   ``Rosemount is actively pursuing export markets,'' said managing
director Chris Hancock.
   Gordon Grant, managing director of the Ryecroft Company,
believes there are still huge opportunities for Australian makers,
particularly in the United States market.
   ``People overseas rarely know if they are eating Australian
beef, or wearing Australian wool, but our wine is seen as an
Australian product,'' said Grant. ``It is an ambassador in a
glass.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>End Weekend Editions Aug. 13-14</HEAD>
