<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-88 1315EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-DiscountRate 3rdLd-Writethru f0077 08-09 1018</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Discount Rate, 3rd Ld-Writethru, f0077,1043</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 1 grafs White House comment after 2nd graf pvs;
inserts 2 grafs further after 8th graf pvs, ``I think ... Also
moving on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Reserve Board announced today it
is boosting its key bank lending rate from 6 percent to 6.5
percent, raising the possibility that other interest rates,
including those on credit cards and mortgages, will go higher too.
   The Fed, in a statement, said its decision ``reflects the intent
of the Federal Reserve to reduce inflationary pressures'' and ``was
taken in light of the growing spread of market interest rates over
the discount rate.''
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Reagan
administration officials were disappointed by the action.
   It was the first change in the central bank's discount rate
since Sept. 4 and put the rate at its highest in more than two
years.
   The increase, effective immediately, set the discount rate,
which is the fee the Fed charges to make loans to U.S. financial
institutions, at its highest level since April 21, 1986, when it
fell to 6.5 percent from 7 percent.
   Analysts had expected the Fed to tighten its reins on the money
supply this week, but few were expecting an increase in the
discount rate, which is the most dramatic move the Fed can take.
   Most were expecting the Fed to push up the federal funds rate,
the interest banks charge each other for overnight loans, by an
eighth or a quarter of a percentage point from its current 7.75
percent.
   David Wyss, an economist with Data Resources Inc., a Lexington,
Mass., consulting firm, said he had not expected a discount rate
increase from the Fed board, all appointees of President Reagan,
until after the November elections. But, he said, the Fed acted now
rather than in the fall, when the GOP presidential campaign of Vice
President George Bush is in full swing.
   ``I think the timing is very deliberate to do it before the
Republican convention. That's sort of the kick off for the
Republican political ampaign and raising the discount rate now may
be seen as better than interrupting the campaign,'' Wyss said.
   Reagan's spokesman, Marlin Fitzwater, said the White House was
``naturally ... disappointed.'' But he also told reporters:
   ``The Federal Reserve has had the task of trying to balance the
resistance to inflationary pressures with maintenance of real
growth in the economy. ... We believe the Federal Reserve has been
doing a good job of balancing these interests.''
   The likely negative effects of the hike include pushing up the
value of the dollar, which could slow the improvement of the U.S.
trade deficit, Wyss said. The dollar has been appreciating against
foreign currencies since early this year and now stands at an
18-month high against the West German mark. It was the previous
fall in the value of the dollar that shrank the trade deficit.
   Wyss also said that the increase now will likely make government
borrowing this week more costly. The Treasury Department, in its
quarterly auctions, plans to sell $11 billion in 10-year notes
today and $11 billion in three-year notes on Wednesday.
   Tuesday's discount rate increase marked the second under the
reign of Alan Greenspan, who took over as Fed chairman a year ago.
In September, the central bank boosted the rate from 5.5 percent to
6 percent, the first increase in three years.
   That move was also taken in response to inflationary fears, but
was later cited by some analysts as a contributing factor to the
October stock market crash.
   After the crash, the Fed pumped liquidity into the banking
system. It loosened money supplies again in mid-winter, when rising
business inventories raised concern that the economy was softening.
   Since then, however, government statistics have portrayed a
strong economy and concern has shifted from recession to inflation.
Tight labor markets in some areas of the country has been sparking
worry about inflationary increases in wages. Some economists say
steadily rising factory operating rates are likely to contribute to
rising prices for manufactured goods.
   Last month, Greenspan said in congressional testimony that the
Fed ``at this juncture might be well advised to err more on the
side of restrictiveness rather than of stimulus.''
   At that hearing, before the Senate Banking Committee on July 13,
Greenspan had played down the prospect of an immediate increase in
the discount rate after he was asked if he were worried about the
growing gap between the discount rate and the federal funds rate,
which had been increased in a series of small steps since late
March.
   Greenspan replied that ``current relationships are
satisfactory'' and noted that the spread had been greater in the
past.
   Too great a spread between the rates tempts banks to misuse the
``discount window'' by borrowing from the Fed and lending to other
banks.
   In its statement today, the Federal Reserve Board said it
increased the discount rate in response to requests from Federal
Reserve banks in Boston; New York; Philadelphia; Cleveland;
Richmond, Va.; Atlanta; St. Louis; Kansas City, Mo., and San
Francisco.
   As inflationary concerns have mounted in financial markets,
other interest rates, including mortgage rates, have been
increasing. The prime rate, the rate charged by banks to their most
creditworthy customers, was raised by most major banks on July 14
from 9 percent to 9.5 percent, its highest since March 1986.
   Wyss said a further increase in the prime rate could come this
week.
   Among the recent signs of strength in the economy was the July
unemployment rate, which at 5.4 percent was near its 14-year lows.
In addition, the monthly trade deficits for April and May were the
lowest in nearly three years.
   Prior to September, the last increase in the discount rate had
come April 6, 1984, when the rate was boosted from 8.5 percent to 9
percent.
   The rate was then cut seven successive times, with the last
reduction on Aug. 20, 1986, when it dropped from 6 percent to 5.5
percent, the lowest level in nearly a decade.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
