<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-88 1417EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreet2pm     08-09 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 2pm,0506</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market held at sharply lower levels
today after falling in reaction to news that the Federal Reserve
boosted its key bank lending rate.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was off 26.67 at
2,080.73 by midafternoon.
   Losers outnumbered gainers by about 14 to 3 in the overall tally
of New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 266 issues up, 1,167
down and 465 unchanged.
   Big Board volume, augmented by dividend-related moves and
computer-triggered sell programs, came to 158.81 million shares as
of 2 p.m. on Wall Street.
   The market slipped shortly after the opening when the Fed
announced it was hiking the discount rate to 6.5 percent from 6
percent. The increase marks the first change in the rate since
Sept. 7 and puts the rate at its highest level in more than two
years.
   The Fed said its decision, which could be mimicked by other
interest rates like those on credit cards and mortgages, ``reflects
the intent ... to reduce inflationary pressure.''
   Analysts expected an initial selloff following the news but were
cautiously optimistic that the market could digest the increase in
a matter of days.
   Eugene Peroni, a technical analyst at Janney Montgomery Scott in
Philadelphia, said that there wasn't any panic selling going on,
although portfolios were being realigned and consolidated.
   A few investors took the opportunity to hunt for bargains and
even looked on the news as positive. ``The feeling is that the
sooner the medicine is administered, the quicker the patient will
recover,'' said Michael Metz, vice president and technical anlayst
at Oppenheimer & Co.
   With the dollar was up sharply on the announcement, analysts
predicted more foreign funds will shift into dollar-denominated
instruments like stocks and bonds.
   While analysts had expected the Fed to tighten its reins on the
money supply this week, few expected the change would come in the
discount rate, which is the most dramatic move the Fed can take.
Most thought the Fed would push up the federal funds rate, the
interest banks charge each other for overnight loans.
   Metz said, however, that the action enhances the Fed's
credibility among those who thought the central bank would refrain
from making any decisive moves before November's presidential
election.
   Traders were keeping a sharp eye on the credit markets, where
the Treasury's bellwether 30-year bond was off about $7.50 per
$1,000 in face value.
   Among actively traded Big Board issues, Houston Industries fell
] to 31{ with more than 51 million shares changing hands as traders
moved to capture the company's dividend.
   Elsewhere, General Electric was down | at 41; IBM was off 1 at
122]; Ford Motor fell ~ to 52[, and American Express was down { at
27|.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks fell
1.75 to 150.77. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index was down 2.99 301.24.
</TEXT>
