<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Upjohn-Rogaine     08-09 0185</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Upjohn-Rogaine,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Upjohn Nears Final FDA Approval for Baldness Drug</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KALAMAZOO, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A baldness remedy developed by the
Upjohn Co. is one step closer to final federal approval, company
officials said Tuesday.
   The Kalamazoo-based pharmaceutical company said it received an
``approvable letter'' from the U.S. Food and Drug Administration
for its topical minoxidil preparation for the treatment of male
pattern baldness, developed under the trade name Rogaine.
   An approvable letter is ``historically the last step before
final approval'' for marketing, said company spokesman R.D. LaRue.
LaRue said the letter means the scientific data submitted by the
company have been approved, leaving only label language to be
worked out.
   LaRue would not speculate when final approval may be granted.
   After a brief halt in dealing on the New York Stock Exchange,
Upjohn was up about 75 cents at $32.25 a share in active afternoon
trading.
   The drug already is approved for use in several other countries,
including Canada.
   Minoxidil was developed as a blood pressure treatment, but the
company noted about 10 years ago that some of its users experienced
increased hair growth.
</TEXT>
