<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Britain-Stocks 1stLd-Writethru   08-09 0240</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0248</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Fall</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New thruout with closing figures, comment.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices fell sharply Tuesday on the London
Stock Exchange after the U.S. Federal Reserve Board unexpectedly
increased its discount rate by a half percentage point to 6.5
percent.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index fell 13.4
points, or 0.7 percent, to 1,862.6.
   Sharply declining prices on Wall Street pulled London equities
lower, dealers said. The Dow Jones industrial average was off 31.12
points at 2,076.12 as the London session drew to a close.
   ``We're entirely geared to Wall Street at this point,'' one
equity analyst said.
   Volume was a moderate 424.9 million shares, compared with
Monday's 369.2 million shares.
   Dealers said London stock prices were still reeling from
Monday's unexpected half-point rise in the British commercial
banks' base lending rate to 11 percent.
   Some dealers said the increase in the U.S. discount rate, on the
heels of Monday's British rate rise, sparked fears of another round
of global interest rate hikes.
   The move by the U.S. central bank ``has reinforced the message
that the Fed is more concerned about the pace of U.S. economic
expansion than they had given voice to previously,'' said Charles
Larkum, a British equity market analyst at the London investment
firm James Capel and Co.
   The Financial Times 30-share index fell 13.6 points to 1,501.1.
But the Financial Times 500-share index rose 7.79 points to close
at 1,062.61.
</TEXT>
