<1ST_LINE>r f AM-WestinghouseCredit     08-09 0166</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Westinghouse Credit,0174</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Westinghouse Credit Sells Division</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Westinghouse Credit Corp., a subsidiary of
Westinghouse Electric Corp., said Tuesday it has agreed to sell its
Fixed-Asset Lending Division to ``a major U.S. corporation'' it did
not identify.
   Westinghouse said the proposed sale would transfer all the
division's financing receivables and other assets, and about 175
employees in 10 cities. It said its receivables were worth about
$650 million on June 30.
   The terms of the sale were not disclosed.
   Westinghouse said the division ``specializes in secured
financing of income-producing capital equipment and facilities for
middle-market customers'' in the United States, including
construction equipment, machine tools, transportation equipment and
computers.
   It said it also provides financing to major fast-food
franchises, convenience store chains and for used cars.
   Westinghouse said its loans average about $150,000 and mature in
an average of four years.
   It said its division offices are in Pittsburgh, Atlanta, Dallas,
Denver, Los Angeles, Minneapolis, Phoenix, Seattle, San Francisco
and Mount Laurel, N.J.
</TEXT>
