<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-88 1640EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     08-09 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Closing,0288</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market fell deep into negative
territory today in reaction to news that the Federal Reserve
boosted its key bank lending rate, but equities managed to finish
off their worst levels.
   The Fed announced shortly after the opening bell that it was
hiking the discount rate a half a percentage point to 6.5 percent,
its highest level in more than two years. Stock prices immediately
headed south.
   An increase in the discount rate, which is the fee the Fed
charges for short-term loans to member banks, is the central bank's
most direct way of pushing interest rates higher as a curb on
economic growth. Jumps in other interest rates, including those on
mortgage rates and credit cards, are likely to follow.
   Analysts were cautiously optimistic that the market, which had
been anticipating higher interest rates, could digest the hike in
the coming days. They reasoned that with the dollar up sharply on
the announcement, foreign funds will shift into dollar-denominated
instruments like stocks and bonds.
   Eugene Peroni, a technical analyst at Janney Montgomery Scott in
Philadelphia, noted that volume, minus dividend-capturing
strategies, was moderate and that there was no sign of any panic
selling.
   A few investors took the opportunity to hunt for bargains and
even considered the news somewhat positive. ``The feeling is that
the sooner the medicine is administered, the quicker the patient
will recover,'' said Michael Metz, vice president and technical
analyst at Oppenheimer & Co.
   He also said the action enhances the Fed's credibility among
those who thought the central bank would refrain from making any
decisive moves before November's presidential election.
</TEXT>
