<FILEID>AP-NR-08-09-88 1702EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-FishFarm Bjt   08-09 0637</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fish Farm, Bjt,0662</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Entrepreneurs Develop Indoor Fish Farm</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID S. MARTIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KUTZTOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steve Van Gorder and Rick Fahs see the
future of the American fishing industry in farmers' barns and
abandoned inner-city buildings.
   Van Gorder and Fahs, co-founders of Fresh-Culture Systems Inc.,
say they've developed a way to raise 40,000 pounds of fish a year
in tanks fitting in 5,000 square feet of space.
   ``I think people will pay more for a top-quality product they
feel safe with,'' Van Gorder said. Reports of medical waste and
other pollution in the nation's waters has spurred increasing
worries among consumer about the fish they buy, he added.
   The Fresh-Culture system, which sells for about $125,000, is the
first to reduce energy costs enough to economically raise
fresh-water fish indoors in the Northeast and Midwest, Van Gorder
and Fahs claim.
   Striped bass, salmon and other fish grown in the system's 15
cylindrical tanks can be sold to restaurants and fish markets to
meet the growing demand for fish, they say.
   Increasingly health conscious Americans have been eating more
fish in recent years. Consumption per capita has grown from 12.3
pounds in 1982 to 15.4 pounds last year, according to the National
Marine Fisheries Service.
   Christian Herr, a program administrator with the state Bureau of
Agricultural Development, said the technology used in the
Fresh-Culture system is new.
   ``We definitely see that it will be able to be used by our
Pennsylvania farmers that want to diversify,'' Herr said.
   Fahs, a 35-year-old former plant manager with General Mills
Inc., said fish farming also could bring industry back to inner
cities.
   ``You can put this in a burned out building they're selling for
a dollar,'' he said.
   Fish farming itself is not new.
   Catfish have been raised in outdoor ponds for about 20 years.
Trout also is ``farmed'' outdoors in Idaho and elsewhere; and
striped bass is raised in tanks in California and elsewhere.
   Unlike these systems, Fresh-Culture recirculates almost all the
water in the tanks, said Van Gorder, 36, who has been researching
aquaculture for 10 years.
   It also costs little to heat, one of the main stumbling blocks
of previous systems with recirculating water, he said.
   In a small building in Kutztown, a rural eastern Pennsylvania
town, Fahs and Van Gorder are raising striped bass, trout and
tilapia in one of their systems. They say they hope to begin
selling their fish to restaurants in January.
   A 2{ horsepower motor pumps air to the 2,000-gallon tanks and
pushes the water filters for them, while a computer monitors water
temperature and heats the tanks overnight, when energy costs are
lower, Van Gorder said.
   During a power outage, a backup gas-powered air pump is
activated, he added.
   Trout and salmon require temperatures from 60 to 70 degrees,
while striped bass and tilapia need 80-degree water, according to
Van Gorder.
   Fahs said fish can be produced in six months for about $2.50 a
pound after start-up costs, with proper management, and sold for $5
or more to restaurants in the New York City and elsewhere in the
Northeast.
   Aquatic Systems Inc., a San Diego-based company, expects to
harvest 650,000 pounds of striped bass this year from a fish farm
in Mecca, Calif., near Palm Springs, said Timothy Hovanec, an
assistant production manager.
   Unlike Fresh-Culture's system, Aquatic Systems has geothermally
heated tanks and only recirculates some of the water, Hovanec said.
   ``I may be unnecessarily skeptical, but there are at least 20 or
30 people trying to get into striped bass,'' he said.
   Van Gorder and Fahs say they expect the skepticism.
   ``There are a lot of systems on paper,'' Fahs acknowledges.
   But they say they are confident their approach will attract
customers.
   ``It's the freshest, non-polluted source of fish you can get,''
Van Gorder said.
</TEXT>
