<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Chevron-Polymer     08-09 0351</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Chevron-Polymer,0363</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chevron Corp. To Expand Capacity For Polymer Grade Propylene
Manufacture</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chevron Corp., a leading marketer of
polymer grade propylene, announced plans Tuesday to expand capacity
for the manufacture of the chemical at two Texas facilities.
   Chevron plans to expand capacity for the manufacture of polymer
grade propylene at its Port Arthur refinery and Cedar Bayou olefins
plant in Texas, the company said in a statement.
   Polymer grade propylene is a high purity building block chemical
used to make other materials such as polypropylene, which is
extensively used in plastic automobile parts, toys, medical
products and appliances.
   ``Chevron remains strongly committed to the polymer grade
propylene business,'' said George Scott, vice president of Chevron
Chemical Co. and general manager of the Olefins & Derivatives
Division.
   ``The domestic and international propylene consuming businesses
have been expanding rapidly in the past two years, especially
polypropylene. This expansion assures that we will be able to keep
pace with that growth,'' said Scott.
   The expansions, to be constructed in two stages, will add about
350 million pounds to the company's annual capacity to produce
polymer grade propylene. The total capacity will be 1.3 billion
pounds per year.
   The first stage is scheduled to begin in October and will boost
capacity at subsidiary Chevron Chemical Co.'s Olefins & Derivatives
Division plant at Cedar Bayou by about 20 percent to 800 million
pounds by adding propylene splitting towers to its ethylene unit.
   The second stage, anticipated to begin during the fourth quarter
of 1989, will boost capacity at subsidiary Chevron U.S.A.'s Port
Arthur refinery by more than 180 million pounds per year by adding
a new propylene upgrading unit.
   The company said expansion at the two facilities will be
complemented by installation of a new olefin splitter and export
facility at Chevron U.S.A.'s Pascagoula, Miss., refinery, designed
to separate and transport dilute propylene to Texas for further
upgrading.
   In addition, the Galena Park terminal of Chevron subsidiary
Warren Petroleum Co., situated on the Houston Ship Channel, will be
modified to receive and transport this material to Port Arthur and
Cedar Bayou.
</TEXT>
