<1ST_LINE>r f AM-GE-EastGermany     08-09 0187</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-GE-East Germany ,0191</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GE Selling Engines to East German Airline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EVENDALE, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Electric Co. announced Tuesday it
is supplying $55 million worth of jet engines to power three
aircraft for Interflug, East Germany's state-owned airline.
   General Electric officials said Interflug chose the GE-built
CF6-80C2 turbofan engine to power three Airbus Industrie A310-300
jetliners. Delivery of the twin-engine A310s is scheduled to begin
in the first quarter of 1989.
   ``Interflug will be the first Eastern bloc (airline) to operate
GE engines. The U.S. government, by granting the export license for
this sale, has opened the door for additional sales to Eastern
Europe,'' said Lee Kapor, vice president and general manager of
commercial engine operations at GE's Aircraft Engine Business Group
headquarters in Evendale, a Cincinnati suburb.
   In order to comply with U.S. export license requirements, the
West German commercial airline Lufthansa has agreed to perform all
aircraft and engine maintenance in Hamburg, West Germany, GE
officials said.
   Total sales of the CF6-80C2 jet engines stand at $6 billion.
General Electric said it has orders from 40 customers to supply
engines for 303 aircraft.
</TEXT>
