<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp 1stLd-Writethru f0256 08-09 0816</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0256,0843</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rain Fears Rein In Soybean Rally</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS 20th graf pvs, Gold settled ... to fix gold's
direction to lower sted higher; Picks up 21st graf pvs, Cattle
futures ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Prospects of a second night of rain in the central Corn Belt
limited rallies in corn and soybean futures prices Tuesday, despite
an influential private report indicating severe drought damage to
the crops.
   Wheat futures also gained slightly on the Chicago Board of Trade
while oat futures closed lower.
   On other markets, coffee futures rose sharply, precious metals
declined; livestock and meat were mixed; energy futures were lower;
and stock-index futures retreated.
   A report from the respected Chicago-based crop analyst Conrad
Leslie generated buying interest in crop futures.
   Leslie estimated 1988 U.S. soybean production at 1.48 billion
bushels, down 23 percent from last year's actual production of 1.91
billion bushels, and corn production at 4.28 billion bushels, a 39
percent drop from the 7.06 billion bushels harvested last year.
   ``This means the worst drought of the century is producing the
smallest U.S. corn crop since 1970,'' Leslie said in his report.
   Leslie also reported signs of spider mite damage to soybean
plants in Illinois and Iowa. Even if such plants received rain, he
said, ``they may only stabili the contract for
delivery in September at $3.79\ a bushel; corn was 1 cent to 4\
cents higher with September at $2.99 a bushel; oats were 1 cent to
5{ cents lower with September at $2.68 a bushel; and soybeans were
3{ cents to 20 cents higher with August at $8.55} a bushel.
   Coffee futures prices surged in light trading on New York's
Coffee, Sugar & Cocoa Exchange but analysts said the rally was
technical in nature and not related to any new developments within
the International Coffee Organization.
   Light buying by coffee roasters nudged prices past a key
technical point, which triggered a broader rally, said Sandra Kaul,
coffee analyst in New York with Shearson, Lehman Hutton Inc.
   Coffee for September delivery settled 3.81 cents higher at
$1.1834 a pound.
   Gold and silver futures retreated on New York's Commodity
Exchange after the Federal Reserve Board announced it was boosting
the discount rate from 6 percent to 6.5 percent.
   But Richard Levine, vice president of the precious metals and
foreign exchange group at Elders Futures Inc. in New York, said the
sell-off was precipitated by weak technical factors, not by
prospects of lower inflation.
   ``Short-term technicals were bearish before the Fed had anything
to say,'' he said.
   Gold settled $2.80 to $3 lower with August at $427.40 a troy
ounce; silver was 8.5 cents to 8.8 cents lower with September at
$6.63 a troy ounce.
   Cattle futures finished mixed on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange
amid conflicting views about future beef demand and cash prices,
analysts said. Pork futures retreated on weakening cash prices.
   Live cattle settled .28 cent lower to .38 cent higher with
August at 68.25 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent lower to
.53 cent higher with August at 79.90 cents a pound; hogs were .15
cent to 1.30 cents lower with August at 45.45 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were .15 cent to .45 cent lower with August at 32.80
cents a pound.
   Oil prices weakened in quiet trading on the New York Mercantile
Exchange. Analysts said the slump was a reaction to Monday's sharp
runup.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 19 cents to 30 cents
lower with September at $15.68 a barrel; heating oil was .43 cent
to .53 cent lower with September at 44.07 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .35 cent to .61 cent lower with September at 46.15
cents a pound.
   Stock-index futures retreated on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, where the contract for September delivery of the Standard
& Poor's 500 index settled 2.40 points lower at 267.40.
