<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Drexel-StaleyCommodities     08-09 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Drexel-Staley Commodities,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drexel Buys Staley Commodity Brokerage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investment banker Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
will buy the commodities brokerage business of Staley Continental
Inc. for an undisclosed amount, the companies said Tuesday.
   The sale of Staley Commodities International Inc. marks the
second divestment of a major Staley asset since early June, when
London-based sugar refiner Tate & Lyle PLC completed its $1.5
billion acquisition of the Rolling Meadows, Ill.-based company.
   Tate & Lyle said when it set out to buy Staley that it would
keep only Staley's corn syrup refining business, the second-largest
such operation in the nation. Tate & Lyle sold Staley's
food-service business to Sysco Corp. for $700 million in June.
   Staley established Staley Commodities in 1976 to handle its own
commodity brokerage requirements. The brokerage has since grown to
become a member of the Chicago Board of Trade with 26 seats on
various commodity exchanges.
   The sale agreement calls for New York-based Drexel to transact,
for at least two years, the agricultural hedging operations
previously handled by Staley Commodities.
   Staley also agreed to drop a 1987 lawsuit alleging that Drexel
had tried to ``extort'' Staley's management into a takeover and had
manipulated Staley's stock to thwart a stock offering.
   Drexel had denied the allegations.
   Drexel officials said in a statement that the acquisition of
Staley Commodities was an important addition to Drexel's commercial
grain futures brokerage business, one of the country's largest.
   Staley Commodities account executives will be invited to join
Drexel, the companies said.
</TEXT>
