<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Rogers-Sale     08-09 0220</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rogers-Sale,0230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rogers Sells U.S. Cable TV Business To Houston Industries</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Dollar figures are U.S.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TORONTO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rogers Communications Inc. has agreed to sell its
U.S. cable television business to a subsidiary of Texas-based
Houston Industries for $1.3 billion, the companies announced
Tuesday.
   The sale to KBL Cable still must be approved by Houston's board
of directors and U.S. regulatory agencies.
   The Toronto-based Rogers announced its intention to sell its
U.S. cable business in April, to give the company an opportunity to
reduce its debt of almost $987 million.
   Rogers has roughly 525,000 subscribers in the United States.
   Ironically, U.S. interest in Rogers was at the heart of the
decision to sell.
   The number of U.S. shareholders exceeded the Canadian
government's guidelines on foreign ownership of cable operators. In
a series of stock buybacks designed to reduce that foreign
ownership, Rogers spent roughly $350 million, incurring a lot of
debt in the process.
   Houston Industries, a utility holding company serving about 1.3
million customers in the Houston area, has a 50 percent interest in
Paragon Communications, which operates U.S. cable systems with more
than 670,000 subscribers in Texas, California and several other
states.
   Rogers has 1.5 million cable subscribers in Canada, owns Toronto
television station CFMT-TV and is the dominant shareholder in the
Canadian Home Shopping Network.
</TEXT>
