<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Farmers-Batus     08-09 0271</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Farmers-Batus,0281</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Batus Sweetens Offer For Farmers Group To $72 A Share From $63</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Batus Inc., struggling to win regulatory
approval for a hostile takeover of Farmers Group Inc., sweetened
its buyout offer Tuesday to more than $4.9 billion from $4.5
billion in an apparent attempt to win a friendly agreement.
   Farmers, a major insurance holding company, stated late Tuesday
that its board would give ``careful consideration'' to the latest
offer.
   Batus raised its offer to $72 cash a share for Farmers' 68.4
million common shares outstanding from the previous $63 a share
bid, and conditioned the sweetened offer on the negotiation of a
definitive merger agreement by Aug. 19.
   Farmers stock rose 12{ cents to $57.75 a share Tuesday on the
New York Stock Exchange. The sweetened offer was disclosed hours
after the market closed.
   Farmers has resisted the overtures by Batus, the U.S. arm of
British conglomerate BAT Industries PLC, since its initial $60 a
share, or $4.2 billion, buyout offer in January.
   Batus also has been attempting to win approval of the hostile
takeover by the insurance commissioners of the nine states in which
Farmers does business, with mixed success.
   Farmers noted three of the states _ Oregon, Idaho and Washington
_ have rejected the takeover due to issues unrelated to the price
offered by Batus. California also has rejected the proposal, but
that decision recently was overturned by a state court. Farmers is
appealing the reversal.
   Batus, which is based in Louisville, Ky., owns operations that
include Brown & Williamson Tobacco Corp. and several retailers, led
by New York's Saks Fifth Avenue.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
